FLASHCARDS.push(
  // ── Maths ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-1-1",islandId:"island-1",front:"What does BODMAS stand for, and in what order do you calculate?",
   back:"Brackets, Order (powers/roots), Division, Multiplication, Addition, Subtraction.\n\nAlways work through in this order. Example:\n3 + 4 × 2 = 3 + 8 = 11 (NOT 7 × 2 = 14 ❌)",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-1-2",islandId:"island-1",front:"Round 4,732 to the nearest hundred.",
   back:"4,700\n\nLook at the tens digit (3). Since 3 < 5, round DOWN — the hundreds digit stays as 7 and everything after becomes 0.\n\nRule: digit < 5 → round down. digit ≥ 5 → round up.",difficulty:1,category:"calculation"},
  {id:"card-1-3",islandId:"island-1",front:"Put in order from smallest to largest:\n−2, 5, −7, 0, 3",
   back:"−7, −2, 0, 3, 5\n\nOn a number line, numbers to the LEFT are smaller. The more negative a number, the smaller it is.\n\n−7 < −2 < 0 < 3 < 5",difficulty:1,category:"application"},

  {id:"card-2-1",islandId:"island-2",front:"How do you convert a fraction to a decimal?",
   back:"Divide the numerator by the denominator.\n\nExamples:\n• 3/4 = 3 ÷ 4 = 0.75\n• 1/5 = 1 ÷ 5 = 0.2\n• 7/10 = 0.7\n\nCommon ones to memorise: 1/2=0.5, 1/4=0.25, 1/8=0.125",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-2-2",islandId:"island-2",front:"What is 25% of 80?",
   back:"20\n\nMethod 1: 25% = ¼, so 80 ÷ 4 = 20\nMethod 2: 10% of 80 = 8, so 25% = 2½ × 8 = 20\nMethod 3: 80 × 0.25 = 20\n\nTop tip: 25% always means 'divide by 4'.",difficulty:1,category:"calculation"},
  {id:"card-2-3",islandId:"island-2",front:"Which is largest: 3/5, 0.65, 58%, 0.6?\nPut all four in order smallest → largest.",
   back:"58%, 0.6, 3/5, 0.65\n\nConvert all to decimals:\n• 3/5 = 0.60\n• 0.65 = 0.65\n• 58% = 0.58\n• 0.6 = 0.60\n\nOrder: 0.58 < 0.60 = 0.60 < 0.65\n\nNote: 3/5 and 0.6 are equal!",difficulty:2,category:"application"},

  {id:"card-3-1",islandId:"island-3",front:"What is the value of 3x + 5 when x = 4?",
   back:"17\n\nSubstitution: replace every x with 4.\n3(4) + 5 = 12 + 5 = 17\n\nTop tip: always put brackets around the substituted number to avoid mistakes.",difficulty:1,category:"calculation"},
  {id:"card-3-2",islandId:"island-3",front:"Find the nth term of the sequence:\n3, 5, 7, 9, 11 …",
   back:"nth term = 2n + 1\n\nThe sequence goes up by 2 each time → coefficient of n is 2.\nWhen n=1: 2(1)+1 = 3 ✓\nWhen n=3: 2(3)+1 = 7 ✓\n\nGeneral method: nth term = (common difference)n + (first term − common difference)",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-3-3",islandId:"island-3",front:"Solve: 4x − 3 = 13",
   back:"x = 4\n\nStep 1: Add 3 to both sides → 4x = 16\nStep 2: Divide both sides by 4 → x = 4\nCheck: 4(4) − 3 = 16 − 3 = 13 ✓\n\nAlways check your answer by substituting back in.",difficulty:2,category:"calculation"},

  {id:"card-4-1",islandId:"island-4",front:"What are the properties of a parallelogram?",
   back:"• 2 pairs of parallel sides\n• Opposite sides are equal in length\n• Opposite angles are equal\n• Diagonals bisect each other (but are NOT equal)\n\nNot the same as a rectangle — parallelograms do not have right angles (unless it is a rectangle!).",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-4-2",islandId:"island-4",front:"Calculate the area of a triangle:\nbase = 10 cm, height = 6 cm",
   back:"30 cm²\n\nArea of triangle = ½ × base × height\n= ½ × 10 × 6 = 30 cm²\n\n⚠️ Always use the PERPENDICULAR height (the vertical one), not the slant side.",difficulty:1,category:"calculation"},
  {id:"card-4-3",islandId:"island-4",front:"What do angles in a triangle add up to?\nWhat about angles in a quadrilateral?",
   back:"Triangle = 180°\nQuadrilateral = 360°\n\nWhy? Any quadrilateral can be split into 2 triangles:\n2 × 180° = 360°\n\nThis works for ALL triangles and ALL quadrilaterals, even irregular ones.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},

  {id:"card-5-1",islandId:"island-5",front:"What is the difference between mean, median and mode?",
   back:"Mean = total sum ÷ number of values (the 'average')\nMedian = the MIDDLE value when ordered\nMode = the MOST FREQUENT value\nRange = highest − lowest (measures spread)\n\nMemory tip: Mode = Most common.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-5-2",islandId:"island-5",front:"Find the median of:\n3, 8, 1, 5, 7, 2, 9",
   back:"Median = 5\n\nStep 1: Order the values: 1, 2, 3, 5, 7, 8, 9\nStep 2: Find the middle — there are 7 values, so the 4th is the median.\n\n1, 2, 3, [5], 7, 8, 9\n\nIf there's an even number of values, find the mean of the two middle numbers.",difficulty:2,category:"calculation"},
  {id:"card-5-3",islandId:"island-5",front:"Find the range of:\n12, 7, 3, 19, 5",
   back:"Range = 16\n\nRange = highest value − lowest value\n= 19 − 3 = 16\n\nThe range tells us how spread out the data is. A large range means the data is very spread out.",difficulty:1,category:"calculation"},

  // ── English ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-6-1",islandId:"island-6",front:"What is inference? Give an example.",
   back:"Inference = using clues in a text to work out something that isn't directly stated.\n\nExample: The text says 'She slammed the door.' We INFER she is angry — it doesn't say she is angry, but we can work it out from the clue.\n\nKey phrase: 'This suggests that…'",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-6-2",islandId:"island-6",front:"What is the difference between a fact and an opinion?",
   back:"Fact = can be proven true or false.\n'London is the capital of England.' ✓\n\nOpinion = a personal view or belief, not provable.\n'London is the best city.' — someone might disagree!\n\nLook for opinion words: I think, I believe, best, should, worst, in my view.",difficulty:1,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-6-3",islandId:"island-6",front:"What does it mean to annotate a text, and why is it useful?",
   back:"Annotating = adding notes to a text as you read.\n\nHow to annotate:\n• Underline key words or phrases\n• Circle literary devices\n• Write short comments in the margin ('This shows…')\n\nWhy useful: helps you find evidence quickly and understand the text more deeply.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},

  {id:"card-7-1",islandId:"island-7",front:"What is the 'story mountain' structure?",
   back:"A 5-stage story structure:\n1. Opening — introduce characters and setting\n2. Build-up — develop the story, create tension\n3. Climax — the main event or turning point (most exciting!)\n4. Resolution — the problem is solved\n5. Ending — show how things are different after\n\nThis gives your writing a clear, satisfying shape.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-7-2",islandId:"island-7",front:"Name 3 techniques for a powerful story opening.",
   back:"1. In medias res (start in the action):\n   'The dragon roared as she tumbled from the cliff.'\n\n2. Atmospheric description:\n   'The fog hung low over the silent village.'\n\n3. Intriguing question:\n   'Have you ever been truly lost?'\n\n❌ Avoid: 'My name is…' or 'Once upon a time…'",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-7-3",islandId:"island-7",front:"What is 'show, don't tell'? Give an example.",
   back:"Instead of TELLING the reader how a character feels, SHOW it through actions, dialogue, and detail.\n\n❌ TELL: 'He was scared.'\n✅ SHOW: 'His hands trembled. He pressed himself against the wall, breath coming in short gasps.'\n\nThe reader works out the emotion — it's more powerful and engaging.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  {id:"card-8-1",islandId:"island-8",front:"What is the difference between a phrase and a clause?",
   back:"Clause = a group of words with a verb; it can stand as a sentence.\n'She ran quickly.' ← main clause\n\nPhrase = a group of words WITHOUT a complete verb; cannot stand alone.\n'Through the dark forest' ← phrase (no verb)\n\nA sentence must contain at least one main clause.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-8-2",islandId:"island-8",front:"When do you use a colon? When do you use a semicolon?",
   back:"Colon (:) — introduces a list or an explanation:\n'She needed three things: courage, a map, and time.'\n\nSemicolon (;) — joins two related main clauses (both must be complete sentences):\n'It was late; she needed to sleep.'\n\nThink: colon = 'namely…', semicolon = 'and furthermore…'",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-8-3",islandId:"island-8",front:"Give 3 uses of the apostrophe with examples.",
   back:"1. Contraction (missing letters):\n   don't = do not | it's = it is\n\n2. Singular possession:\n   the dog's lead (one dog)\n\n3. Plural possession (plural ends in s):\n   the dogs' leads (more than one dog)\n\n⚠️ NEVER use an apostrophe for a simple plural: dogs NOT dog's",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},

  {id:"card-9-1",islandId:"island-9",front:"What is the difference between a simile and a metaphor?",
   back:"Simile: compares using 'like' or 'as'\n'The moon was LIKE a silver coin.'\n\nMetaphor: directly says one thing IS another\n'The moon WAS a silver coin.'\n\nMetaphors are more powerful — the comparison is immediate and direct, with no softening 'like'.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-9-2",islandId:"island-9",front:"What is alliteration and why do writers use it?",
   back:"Alliteration = the repetition of the same consonant sound at the start of nearby words.\n\n'Peter Piper picked a peck of pickled peppers.'\n'The cold, cruel cliffs crashed into the sea.'\n\nEffects:\n• Creates rhythm and musicality\n• Makes phrases memorable\n• Can create mood (hard sounds = danger; soft sounds = calm)",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-9-3",islandId:"island-9",front:"What is personification? Give two examples.",
   back:"Personification = giving human qualities, feelings or actions to a non-human thing.\n\n'The wind WHISPERED through the trees.' (wind can't whisper)\n'The sun SMILED down on us.' (sun can't smile)\n\nEffect: creates vivid imagery, makes descriptions more emotional and atmospheric.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},

  {id:"card-10-1",islandId:"island-10",front:"Name 4 techniques for confident public speaking.",
   back:"1. Make eye contact with your audience (not just your notes)\n2. Speak clearly and not too fast — use pauses for effect\n3. Project your voice so everyone can hear\n4. Vary your tone to keep the audience engaged\n\nAlso: know your material, use natural gestures, stand tall.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-10-2",islandId:"island-10",front:"What is the difference between formal and informal language?",
   back:"Formal: used in speeches, essays, presentations.\n• No slang or contractions\n• Full, complete sentences\n• Standard grammar\nExample: 'Good afternoon. I would like to discuss…'\n\nInformal: used with friends, casual writing.\n• Contractions, slang ok\nExample: 'Hey! So basically…'\n\nAlways match your language to your AUDIENCE and PURPOSE.",difficulty:1,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-10-3",islandId:"island-10",front:"What does PEEL stand for and how do you use it?",
   back:"P — Point: Make your main argument clearly.\nE — Evidence: Provide a quote or example.\nE — Explanation: Explain how the evidence supports your point.\nL — Link: Connect back to the question or your overall argument.\n\nUse PEEL in essays AND in spoken debate to structure your ideas clearly.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},

  // ── Science ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-11-1",islandId:"island-11",front:"What does MRS GREN stand for?",
   back:"The 7 life processes that ALL living things must carry out:\n\nM — Movement\nR — Respiration\nS — Sensitivity\nG — Growth\nR — Reproduction\nE — Excretion\nN — Nutrition\n\nIf something doesn't do ALL 7, it is NOT alive.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-11-2",islandId:"island-11",image:"cell-comparison",front:"Name 3 things plant cells have that animal cells don't.",
   back:"1. Cell wall — made of cellulose; gives rigid support\n2. Chloroplasts — contain chlorophyll; carry out photosynthesis\n3. Large permanent vacuole — stores water and maintains cell pressure\n\nBoth plant AND animal cells have:\nnucleus, cell membrane, cytoplasm, mitochondria",difficulty:1,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-11-3",islandId:"island-11",image:"cell-organisation",front:"What is the order of organisation from cell to organism?",
   back:"Cell → Tissue → Organ → Organ System → Organism\n\nExample:\nHeart muscle cell → Muscle tissue → Heart → Circulatory system → Human being\n\nEach level is more complex than the last. Cells are the basic building blocks of all living things.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},

  {id:"card-12-1",islandId:"island-12",image:"food-chain",front:"What is the difference between a producer and a consumer?",
   back:"Producer = makes its own food through photosynthesis (plants, algae)\n→ Always at the START of a food chain\n\nPrimary consumer = eats producers (herbivores)\nSecondary consumer = eats primary consumers\nTertiary consumer = eats secondary consumers\n\nEnergy flows from producers upwards through the chain.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-12-2",islandId:"island-12",front:"What does an arrow in a food chain represent?\nWhy do students often get this wrong?",
   back:"The arrow shows the direction of ENERGY TRANSFER.\n\n'Grass → Rabbit → Fox'\nmeans: energy passes FROM grass TO rabbit TO fox.\n\n❌ Common mistake: students draw the arrow to point at what something eats (as if meaning 'eats'). \n\nRemember: the arrow points FROM what is eaten TO what eats it.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-12-3",islandId:"island-12",front:"What is an adaptation? Give 2 examples.",
   back:"An adaptation is an inherited feature that helps an organism survive in its environment.\n\nExamples:\n1. Polar bear's thick white fur → insulation from cold + camouflage in snow\n2. Cactus's waxy skin and spines → reduces water loss + protection from animals\n\nAdaptations are passed from parents to offspring through genes.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},

  {id:"card-13-1",islandId:"island-13",image:"particle-states",front:"Describe the arrangement and movement of particles in a solid, liquid and gas.",
   back:"Solid: close together in a fixed, regular pattern — vibrate in place only\nLiquid: close together but can slide past each other — random arrangement\nGas: far apart, move quickly and randomly in all directions\n\nHeating gives particles more energy → they move more → substance can change state.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-13-2",islandId:"island-13",image:"changes-of-state",front:"What is the difference between melting and dissolving?",
   back:"Melting = solid changes to liquid due to heat.\n• Example: ice → water\n• Physical change — no new substance is made\n• Reversible: cool it down and it freezes again\n\nDissolving = solid mixes into liquid to form a solution.\n• Example: salt + water → salt water\n• The salt hasn't disappeared — it's just spread out (still there!)\n• Reversible: evaporate the water to get the salt back",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-13-3",islandId:"island-13",front:"What is the particle model and what does it explain?",
   back:"The particle model: all matter is made of tiny particles in constant motion.\n\nIt explains:\n• Why solids keep their shape (fixed particle positions)\n• Why gases fill any container (particles move freely)\n• Why substances expand when heated (particles move faster, spread out)\n• Diffusion (particles spread from high to low concentration)\n\nIt's a model — a simplified idea to help explain real-world observations.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  {id:"card-14-1",islandId:"island-14",front:"What is the difference between mass and weight?",
   back:"Mass = amount of matter in an object. Measured in kg. NEVER changes, wherever you are.\n\nWeight = the force of gravity pulling on an object. Measured in Newtons (N).\nW = m × g (g = 10 N/kg on Earth; g = 1.6 N/kg on the Moon)\n\nYou would weigh less on the Moon but your mass stays the same!",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-14-2",islandId:"island-14",image:"force-arrows",front:"What happens when forces are balanced vs unbalanced?",
   back:"Balanced forces (net force = 0):\n→ Object stays STILL, or moves at CONSTANT SPEED\nExample: book on a table (weight down = reaction force up)\n\nUnbalanced forces (net force ≠ 0):\n→ Object SPEEDS UP, SLOWS DOWN, or CHANGES DIRECTION\nExample: a kicked football (unbalanced → accelerates)\n\nNewton's First Law: an object keeps doing what it's doing unless acted on by an unbalanced force.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-14-3",islandId:"island-14",front:"What is friction? Is it always a bad thing?",
   back:"Friction is a force that opposes motion between two surfaces in contact.\n\nUseful friction:\n• Grip on your shoes lets you walk\n• Car brakes slow you down safely\n• Rubbing hands together makes heat\n\nUnhelpful friction:\n• Slows down machines (wastes energy)\n• Wears down tyres and brake pads\n\nReduced by: smooth surfaces, lubrication (oil, grease), ball bearings.",difficulty:1,category:"concept"},

  {id:"card-15-1",islandId:"island-15",front:"How does light travel, and what does this explain?",
   back:"Light travels in STRAIGHT LINES (rectilinear propagation) at 300,000 km/s.\n\nThis explains:\n1. Shadows — objects block straight-line light\n2. Why you can't see around corners\n3. How periscopes work (mirrors redirect the straight line)\n\nLight is the fastest thing in the universe.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-15-2",islandId:"island-15",image:"law-of-reflection",front:"State the law of reflection.",
   back:"Angle of incidence = Angle of reflection\n\nBoth angles are measured from the NORMAL — an imaginary line at 90° to the mirror surface.\n\nApplications:\n• Plane mirrors\n• Periscopes\n• Cat's eyes on roads\n• CCTV mirrors in shops\n\nThe image in a flat mirror is the same size, virtual, and laterally inverted (flipped).",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-15-3",islandId:"island-15",front:"How is sound different from light?",
   back:"Sound:\n• Needs a medium (particles to vibrate through)\n• Travels through solids, liquids, gases — NOT through space\n• Speed: ~340 m/s in air\n\nLight:\n• Does NOT need a medium — travels through a vacuum (space)\n• Speed: 300,000 km/s (almost 1 million times faster than sound!)\n\nThis is why you see lightning BEFORE you hear thunder.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── History ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-16-1",islandId:"island-16",front:"Who were the main claimants to the English throne in 1066?",
   back:"1. Harold Godwinson (Earl of Wessex) — crowned king Jan 1066; most powerful English noble\n2. William, Duke of Normandy — claimed Edward the Confessor had promised him the crown\n3. Harald Hardrada (Norway) — claimed through Scandinavian links\n4. Edgar Atheling — last Anglo-Saxon royal heir; too young and lacked support\n\nHarold Godwinson was crowned first but faced two invasions in 1066.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-16-2",islandId:"island-16",front:"What happened at the Battle of Hastings, 14 October 1066?",
   back:"Harold's exhausted army took position on Senlac Hill.\nThe Normans attacked uphill — Harold's shield wall held at first.\n\nTurning point: Normans faked a retreat — English broke formation to chase them → shield wall broken.\nHarold was killed (possibly by an arrow to the eye).\nWilliam was crowned King of England on Christmas Day 1066.\n\nThe Norman Conquest transformed England's language, culture, and ruling class.",difficulty:1,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-16-3",islandId:"island-16",front:"What was the Domesday Book and why did William order it?",
   back:"Completed 1086 — a detailed survey of all land and property in England.\n\nWilliam ordered it to:\n1. Find out exactly who owned what land\n2. Calculate how much tax could be collected\n3. Demonstrate that he was the rightful ruler of everything in England\n\nEach county listed: who owned the land, its value, how many people, animals and resources.\nIt is one of the most important documents in English history.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-16-4",islandId:"island-16",front:"What was the Harrying of the North (1069–70)? Why is it significant?",
   back:"After repeated rebellions in northern England, William ordered the SYSTEMATIC DESTRUCTION of the region.\n\nWhat happened:\n• Villages, crops and livestock burned\n• Food stores destroyed to prevent any further resistance\n• Thousands died of starvation over the following years\n• Land left so devastated it was still recorded as 'waste' in the Domesday Book 16 years later\n\nSignificance:\n• Shows the BRUTAL side of Norman control\n• Key evidence used by historians who view William as a tyrant\n• Ensured no further major northern rebellion",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-16-5",islandId:"island-16",front:"How did the Norman Conquest change the English language?",
   back:"The Normans spoke FRENCH — and it became the language of the ruling class, law and government.\n\nExamples of French words that entered English:\n• Government, parliament, justice, castle, prison\n• Beef (boeuf), pork (porc), mutton (mouton) — the animals kept their English names (cow, pig, sheep)\n\nLatin became the language of the Church and education.\nOrdinary people continued speaking English.\n\nResult: modern English is a BLEND of Anglo-Saxon (Germanic) and Norman French — one of the most lasting impacts of 1066.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  {id:"card-17-1",islandId:"island-17",front:"Explain the feudal system — who was at each level?",
   back:"A pyramid of power (top → bottom):\n\n👑 King — owned ALL land; gave it to lords for loyalty and military service\n🏰 Lords/Barons/Church — managed large estates; gave land to knights\n⚔️ Knights — provided military service; protected the manor\n👨‍🌾 Peasants/Serfs — worked the land in exchange for protection and a small plot\n\nEveryone owed a duty to those above them. No one owned land freely — it was always held 'from' someone.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-17-2",islandId:"island-17",front:"Why were castles important in Norman England?",
   back:"Castles served as centres of military and political power.\n\nPurposes:\n1. Defence — protect Norman rulers from Anglo-Saxon rebellions\n2. Control — intimidate and control the local population\n3. Administration — lords ran their estates from here\n4. Symbol of power — showed who was in charge\n\nEarly castles: motte-and-bailey (wood, quick to build). Later: stone keeps (stronger, permanent).",difficulty:1,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-17-3",islandId:"island-17",front:"What role did the Catholic Church play in medieval life?",
   back:"The Church was the most powerful institution in medieval Europe.\n\nIt:\n• Ran education (monasteries ran the only schools)\n• Collected tithes (10% of everyone's income — compulsory)\n• Ran hospitals and cared for the poor\n• Controlled marriage, funerals, moral life\n• Could excommunicate kings (cut them off from God)\n\nMost people believed completely in heaven and hell — the Church controlled access to both.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-17-4",islandId:"island-17",front:"Describe how castles evolved from motte-and-bailey to concentric castles.",
   back:"Three stages of castle evolution:\n\n1. MOTTE-AND-BAILEY (1066+):\n• Wooden tower on a raised mound (motte) + enclosed yard (bailey)\n• Quick and cheap to build — 500+ built by 1086\n• Weakness: wood burns easily\n\n2. STONE KEEPS (late 11th–12th century):\n• Replaced wood with stone walls and towers (e.g. Tower of London)\n• Much stronger — resistant to fire and siege\n• Expensive and slow to build\n\n3. CONCENTRIC CASTLES (13th century):\n• Multiple rings of walls — castle within a castle (e.g. Caernarfon)\n• Attackers had to breach several walls\n• Peak of medieval military engineering",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-17-5",islandId:"island-17",front:"What was the open field system? How did medieval farming work?",
   back:"Most medieval villages used THREE large open fields:\n• Field 1: wheat\n• Field 2: barley or oats\n• Field 3: FALLOW (resting — to recover soil fertility)\n• Fields rotated each year\n\nEach peasant farmed several narrow STRIPS scattered across the fields (to share good and bad land fairly).\n\nFarming was COMMUNAL:\n• Shared ploughs and oxen (too expensive for one family)\n• Worked together at harvest time\n• Common land for grazing animals\n\nThis system lasted until the Enclosure Acts (18th–19th century) replaced it with private fields.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},

  {id:"card-18-1",islandId:"island-18",front:"What was the Black Death and how did it reach England?",
   back:"The Black Death was a devastating plague that killed ~1/3 of Europe's population (1347–1351).\n\nCause: bacterium Yersinia pestis (not known at the time)\nSpread by: fleas on black rats → bit humans → bubonic plague. Also spread through the air (pneumonic plague).\n\nRoute: Central Asia → trade ships to Sicily (1347) → swept across Europe → reached England via trade ships in 1348, landing in Dorset.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-18-2",islandId:"island-18",front:"What were the symptoms of the Black Death? What did medieval people think caused it?",
   back:"Symptoms:\n• Buboes — large, painful swellings in armpit, groin, neck\n• Black skin patches (internal bleeding → 'Black Death')\n• Fever, vomiting blood\n• Most died within 1–5 days\n\nMedieval explanations:\n• Punishment from God (sin)\n• 'Bad air' (miasma theory)\n• Planets aligned wrongly\n• Wrongly blamed Jewish communities\n\nNobody knew it was caused by bacteria — germ theory wasn't developed until the 19th century.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-18-3",islandId:"island-18",front:"What were the long-term effects of the Black Death on medieval society?",
   back:"1. Labour shortage → surviving peasants could DEMAND higher wages and better conditions\n2. Weakened the feudal system — peasants had more bargaining power\n3. Led to the Peasants' Revolt (1381) — uprising against continued serfdom\n4. Loss of faith in the Church (prayers hadn't stopped the plague)\n5. Advances in medicine — people tried harder to understand disease\n\nThe Black Death helped bring the medieval feudal system to an end.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-18-4",islandId:"island-18",front:"Who were the flagellants? Why were Jewish communities persecuted during the Black Death?",
   back:"FLAGELLANTS:\n• Groups who publicly whipped themselves as penance\n• Believed self-punishment would persuade God to end the plague\n• Travelled town to town, attracting crowds\n• Eventually condemned by the Pope\n\nJEWISH PERSECUTION:\n• Jewish communities were falsely accused of poisoning wells\n• Thousands attacked and killed, especially in Germany, France and Spain\n• Driven by existing prejudice + desperate need for someone to blame\n• An early and horrific example of SCAPEGOATING during a crisis\n\nBoth responses show how fear and panic can lead to extreme behaviour.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-18-5",islandId:"island-18",front:"How did the Black Death lead directly to the Peasants' Revolt of 1381?",
   back:"Chain of causation:\n\n1. Black Death (1348–49) kills ~1/3 of population → LABOUR SHORTAGE\n2. Surviving peasants demand higher wages — they have bargaining power\n3. Government passes STATUTE OF LABOURERS (1351) — tries to freeze wages at pre-plague levels\n4. Peasants deeply resent this — they're told they can't move or ask for more pay\n5. A POLL TAX is introduced (1380) — every adult must pay the same flat rate regardless of wealth\n6. This is the final provocation → PEASANTS' REVOLT (1381)\n7. Led by Wat Tyler and John Ball; marched on London\n\nThe revolt was defeated but serfdom gradually died out over the next century.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},

  {id:"card-19-1",islandId:"island-19",front:"Why did the barons rebel against King John in 1215?",
   back:"King John was deeply unpopular because he:\n1. Lost English lands in France (Normandy lost, 1204)\n2. Taxed barons very heavily to pay for failed wars\n3. Ignored traditional rights — acted as if above the law\n4. Quarrelled with Pope Innocent III (England placed under interdict — no church services)\n\nIn 1215, angry barons marched on London. John had to negotiate — he signed the Magna Carta at Runnymede.",difficulty:1,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-19-2",islandId:"island-19",front:"What was the Magna Carta (1215) and why is it historically significant?",
   back:"Magna Carta = 'Great Charter' — signed by King John under pressure from barons.\n\nKey principles:\n• No one (including the king) is above the law\n• No imprisonment without fair trial (habeas corpus)\n• Taxes require agreement of the barons\n\nSignificance:\nFirst time a king was made subject to the rule of law. Foundation of modern constitutional government and democracy. Influenced the US Constitution and human rights law worldwide.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-19-3",islandId:"island-19",front:"How did Parliament begin to develop in medieval England?",
   back:"1215 — Magna Carta: barons gain rights; king must consult them\n1258 — Provisions of Oxford: Henry III forced to consult a council of barons\n1265 — Simon de Montfort calls Parliament: includes knights AND town representatives (not just barons) for the first time\n1295 — Edward I's 'Model Parliament': wider representation becomes established\n\nGradually, Parliament gained the power to approve taxes and have a say in governing.\nThis is the beginning of representative democracy in England.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-19-4",islandId:"island-19",front:"Why is Magna Carta still important today? Name two documents it influenced.",
   back:"Magna Carta established the principle that NO ONE IS ABOVE THE LAW — including rulers.\n\nKey principles still used today:\n• Habeas corpus — cannot be imprisoned without fair trial\n• Trial by jury — judged by your peers\n• Rule of law — the law applies equally to everyone\n\nDocuments influenced:\n1. US Constitution and Bill of Rights (1787/1791)\n2. Universal Declaration of Human Rights (1948)\n\nAlso influenced: English Bill of Rights (1689), many national constitutions worldwide.\n\nCopies displayed in the British Library and US National Archives.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},

  // ── Geography ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-20-1",islandId:"island-20",image:"grid-reference",front:"How do you read a 4-figure grid reference?",
   back:"Go along the corridor (eastings) FIRST, then up the stairs (northings).\n\nMemory aid: 'Along the corridor and up the stairs.'\n\nExample: Grid reference 2534\n→ Easting: 25 (go right to line 25)\n→ Northing: 34 (go up to line 34)\nThe grid reference describes the SQUARE to the top-right of where the lines meet.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-20-2",islandId:"island-20",image:"contour-cross-section",front:"What do contour lines show on a map?",
   back:"Contour lines join points of EQUAL HEIGHT above sea level.\n\nClose together = steep slope\nFar apart = gentle slope\nCircle of contours = hill or summit\nContours never cross each other\n\nThe number on each line shows height in metres.\n\nUse them to identify: valleys, ridges, cliff faces, gentle plains.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-20-3",islandId:"island-20",front:"What is the difference between a large scale and small scale map?",
   back:"Large scale (e.g. 1:25,000):\n• Shows a SMALL area in LOTS of detail\n• Used for: walking maps, town plans, OS Explorer\n• 1 cm = 250 m\n\nSmall scale (e.g. 1:1,000,000):\n• Shows a LARGE area with LITTLE detail\n• Used for: atlas maps, road maps of whole countries\n• 1 cm = 10 km\n\nThink: large scale = zoom in = more detail.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-20-4",islandId:"island-20",front:"What is GIS and why is it useful to geographers?",
   back:"GIS = Geographical Information Systems\n\nComputer software that stores, analyses and displays LAYERS of geographical data on a digital map.\n\nExamples of layers:\n• Population density\n• Flood risk zones\n• Land use (farms, housing, forests)\n• Transport networks\n\nWhy useful: you can overlay multiple datasets to spot patterns — e.g. 'Which areas have high flood risk AND high population density?'\n\nUsed by councils, emergency services, environmental agencies and businesses.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-20-5",islandId:"island-20",front:"How do you draw a cross-section from a contour map?",
   back:"Step-by-step:\n1. Draw a straight line between your two points on the map\n2. Place the edge of a piece of paper along the line\n3. Mark where each contour line crosses — write the HEIGHT at each mark\n4. Transfer these marks to graph paper with height on the y-axis\n5. Plot each height and join the dots with a smooth curve\n\nThe result shows you the SHAPE OF THE LAND (profile) between the two points — hills, valleys, flat sections.\n\nAlways label the axes: distance (m) on x-axis, height (m) on y-axis.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},

  {id:"card-21-1",islandId:"island-21",front:"What is the difference between weather and climate?",
   back:"Weather = the short-term, day-to-day conditions of the atmosphere.\n(temperature, rain, wind, sunshine today or this week)\n\nClimate = the AVERAGE weather conditions over a LONG period (30+ years) for a particular place.\n\n'Climate is what you expect; weather is what you get.'\n\nThe UK has a temperate maritime climate — mild and wet all year.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-21-2",islandId:"island-21",front:"Name 4 instruments used to measure weather and what each one measures.",
   back:"1. Thermometer — temperature (°C)\n2. Rain gauge — precipitation (mm)\n3. Anemometer — wind speed (km/h)\n4. Barometer — air pressure (millibars)\n\nAlso:\n• Wind vane — wind direction\n• Hygrometer — humidity (moisture in the air)\n• Sunshine recorder — hours of sunshine\n\nWeather stations combine all these to produce accurate forecasts.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-21-3",islandId:"island-21",image:"relief-rainfall",front:"Why does the UK have a mild, wet climate?",
   back:"Four main reasons:\n\n1. Prevailing south-westerly winds bring warm, moist air from the Atlantic Ocean\n2. North Atlantic Drift (warm ocean current) keeps UK winters milder than expected for our latitude\n3. Island location — the surrounding sea moderates temperatures (cool summers, mild winters)\n4. Relief rainfall — moist air rises over hills, cools, and falls as rain → western UK is wetter\n\nResult: the UK is rarely extremely hot or cold, and receives rain throughout the year.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-21-4",islandId:"island-21",image:"greenhouse-effect",front:"How has climate changed since the Ice Age? Give three examples of evidence.",
   back:"The last Ice Age ended ~11,700 years ago. Since then:\n• Medieval Warm Period (~900–1300 AD) — vineyards grew in England\n• Little Ice Age (~1300–1850 AD) — the Thames froze; frost fairs held\n• Current warming — faster than any natural change on record\n\nEvidence:\n1. Ice cores — trapped air bubbles show past CO₂ and temperature\n2. Tree rings — wider rings = warmer/wetter growing seasons\n3. Historical records — harvest dates, paintings of frozen rivers, diaries\n\nAlso: fossils, pollen analysis, ocean sediment cores.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-21-5",islandId:"island-21",front:"What is a microclimate? Give two examples.",
   back:"A microclimate is a small area where climate conditions differ from the surrounding region.\n\nExamples:\n1. A south-facing slope is WARMER than a north-facing slope (receives more direct sunlight)\n2. A city centre is WARMER than surrounding countryside (urban heat island effect — dark surfaces absorb heat, buildings trap warmth, less vegetation)\n\nOther factors creating microclimates:\n• Shelter from wind (e.g. behind a wall)\n• Proximity to water (moderates temperature)\n• Surface type (tarmac absorbs more heat than grass)",difficulty:2,category:"application"},

  {id:"card-22-1",islandId:"island-22",image:"river-long-profile",front:"Name 3 processes of river erosion and explain each.",
   back:"1. Hydraulic action — the sheer force of moving water breaks away rock from banks and bed\n2. Abrasion — sediment (stones) carried by the river scrapes and wears away the channel (like sandpaper)\n3. Solution — slightly acidic water dissolves soluble rocks like limestone\n\nErosion is GREATEST in the upper course (fast flow, lots of energy, steep gradient).",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-22-2",islandId:"island-22",image:"meander-formation",front:"How does a meander form?",
   back:"A meander is a bend in a river.\n\nHow it forms:\n1. Water flows FASTER on the OUTSIDE of a bend → more erosion → river cliff forms\n2. Water flows SLOWER on the INSIDE → deposition → slip-off slope builds up\n3. The bend gradually becomes more exaggerated\n4. Eventually the loop is cut off → OXBOW LAKE forms\n\nMeanders are typical of the MIDDLE and LOWER course of a river.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-22-3",islandId:"island-22",front:"What is the difference between erosion and deposition?",
   back:"Erosion = the wearing away and removal of material (rock, soil, sediment) by the river.\n→ Happens when the river has HIGH ENERGY (fast flow, steep gradient)\n→ Most in the upper course\n\nDeposition = when the river drops/deposits the material it's carrying.\n→ Happens when the river SLOWS DOWN and loses energy\n→ Most in the lower course (flat land, wide channel)\n\nDeposition builds floodplains, deltas and beaches.",difficulty:1,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-22-4",islandId:"island-22",image:"drainage-basin",front:"What is a drainage basin? Define: watershed, tributary, confluence, source, mouth.",
   back:"A drainage basin is the area of land drained by a river and its tributaries.\n\nKey terms:\n• Watershed — the ridge of high land forming the boundary of the drainage basin\n• Tributary — a smaller river flowing into the main river\n• Confluence — the point where two rivers meet\n• Source — where a river begins (usually in upland areas)\n• Mouth — where a river meets the sea\n\nAll precipitation within the watershed eventually reaches the main river.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-22-5",islandId:"island-22",front:"Compare hard and soft engineering for flood management. Give one example of each.",
   back:"HARD engineering = man-made structures:\n• Example: Embankments (levees) — raised banks along the river\n• Pros: effective, protects property\n• Cons: expensive, ugly, can worsen flooding downstream\n\nSOFT engineering = working with nature:\n• Example: Afforestation — planting trees to slow runoff\n• Pros: cheap, sustainable, creates habitats\n• Cons: takes years, may not prevent major floods\n\nBest approach: use BOTH together for balance of cost, effectiveness and sustainability.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},

  {id:"card-23-1",islandId:"island-23",front:"What is population density and how is it calculated?",
   back:"Population density = the number of people per square kilometre (km²).\n\nFormula:\nPopulation density = Total population ÷ Area (km²)\n\nExample: 500,000 people in 100 km² = 5,000 people/km² (high density!)\n\nHigh density: cities, fertile plains, mild climates\nLow density: deserts, mountains, arctic regions",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-23-2",islandId:"island-23",front:"Name 3 physical and 3 human factors that influence where people settle.",
   back:"Physical factors (natural):\n1. Flat land — easy to build on\n2. Near a river — fresh water for drinking and farming\n3. Sheltered from harsh weather\n\nHuman factors (man-made):\n4. Near trade routes or roads — easy to transport goods\n5. Employment opportunities nearby\n6. Existing community/services — schools, shops\n\nHistorically: rivers most important. Today: transport links and jobs dominate.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-23-3",islandId:"island-23",front:"What is urbanisation and what causes it?",
   back:"Urbanisation = the process of more people moving to live in urban areas (towns and cities).\n\nCauses:\nPull factors (into cities):\n• More jobs and higher wages\n• Better services (hospitals, schools)\n• Improved transport links\n\nPush factors (out of rural areas):\n• Fewer jobs (mechanisation of farming)\n• Limited services in countryside\n• Lower wages\n\nOver 55% of the world's population now lives in urban areas.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-23-4",islandId:"island-23",image:"population-pyramid",front:"What is a population pyramid and what can its shape tell you?",
   back:"A population pyramid is a bar chart showing age groups (y-axis) and population by sex (males left, females right).\n\nShapes:\n• WIDE BASE, narrow top = high birth rate, low life expectancy → LIC (Stage 2 DTM)\n• EVEN/COLUMN shape = moderate birth and death rates → middle-income country (Stage 3)\n• NARROW BASE, wider top = low birth rate, ageing population → HIC (Stage 4/5 DTM)\n\nUseful for planning: schools (young population), pensions (ageing population), healthcare.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-23-5",islandId:"island-23",image:"dtm-model",front:"Name the 5 stages of the Demographic Transition Model (DTM).",
   back:"Stage 1: HIGH birth rate + HIGH death rate = low, stable population\nStage 2: Birth rate stays high, DEATH RATE FALLS = rapid growth (e.g. some LICs)\nStage 3: BIRTH RATE FALLS, death rate low = growth slows (e.g. Brazil, India)\nStage 4: LOW birth + LOW death = stable, high population (e.g. UK, USA)\nStage 5: Birth rate BELOW death rate = population DECLINE (e.g. Japan, Germany)\n\nKey: death rate falls first (healthcare), then birth rate falls later (education, contraception).",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},

  // ── Maths: Ratio, Proportion & Rates ─────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-24-1",islandId:"island-24",front:"Simplify the ratio 24 : 36.",
   back:"2 : 3\n\nFind the HCF of 24 and 36 = 12.\nDivide both parts by 12: 24÷12 = 2, 36÷12 = 3.\n\nAlways simplify ratios until no common factor remains.\nCheck: 2 and 3 share no common factor ✓",difficulty:1,category:"calculation"},
  {id:"card-24-2",islandId:"island-24",front:"Share £40 in the ratio 3 : 5.",
   back:"£15 and £25\n\nStep 1: Total parts = 3 + 5 = 8\nStep 2: Value of 1 part = £40 ÷ 8 = £5\nStep 3: First share = 3 × £5 = £15\n         Second share = 5 × £5 = £25\n\nCheck: £15 + £25 = £40 ✓",difficulty:2,category:"calculation"},
  {id:"card-24-3",islandId:"island-24",front:"A car travels 120 km in 2 hours. What is its speed?\nWhat is the formula triangle for speed?",
   back:"Speed = 60 km/h\n\nFormula: Speed = Distance ÷ Time\n           Distance = Speed × Time\n           Time = Distance ÷ Speed\n\nMemory aid: the SDT triangle — cover the one you want.\n\n120 ÷ 2 = 60 km/h\n\n⚠️ Always check units match (km and hours, or metres and seconds).",difficulty:2,category:"calculation"},

  // ── English: Shakespeare ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-25-1",islandId:"island-25",front:"Describe the Globe Theatre. How was it different from modern theatres?",
   back:"The Globe (built 1599, London):\n• Open-air, circular wooden theatre\n• 'Groundlings' stood in the yard for 1 penny — no seats, no roof\n• Wealthy audience sat in covered galleries\n• No artificial lighting — plays performed in daylight\n• No female actors — women's roles played by boys\n• Simple staging; audience used imagination\n\nVery different from modern theatres — no scenery, no dimming lights, audience interacted with performers.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-25-2",islandId:"island-25",front:"What is a PEE paragraph and how do you write one?",
   back:"PEE = Point, Evidence, Explanation\n\nP — Make your point: 'Shakespeare presents Puck as mischievous…'\nE — Provide a quote: '…when he says \"Lord, what fools these mortals be!\"'\nE — Explain the effect: 'This suggests Puck views humans with amused contempt, showing his superiority over the mortal characters.'\n\nTip: your Explanation should use language like 'This suggests…', 'This shows…', 'This implies…'",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-25-3",islandId:"island-25",front:"Name two key themes in A Midsummer Night's Dream (or The Tempest) and give one example of each.",
   back:"A Midsummer Night's Dream:\n• Love and confusion — the lovers' relationships are manipulated by the fairies, showing love is irrational\n• Order vs chaos — the fairy world disrupts the human world\n\nThe Tempest:\n• Power and control — Prospero controls the island and its inhabitants\n• Revenge vs forgiveness — Prospero chooses forgiveness over revenge at the end\n\nThemes are the BIG IDEAS the playwright explores through characters and events.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── English: Non-Fiction Writing ──────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-26-1",islandId:"island-26",front:"What are the main non-fiction text types and their purposes?",
   back:"• News article — to inform; 5 Ws (who, what, where, when, why) in first paragraph\n• Speech — to persuade or inspire; uses rhetoric, direct address, rule of three\n• Formal letter — to argue, complain, request; clear structure, formal register\n• Blog — to inform/entertain; personal voice, informal tone\n• Travel writing — to describe and inform; vivid language\n\nAlways identify: PURPOSE (why?) + AUDIENCE (who?) + TONE (how?)",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-26-2",islandId:"island-26",front:"What is the 'rule of three' and why do writers use it?",
   back:"The rule of three = using three connected words, phrases or ideas together.\n\nExamples:\n'Government of the people, BY the people, FOR the people.' (Lincoln)\n'Our school is safe, supportive and successful.'\n\nWhy it works:\n• Three items feel complete and satisfying to the ear\n• Creates rhythm and makes ideas memorable\n• Adds rhetorical power to persuasive writing\n\nAlso called a 'tricolon' in rhetoric.",difficulty:1,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-26-3",islandId:"island-26",front:"What techniques make persuasive writing effective? Name at least 5.",
   back:"1. Rule of three — 'fast, reliable and affordable'\n2. Rhetorical questions — 'Surely we can do better?'\n3. Direct address — 'You can make a difference.'\n4. Statistics and facts — add credibility\n5. Anecdote — a personal story to make it relatable\n6. Emotive language — words that trigger strong feelings\n7. Counter-argument then rebuttal — shows you've considered the other side\n\nRemember AFOREST: Anecdote, Fact, Opinion, Rhetorical question, Emotive language, Statistics, Triplet.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},

  // ── English: Myths, Legends & Gothic Fiction ──────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-27-1",islandId:"island-27",front:"What are the key conventions of Gothic fiction?",
   back:"Gothic fiction creates fear, mystery and atmosphere through:\n\n• Setting: crumbling castles, dark mansions, moors, graveyards\n• Weather: storms, mist, darkness — pathetic fallacy\n• Characters: villains, monsters, damsels in distress, mysterious strangers\n• Themes: death, madness, the supernatural, forbidden knowledge\n• Language: dark, dramatic adjectives; long, winding sentences\n\nExamples: Frankenstein, Dracula, The Tell-Tale Heart\n\nGothic atmosphere relies on slow build-up, not jump-scares.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-27-2",islandId:"island-27",front:"What is pathetic fallacy? Give two examples.",
   back:"Pathetic fallacy = using weather or the natural environment to reflect a character's mood or the atmosphere of a scene.\n\nExamples:\n1. 'Thunder roared as she opened the letter' — storm mirrors her shock/dread\n2. 'The sun shone brightly on their wedding day' — sunshine mirrors happiness\n\nThe term was coined by critic John Ruskin.\n\nEffect: creates atmosphere, mirrors emotion without stating it directly — a form of 'show, don't tell'.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-27-3",islandId:"island-27",front:"What is the difference between a myth and a legend?",
   back:"Myth:\n• Explains natural phenomena or the origins of the world\n• Features gods and supernatural beings\n• Set in a sacred or timeless past\nExample: Persephone explains the seasons; Prometheus explains fire\n\nLegend:\n• Based (loosely) on historical figures or events\n• Features human heroes, often with supernatural elements\n• Celebrates courage, loyalty or moral values\nExample: King Arthur, Robin Hood, Beowulf\n\nBoth are part of oral tradition — passed down through storytelling before being written down.",difficulty:1,category:"concept"},

  // ── Science: Reproduction & Life Cycles ──────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-28-1",islandId:"island-28",front:"What is the difference between sexual and asexual reproduction?",
   back:"Sexual reproduction:\n• Involves TWO parents\n• Produces genetically UNIQUE offspring (variation)\n• Involves fertilisation (joining of egg and sperm)\n• Slower but creates variety — important for evolution\n\nAsexual reproduction:\n• Involves ONE parent\n• Produces IDENTICAL offspring (clones)\n• Examples: bacteria splitting, strawberry runners, bulbs\n• Faster but no genetic variation\n\nMost animals use sexual reproduction; many plants and fungi can use both.",difficulty:1,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-28-2",islandId:"island-28",image:"pollination-diagram",front:"Describe the process of pollination in flowering plants.",
   back:"Pollination = transfer of pollen from the anther (male) to the stigma (female) of a flower.\n\nInsect pollination:\n• Bright petals and nectar attract insects\n• Pollen grains are sticky, attach to insect\n• Insect transfers pollen to next flower\n\nWind pollination:\n• Dull flowers, no nectar\n• Pollen is light and produced in huge quantities\n• Carried by the wind — less reliable\n\nAfter pollination: pollen tube grows down to ovule → FERTILISATION occurs → seed forms.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-28-3",islandId:"island-28",front:"Name the main changes that happen during puberty in males and females.",
   back:"Both sexes:\n• Growth spurt\n• Body hair grows\n• Sweating increases\n• Emotional changes\n\nFemales:\n• Breasts develop\n• Hips widen\n• Menstrual cycle begins (menarche)\n\nMales:\n• Voice breaks (deepens)\n• Shoulders broaden\n• Testes produce sperm\n• Facial hair grows\n\nPuberty is triggered by hormones (oestrogen in females; testosterone in males). Typically begins age 9–14.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},

  // ── Science: Elements, Compounds & Reactions ─────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-29-1",islandId:"island-29",front:"What is the difference between an element, a compound and a mixture?",
   back:"Element:\n• Made of ONE type of atom only\n• Cannot be broken down further by chemical means\n• Found in the Periodic Table (e.g. O, Fe, Cu)\n\nCompound:\n• Made of TWO or MORE different elements CHEMICALLY joined\n• Has different properties from its elements\n• Can only be separated by chemical reactions (e.g. water H₂O, salt NaCl)\n\nMixture:\n• Two or more substances PHYSICALLY combined (not chemically)\n• Each substance keeps its own properties\n• Easily separated (e.g. sand + water, air)",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-29-2",islandId:"island-29",front:"How is the Periodic Table organised? What are groups and periods?",
   back:"The Periodic Table organises all known elements by atomic number (number of protons).\n\nPeriods (horizontal rows):\n• Each row represents a new electron 'shell'\n• Period 1 = 2 elements; Period 2 = 8 elements, etc.\n\nGroups (vertical columns):\n• Elements in the same group have similar chemical properties\n• Key groups: Group 1 (alkali metals), Group 7 (halogens), Group 0 (noble gases)\n\nMetals are on the LEFT; non-metals on the RIGHT.\nThe zigzag line separates them.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-29-3",islandId:"island-29",image:"separation-techniques",front:"Name 4 separation techniques and when you would use each.",
   back:"1. Filtration — separates an insoluble solid from a liquid (e.g. sand from water)\n2. Evaporation — removes liquid to leave a dissolved solid (e.g. salt from salt water)\n3. Distillation — separates a liquid from a solution using boiling points (e.g. pure water from sea water)\n4. Chromatography — separates mixtures of dissolved substances by how far they travel (e.g. inks, food dyes)\n\nKey: these are all PHYSICAL methods — no new substance is made.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},

  // ── Science: Energy Stores & Transfers ───────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-30-1",islandId:"island-30",image:"energy-stores",front:"Name 6 energy stores with an example of each.",
   back:"1. Kinetic — a moving car\n2. Thermal (heat) — a hot cup of tea\n3. Chemical — food, fuel, batteries\n4. Gravitational potential — a book on a shelf\n5. Elastic potential — a stretched rubber band\n6. Nuclear — atoms in a nuclear reactor\n\nAlso: magnetic, electrostatic.\n\nEnergy is NEVER created or destroyed — it is transferred between stores.\n(Law of Conservation of Energy)",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-30-2",islandId:"island-30",image:"heat-transfer-methods",front:"What is the difference between conduction, convection and radiation?",
   back:"Conduction:\n• Heat transfer through a solid by particle vibration\n• Best in metals (good conductors); poor in wood/plastic (insulators)\n\nConvection:\n• Heat transfer in fluids (liquids/gases) by currents\n• Hot fluid rises (less dense), cool fluid sinks → convection current\n\nRadiation:\n• Infrared electromagnetic waves — needs NO medium\n• Works in a vacuum (e.g. heat from the Sun reaching Earth)\n• Dark, matt surfaces absorb and emit best\n• Light, shiny surfaces reflect best",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-30-3",islandId:"island-30",front:"What is the Law of Conservation of Energy?",
   back:"Energy cannot be created or destroyed — it can only be TRANSFERRED from one store to another.\n\nExample: a bouncing ball\n• At the top: gravitational potential energy store is FULL\n• Falling: GPE transfers to kinetic store\n• At the bottom: KE transfers to elastic store (ball squishes) then back to KE\n• Some energy also transfers to thermal store (heat) due to air resistance\n\nTotal energy IN = Total energy OUT\n\nNo machine is 100% efficient — some energy is always 'wasted' as heat.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-30-4",islandId:"island-30",image:"sankey-diagram",front:"What is a Sankey diagram and how do you calculate efficiency?",
   back:"A Sankey diagram shows how input energy is split into useful output and wasted energy.\n\nThe width of each arrow represents the amount of energy.\n\nEfficiency = (useful energy output ÷ total energy input) × 100\n\nExample: A light bulb receives 100 J of electrical energy.\n• 20 J → useful light\n• 80 J → wasted heat\n• Efficiency = 20 ÷ 100 × 100 = 20%\n\nNo device is 100% efficient — energy is always 'wasted' (usually as heat).\nLED bulbs (~90% efficient) are much better than old filament bulbs (~10%).",difficulty:2,category:"application"},

  // ── Science: Scientific Skills & Enquiry ─────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-38-1",islandId:"island-38",image:"variables-diagram",front:"What are the three types of variable in a scientific experiment?",
   back:"1. Independent variable — the one you CHANGE deliberately\n2. Dependent variable — the one you MEASURE (it depends on the independent variable)\n3. Control variables — everything else you KEEP THE SAME to make it a fair test\n\nExample: testing how temperature affects enzyme activity:\n• Independent: temperature\n• Dependent: rate of reaction\n• Control: pH, enzyme concentration, substrate concentration",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-38-2",islandId:"island-38",front:"What is a hypothesis and what makes a good one?",
   back:"A hypothesis is a testable prediction — a statement about what you think will happen and why.\n\nA good hypothesis:\n• Makes a specific, measurable prediction\n• Is based on scientific reasoning\n• Can be proved right or wrong by evidence\n\nExample: 'I predict that increasing light intensity will increase the rate of photosynthesis because plants need light energy to convert CO₂ and water into glucose.'\n\nNot a hypothesis: 'I think the plant will grow.' (too vague!)",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-38-3",islandId:"island-38",front:"Name 5 important laboratory safety rules.",
   back:"1. Always wear safety goggles when heating or using chemicals\n2. Tie back long hair and avoid loose clothing near flames\n3. Never point a test tube at anyone when heating\n4. Know where the fire extinguisher, eye wash and fire blanket are\n5. Wash hands before leaving the lab\n\nAlso:\n• Never taste chemicals\n• Report spillages and broken glass immediately\n• Use tongs or heatproof mats for hot equipment\n\nHazard symbols warn you about dangerous substances.",difficulty:1,category:"application"},

  // ── Science: Electricity & Magnetism ─────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-39-1",islandId:"island-39",front:"What is the difference between current, voltage and resistance?",
   back:"Current (I): the flow of electric charge through a circuit. Measured in Amperes (A).\n\nVoltage (V): the 'push' or energy given to each unit of charge by the power source. Measured in Volts (V).\n\nResistance (R): how much a component opposes the flow of current. Measured in Ohms (Ω).\n\nOhm's Law: V = I × R\n(voltage = current × resistance)\n\nThink: voltage is the pressure, current is the flow, resistance is the restriction.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-39-2",islandId:"island-39",image:"circuit-comparison",front:"What is the difference between a series and a parallel circuit?",
   back:"Series circuit:\n• Components connected in ONE loop\n• Same current flows through everything\n• Voltage shared between components\n• If one component breaks → ALL go out\n\nParallel circuit:\n• Components connected in SEPARATE branches\n• Each branch gets the full voltage\n• Different currents can flow in each branch\n• If one component breaks → others keep working\n• Used in household wiring\n\nParallel is preferred in homes because each device gets full voltage and works independently.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-39-3",islandId:"island-39",front:"What is a magnetic field? Which materials are magnetic?",
   back:"A magnetic field is the region around a magnet where a magnetic force is experienced. It is shown by field lines — arrows pointing from NORTH to SOUTH pole.\n\nField lines are CLOSEST (strongest) near the poles.\n\nMagnetic materials (attracted to magnets):\n• Iron\n• Steel\n• Nickel\n• Cobalt\n\n⚠️ Most metals are NOT magnetic (e.g. aluminium, copper, gold)\n\nElectromagnets: a coil of wire carrying current acts as a magnet — turn off the current and the magnetism disappears.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},

  // ── Science: Waves & Electromagnetic Spectrum ─────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-40-1",islandId:"island-40",image:"wave-properties",front:"What are amplitude, frequency and wavelength of a wave?",
   back:"Amplitude: the maximum displacement from the rest position — how 'tall' the wave is. Bigger amplitude = more energy.\n\nFrequency: the number of complete waves passing a point per second. Measured in Hertz (Hz).\n\nWavelength: the distance from one crest to the next (or trough to trough). Measured in metres.\n\nWave speed = frequency × wavelength\n(v = f × λ)\n\nIn a transverse wave, particles vibrate AT RIGHT ANGLES to the direction of travel (e.g. light, water waves).",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-40-2",islandId:"island-40",image:"em-spectrum",front:"List the electromagnetic spectrum in order from lowest to highest frequency.",
   back:"Radio → Microwave → Infrared → Visible light → Ultraviolet → X-rays → Gamma rays\n\nMemory aid: 'Really Mighty Invisible Vibrations Undo X-ray Guns'\n\nAll EM waves:\n• Travel at the speed of light (3×10⁸ m/s) in a vacuum\n• Are transverse waves\n• Transfer energy\n• Do NOT need a medium\n\nHigher frequency = shorter wavelength = more energy",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-40-3",islandId:"island-40",front:"Give one use and one hazard for infrared and ultraviolet radiation.",
   back:"Infrared (IR):\n✅ Uses: TV remote controls, thermal cameras, night-vision goggles, grills and toasters\n⚠️ Hazard: skin burns from intense heat sources\n\nUltraviolet (UV):\n✅ Uses: sterilising medical equipment, detecting forged banknotes, sunbeds\n⚠️ Hazard: can damage skin cells → sunburn, increased risk of skin cancer; can damage eyes\n\nProtect yourself from UV: use sunscreen (SPF), wear sunglasses, cover skin in strong sunlight.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},

  // ── Science: Classification of Living Things ──────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-41-1",islandId:"island-41",image:"five-kingdoms",front:"What are the five kingdoms of living things?",
   back:"1. Animals — multicellular, no cell wall, feed by ingestion (eating)\n2. Plants — multicellular, cell wall of cellulose, make food by photosynthesis\n3. Fungi — cell wall of chitin, feed by external digestion (decomposers/parasites)\n4. Protists — mostly single-celled eukaryotes (e.g. amoeba, algae)\n5. Prokaryotes — no nucleus, single-celled (bacteria)\n\nEukaryotes have a nucleus; prokaryotes do not.\n\nViruses are NOT in any kingdom — they are not considered truly alive.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-41-2",islandId:"island-41",front:"What is binomial nomenclature? Give an example.",
   back:"Binomial nomenclature is the two-part scientific naming system devised by Carl Linnaeus.\n\nFormat: Genus species (both in italics; Genus capitalised)\n\nExamples:\n• Homo sapiens (humans)\n• Panthera leo (lion)\n• Rosa canina (dog rose)\n\nWhy use it?\n• Avoids confusion caused by different common names in different languages\n• Same name used by scientists worldwide\n• Shows evolutionary relationship (same genus = closely related)\n\nFull classification: Kingdom → Phylum → Class → Order → Family → Genus → Species",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-41-3",islandId:"island-41",front:"What is a dichotomous key and how do you use one?",
   back:"A dichotomous key is a tool for identifying unknown organisms using a series of YES/NO questions.\n\nHow to use:\n1. Start at question 1 — answer yes or no\n2. Follow the branch to the next question\n3. Continue until you reach the organism's name\n\nExample:\n1. Does it have wings? → Yes → 2. Are wings feathered? → Yes → Bird\n\nWhy useful: allows anyone to identify organisms systematically, even without expert knowledge.\n\nDichotomous = splitting into two at each step.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},

  // ── Science: Human Body Systems ───────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-42-1",islandId:"island-42",image:"heart-diagram",front:"Describe the path of blood through the heart.",
   back:"The heart has FOUR chambers:\n\nRight side (deoxygenated blood):\n1. Blood from body enters right atrium\n2. Flows to right ventricle\n3. Pumped to lungs to pick up oxygen\n\nLeft side (oxygenated blood):\n4. Returns from lungs to left atrium\n5. Flows to left ventricle\n6. Pumped out to the whole body\n\nBlood vessels:\n• Arteries: carry blood AWAY from heart (thick walls, under pressure)\n• Veins: carry blood BACK to heart (valves prevent backflow)\n• Capillaries: tiny vessels where gas/nutrient exchange happens\n\nThe heart is a double pump.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-42-2",islandId:"island-42",image:"digestive-system",front:"Name the main organs of the digestive system in order.",
   back:"Mouth → Oesophagus → Stomach → Small intestine → Large intestine → Rectum → Anus\n\nKey functions:\n• Mouth: mechanical digestion (chewing) + amylase (breaks down starch)\n• Stomach: churns food + hydrochloric acid kills bacteria + protease enzymes\n• Small intestine: most chemical digestion + absorption of nutrients into blood\n• Large intestine: absorbs water; remaining solid waste becomes faeces\n• Liver: produces bile (emulsifies fats), processes absorbed nutrients\n• Pancreas: produces digestive enzymes and releases them into small intestine",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-42-3",islandId:"island-42",image:"reflex-arc",front:"What is a reflex action? Name the steps in the reflex arc.",
   back:"A reflex action is a fast, automatic response to a stimulus that protects the body. It bypasses conscious thought.\n\nReflex arc:\n1. Stimulus (e.g. pain from touching a hot surface)\n2. Receptor detects stimulus (pain receptors in skin)\n3. Sensory neuron carries impulse to spinal cord\n4. Relay neuron in spinal cord passes signal\n5. Motor neuron carries impulse to effector\n6. Effector (muscle) responds — hand pulls away\n\nThis all happens in milliseconds — BEFORE the brain processes the pain.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},

  // ── Science: Genetics & Natural Selection ────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-43-1",islandId:"island-43",image:"dna-genes-chromosomes",front:"What is the difference between genotype and phenotype?",
   back:"Genotype = the genetic make-up of an organism — the actual alleles it carries.\nE.g. Tt or TT or tt\n\nPhenotype = the observable characteristics that result from the genotype (and environment).\nE.g. 'tall' or 'short'\n\nDominant allele (capital letter): expressed even when only one copy is present\nRecessive allele (lowercase): only expressed when TWO copies are present (homozygous recessive)\n\nHomozygous: both alleles the same (TT or tt)\nHeterozygous: alleles are different (Tt) — also called a carrier of the recessive allele",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-43-2",islandId:"island-43",image:"punnett-square",front:"How do you complete a Punnett square? Give an example.",
   back:"A Punnett square predicts possible offspring genotypes.\n\nExample: both parents are Tt (heterozygous for height)\n\n     T    t\nT | TT | Tt |\nt | Tt | tt |\n\nResults:\n• TT (25%) — homozygous dominant → tall\n• Tt (50%) — heterozygous → tall (T is dominant)\n• tt (25%) — homozygous recessive → short\n\nPhenotype ratio: 3 tall : 1 short\nGenotype ratio: 1 TT : 2 Tt : 1 tt\n\nKey: put parent 1 alleles along the top, parent 2 down the side.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-43-3",islandId:"island-43",front:"Explain natural selection in 4 steps.",
   back:"1. VARIATION — individuals in a population have different inherited characteristics\n\n2. STRUGGLE FOR SURVIVAL — more offspring are born than can survive (competition for food, mates, space)\n\n3. SELECTION — individuals with advantageous characteristics are more likely to survive and reproduce ('survival of the fittest')\n\n4. INHERITANCE — survivors pass their favourable alleles to offspring\n\nOver many generations: the favourable trait becomes more common → the species becomes better adapted.\n\nCharles Darwin proposed natural selection in 'On the Origin of Species' (1859).",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── Science: Photosynthesis & Respiration ────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-44-1",islandId:"island-44",image:"photosynthesis-diagram",front:"Write the word equation and symbol equation for photosynthesis.",
   back:"Word equation:\nCarbon dioxide + Water → Glucose + Oxygen\n(using light energy, in chloroplasts containing chlorophyll)\n\nSymbol equation:\n6CO₂ + 6H₂O → C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂\n\nWhat the plant does with glucose:\n• Respiration (release energy)\n• Making cell walls (cellulose)\n• Making proteins (with minerals)\n• Storing as starch\n• Making fats/oils for seeds",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-44-2",islandId:"island-44",front:"What three factors affect the rate of photosynthesis?",
   back:"1. Light intensity — more light = faster rate (up to a maximum)\n2. CO₂ concentration — more CO₂ = faster rate (up to a maximum)\n3. Temperature — warmer = faster rate (up to ~40°C; above this enzymes denature and rate falls)\n\nLimiting factor: the factor in shortest supply that is holding the rate back, even if other factors are increased.\n\nE.g. If CO₂ is low, increasing light won't help — CO₂ is the limiting factor.\n\nWater is also needed but is rarely the limiting factor in typical conditions.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-44-3",islandId:"island-44",image:"respiration-comparison",front:"Compare aerobic and anaerobic respiration.",
   back:"Aerobic respiration (with oxygen):\nGlucose + Oxygen → Carbon dioxide + Water (+large amount of energy)\nC₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂ → 6CO₂ + 6H₂O\nHappens in: mitochondria\n\nAnaerobic respiration (without oxygen):\nIn animals/humans: Glucose → Lactic acid (+small amount of energy)\nIn yeast/plants: Glucose → Ethanol + Carbon dioxide\nHappens in: cytoplasm\n\nAnaerobic is used when oxygen can't reach muscles fast enough (e.g. sprinting).\nLactic acid build-up causes muscle fatigue and soreness.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── Science: Rocks & Earth Structure ─────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-45-1",islandId:"island-45",image:"earth-layers",front:"Name the four layers of the Earth and describe each.",
   back:"From outside to inside:\n\n1. Crust — thin, solid outer layer (oceanic: 5–10 km; continental: 30–70 km)\n2. Mantle — thick layer of semi-molten rock; convection currents drive plate movement\n3. Outer core — liquid iron and nickel; generates Earth's magnetic field\n4. Inner core — solid iron and nickel; extremely hot (~5,000°C) but solid due to intense pressure\n\nTotal radius: ~6,371 km\nThe crust + top of mantle = lithosphere (broken into tectonic plates)",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-45-2",islandId:"island-45",front:"What is the difference between igneous, sedimentary and metamorphic rocks?",
   back:"Igneous — formed when magma/lava COOLS and solidifies\n• Intrusive (slow cooling underground) → large crystals (e.g. granite)\n• Extrusive (fast cooling at surface) → small crystals (e.g. basalt)\n\nSedimentary — formed from COMPRESSED layers of sediment\n• Examples: sandstone, limestone, chalk\n• Often contain fossils; layers (strata) visible\n\nMetamorphic — formed when existing rocks are changed by HEAT and PRESSURE\n• Original rock recrystallises without melting\n• Examples: marble (from limestone), slate (from mudstone)",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-45-3",islandId:"island-45",image:"rock-cycle",front:"Describe the rock cycle.",
   back:"The rock cycle shows how rocks are continuously formed, changed and reformed:\n\n1. Magma → cools → IGNEOUS rock\n2. Any rock → weathering and erosion → sediment\n3. Sediment → compaction and cementation → SEDIMENTARY rock\n4. Any rock → heat and pressure → METAMORPHIC rock\n5. Any rock → melts → MAGMA (cycle restarts)\n\nDriving forces: volcanic activity, plate tectonics, weathering, erosion\n\nThe rock cycle operates over millions of years — rocks are constantly recycled.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── Science: Earth's Cycles & Atmosphere ──────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-46-1",islandId:"island-46",image:"water-cycle",front:"Describe the key stages of the water cycle.",
   back:"1. Evaporation — water from oceans/lakes heats up and turns to water vapour\n2. Transpiration — water vapour released by plants through stomata\n3. Condensation — water vapour rises, cools, and condenses into clouds (tiny water droplets)\n4. Precipitation — water falls as rain, snow, sleet or hail\n5. Run-off — water flows along the surface into rivers and back to the sea\n6. Infiltration — water soaks into the ground → groundwater\n\nThe sun provides energy for evaporation. Gravity drives precipitation and run-off.\n\nThe water cycle continuously moves fresh water around Earth — it is never 'used up'.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-46-2",islandId:"island-46",front:"What is the greenhouse effect and what causes the enhanced greenhouse effect?",
   back:"Natural greenhouse effect:\n• Sun's radiation warms Earth's surface\n• Earth emits infrared (heat) radiation\n• Greenhouse gases (CO₂, methane, water vapour) ABSORB and RE-EMIT this infrared, trapping heat\n• Keeps Earth warm enough for life (~15°C average)\n\nEnhanced (man-made) greenhouse effect:\n• Burning fossil fuels, deforestation and farming increase CO₂ and methane\n• More heat is trapped → global temperatures rise → climate change\n\nEvidence: rising CO₂ levels, rising global temperatures, melting ice caps, rising sea levels.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-46-3",islandId:"island-46",image:"carbon-cycle",front:"Describe the carbon cycle — how does carbon move between stores?",
   back:"Carbon stores: atmosphere (CO₂), plants, animals, soil, oceans, fossil fuels\n\nCarbon enters the atmosphere:\n• Respiration (animals and plants release CO₂)\n• Combustion — burning fossil fuels and wood\n• Decomposition — microorganisms break down dead organisms\n• Volcanic eruptions\n\nCarbon leaves the atmosphere:\n• Photosynthesis — plants absorb CO₂ and fix carbon into glucose\n• Dissolving into oceans\n• Shell formation (carbon locked into calcium carbonate)\n\nFossil fuels = carbon locked underground for millions of years; burning releases it rapidly.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── Science: Astronomy & Space ────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-47-1",islandId:"island-47",image:"solar-system",front:"Name the eight planets of the Solar System in order from the Sun.",
   back:"My Very Educated Mother Just Served Us Nachos:\n\nMercury — Venus — Earth — Mars — Jupiter — Saturn — Uranus — Neptune\n\nKey facts:\n• Mercury: closest to Sun, no atmosphere, extreme temperature swings\n• Mars: the 'red planet'; thin atmosphere\n• Jupiter: largest planet; Great Red Spot (giant storm)\n• Saturn: famous rings made of ice and rock\n• Uranus/Neptune: 'ice giants'; very cold and distant\n\nDwarf planets include Pluto (no longer classed as a full planet).\nThe asteroid belt lies between Mars and Jupiter.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-47-2",islandId:"island-47",image:"moon-phases",front:"Why does the Moon appear to change shape throughout the month?",
   back:"The Moon does NOT change shape — we see different proportions of its lit surface depending on its position relative to Earth and the Sun.\n\nThe Moon takes ~27–29 days to orbit Earth.\n\nPhases:\n• New Moon — Moon between Earth and Sun; dark side faces Earth\n• Waxing crescent → First quarter → Waxing gibbous\n• Full Moon — Earth between Moon and Sun; full lit face visible\n• Waning gibbous → Third quarter → Waning crescent\n• Back to New Moon\n\n'Waxing' = getting bigger. 'Waning' = getting smaller.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-47-3",islandId:"island-47",front:"What causes the seasons on Earth?",
   back:"Seasons are caused by Earth's AXIAL TILT (about 23.5°), NOT by Earth's changing distance from the Sun.\n\nNorthern Hemisphere summer (June):\n• North Pole tilted TOWARD the Sun\n• Sun is higher in the sky → more direct sunlight → more energy per m² → warmer\n• Longer days\n\nNorthern Hemisphere winter (December):\n• North Pole tilted AWAY from the Sun\n• Sunlight spread over larger area → less energy per m² → colder\n• Shorter days\n\nWhen it is summer in the Northern Hemisphere, it is winter in the Southern Hemisphere and vice versa.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── Science: Nutrition & Digestion ──────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-60-1",islandId:"island-60",front:"Name the seven nutrient groups and their main functions.",
   back:"1. CARBOHYDRATES — main source of energy (bread, pasta, rice)\n2. LIPIDS (fats and oils) — concentrated energy store, insulation, protects organs\n3. PROTEINS — growth and repair of cells and tissues (meat, fish, eggs, beans)\n4. VITAMINS — needed in small amounts for specific functions (e.g. vitamin C prevents scurvy, vitamin D for healthy bones)\n5. MINERALS — needed in small amounts (e.g. iron for haemoglobin, calcium for strong bones and teeth)\n6. FIBRE (roughage) — keeps the digestive system healthy, prevents constipation\n7. WATER — needed for chemical reactions, transport of substances, temperature regulation\n\nA balanced diet contains all seven in the right proportions.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-60-2",islandId:"island-60",front:"Describe the journey of food through the human digestive system.",
   back:"1. MOUTH — teeth physically break down food (mechanical digestion); saliva contains amylase enzyme (chemical digestion of starch)\n2. OESOPHAGUS — muscular tube pushes food to stomach by peristalsis\n3. STOMACH — churns food; produces hydrochloric acid (kills bacteria, provides acidic conditions); protease enzyme begins protein digestion\n4. SMALL INTESTINE — main site of digestion and absorption; enzymes from pancreas complete breakdown; bile from liver emulsifies fats; villi absorb nutrients into blood\n5. LARGE INTESTINE — absorbs water from undigested food; bacteria produce some vitamins\n6. RECTUM — stores faeces before excretion\n\nEnzymes are biological catalysts that break large molecules into small, soluble ones.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-60-3",islandId:"island-60",front:"What are the consequences of an imbalanced diet?",
   back:"Too much energy intake:\n• OBESITY — excess energy stored as fat; increases risk of type 2 diabetes, heart disease, joint problems\n\nToo little energy intake:\n• STARVATION — body breaks down fat and muscle for energy; weakened immune system; organ failure\n\nDeficiency diseases:\n• Lack of VITAMIN C → SCURVY (bleeding gums, poor wound healing)\n• Lack of VITAMIN D → RICKETS (soft, weak bones in children)\n• Lack of IRON → ANAEMIA (too few red blood cells, tiredness)\n• Lack of CALCIUM → weak bones and teeth\n\nEnergy requirements depend on age, sex, activity level and whether pregnant.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── Science: Pressure ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-61-1",islandId:"island-61",front:"Explain the formula for pressure and give the units.",
   back:"PRESSURE = FORCE ÷ AREA\nP = F / A\n\nUnits:\n• Force in Newtons (N)\n• Area in square metres (m²)\n• Pressure in Pascals (Pa) — 1 Pa = 1 N/m²\n\nKey idea: the SAME force over a SMALLER area creates GREATER pressure.\n\nExamples:\n• Knife blade — small area → high pressure → cuts easily\n• Snowshoes — large area → low pressure → don't sink into snow\n• Drawing pin — tiny point → huge pressure → pushes into surfaces easily\n\nTo rearrange: F = P × A or A = F ÷ P",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-61-2",islandId:"island-61",front:"Explain atmospheric pressure and how it changes with altitude.",
   back:"Atmospheric pressure is caused by the WEIGHT of the air above a surface.\n\n• Air has mass and gravity pulls it downwards\n• At sea level: ~101,325 Pa (about 101 kPa)\n• As altitude increases, there is LESS air above → pressure DECREASES\n• On top of a mountain, atmospheric pressure is lower than at sea level\n\nThis is why:\n• Water boils at a lower temperature on mountains (less pressure on the surface)\n• Ears 'pop' in aeroplanes (pressure difference either side of eardrum)\n• Air is 'thinner' at high altitude (fewer air molecules per unit volume)\n\nAtmospheric pressure acts in ALL directions — not just downwards.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-61-3",islandId:"island-61",front:"Explain pressure in liquids, upthrust, and why some objects float.",
   back:"Pressure in liquids:\n• Increases with DEPTH (more liquid above = more weight pushing down)\n• Acts in ALL directions at any given depth\n• Does not depend on the shape of the container\n\nUPTHRUST:\n• The upward force a liquid exerts on an object placed in it\n• Caused by the pressure difference between the bottom and top of the object (higher pressure at the bottom pushes up more)\n\nFloating and sinking:\n• Object FLOATS when upthrust = weight (forces balanced)\n• Object SINKS when weight > upthrust (unbalanced — net downward force)\n\nDensity matters: objects less dense than the liquid float; objects more dense sink.\n\nExample: steel ship floats because its hollow shape displaces enough water for upthrust to equal its weight.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── Science: The Periodic Table ─────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-62-1",islandId:"island-62",front:"Describe the structure of the Periodic Table.",
   back:"The Periodic Table arranges all known elements in order of ATOMIC NUMBER.\n\nROWS = PERIODS (7 periods)\n• Elements in the same period have the same number of electron shells\n• Properties change gradually across a period (metal → non-metal)\n\nCOLUMNS = GROUPS (numbered 1–7 and 0)\n• Elements in the same group have the same number of outer-shell electrons\n• Same group = similar chemical properties\n\nKey groups:\n• Group 1: Alkali metals (Li, Na, K) — very reactive metals\n• Group 7: Halogens (F, Cl, Br, I) — reactive non-metals\n• Group 0: Noble gases (He, Ne, Ar) — unreactive, full outer shell\n\nMetals on the LEFT; non-metals on the RIGHT.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-62-2",islandId:"island-62",front:"What was Mendeleev's contribution to the Periodic Table?",
   back:"Dmitri Mendeleev (1869) created the first widely accepted Periodic Table.\n\nWhat he did:\n• Arranged elements by ATOMIC MASS\n• Grouped elements with similar properties in COLUMNS\n• LEFT GAPS for undiscovered elements\n• PREDICTED the properties of missing elements\n\nKey examples:\n• 'Eka-aluminium' → later discovered as GALLIUM (1875) — matched his predictions\n• 'Eka-silicon' → later discovered as GERMANIUM (1886)\n\nWhy it was brilliant:\n• His predictions were confirmed, proving the table was correct\n• Modern table uses ATOMIC NUMBER instead of mass, but the structure is essentially the same\n\nMendeleev is considered the father of the modern Periodic Table.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-62-3",islandId:"island-62",front:"Compare the properties of metals and non-metals.",
   back:"METALS (left side of Periodic Table):\n• Good conductors of electricity and heat\n• Shiny (lustrous) when polished\n• Malleable (can be hammered into shape)\n• Ductile (can be drawn into wires)\n• Usually high melting and boiling points\n• Usually solid at room temperature (except mercury)\n• Form positive ions by LOSING electrons\n\nNON-METALS (right side of Periodic Table):\n• Poor conductors (insulators) — except graphite\n• Dull appearance\n• Brittle when solid\n• Lower melting and boiling points\n• Can be solid, liquid or gas at room temperature\n• Form negative ions by GAINING electrons\n\nMetalloids (e.g. silicon) have properties of both.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},

  // ── Science: Materials & Reactivity ──────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-63-1",islandId:"island-63",front:"List the reactivity series of metals and explain displacement reactions.",
   back:"Reactivity series (most → least reactive):\nPotassium > Sodium > Calcium > Magnesium > Aluminium > CARBON > Zinc > Iron > Copper > Silver > Gold > Platinum\n\nMemory aid: 'Please Stop Calling Me A Cute Zebra, I Clearly Should Go Platinum'\n\nDISPLACEMENT REACTIONS:\n• A MORE reactive metal can displace a LESS reactive metal from its compound\n• E.g. Zinc + Copper sulfate → Zinc sulfate + Copper (zinc is more reactive)\n• Iron + Copper sulfate → Iron sulfate + Copper (iron is more reactive)\n• Copper + Iron sulfate → NO REACTION (copper is less reactive)\n\nCarbon is included because it is used to extract metals.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-63-2",islandId:"island-63",front:"How is carbon used to extract metals from their ores?",
   back:"Metals BELOW carbon in the reactivity series can be extracted by heating with carbon (reduction).\n\nExample — extracting iron:\nIron oxide + Carbon → Iron + Carbon dioxide\n(Done in a blast furnace at high temperatures)\n\nWhy it works:\n• Carbon is MORE reactive than iron\n• Carbon 'steals' the oxygen from the metal oxide\n• This is a DISPLACEMENT reaction\n\nMetals ABOVE carbon (e.g. aluminium, sodium, potassium):\n• Cannot be extracted with carbon\n• Must be extracted by ELECTROLYSIS (using electricity)\n• Electrolysis is more expensive\n\nVery unreactive metals (gold, silver, platinum) are found NATIVE (pure) in the ground.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-63-3",islandId:"island-63",front:"Compare the properties of ceramics, polymers and composites.",
   back:"CERAMICS (e.g. clay, glass, porcelain, bricks):\n• Hard but brittle\n• Heat-resistant\n• Electrical insulators\n• Made by heating natural materials to high temperatures\n\nPOLYMERS (e.g. polythene, PVC, nylon, rubber):\n• Long-chain molecules made of repeating units (monomers)\n• Lightweight and flexible\n• Electrical insulators\n• Can be moulded into shape\n• Low melting points compared to metals\n\nCOMPOSITES (e.g. fibreglass, reinforced concrete, carbon fibre):\n• Made from TWO or more materials combined\n• Properties better than either material alone\n• E.g. carbon fibre = strong AND lightweight\n• E.g. reinforced concrete = strong in compression AND tension\n\nChoosing materials depends on: strength, weight, cost, flexibility, conductivity.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── Science: Hooke's Law & Springs ──────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-64-1",islandId:"island-64",front:"State Hooke's Law and explain the equation F = k × e.",
   back:"HOOKE'S LAW: The extension of a spring is DIRECTLY PROPORTIONAL to the force applied, provided the LIMIT OF PROPORTIONALITY is not exceeded.\n\nEquation: F = k × e\n• F = force applied (Newtons, N)\n• k = spring constant (N/m) — measures stiffness\n• e = extension (metres, m)\n\nRearranging:\n• k = F ÷ e\n• e = F ÷ k\n\nExtension = stretched length − original length\n\nKey points:\n• Higher k = stiffer spring (needs more force per metre of stretch)\n• Double the force → double the extension (if within limit)\n• The force–extension graph is a STRAIGHT LINE through the origin",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-64-2",islandId:"island-64",front:"Explain elastic deformation, plastic deformation and the limit of proportionality.",
   back:"ELASTIC DEFORMATION:\n• Object returns to its ORIGINAL shape when force is removed\n• Like stretching a spring gently — it bounces back\n• Hooke's Law applies in this region\n\nPLASTIC DEFORMATION:\n• Object is PERMANENTLY changed — does NOT return to original shape\n• Like bending a paperclip — it stays bent\n• Happens beyond the elastic limit\n\nLIMIT OF PROPORTIONALITY:\n• The point where the force–extension graph stops being a straight line\n• Beyond this point, F and e are NO LONGER directly proportional\n• Hooke's Law no longer applies\n• The spring may still deform elastically for a short time beyond this point\n\nELASTIC LIMIT:\n• The point beyond which deformation becomes PLASTIC (permanent)\n• Slightly beyond the limit of proportionality",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-64-3",islandId:"island-64",front:"How do you interpret a force–extension graph for a spring?",
   back:"STRAIGHT LINE through the origin:\n• Hooke's Law applies (F = k × e)\n• Extension is directly proportional to force\n• Gradient = spring constant (k)\n• Steeper line = stiffer spring\n\nLIMIT OF PROPORTIONALITY:\n• Where the straight line starts to curve\n• Beyond this, F and e are no longer proportional\n\nCURVED section:\n• More extension for each unit of force\n• Spring may be undergoing plastic deformation\n\nCalculating k from the graph:\nk = change in force ÷ change in extension\n(Take values from the straight-line section)\n\nExample: if 10 N causes 0.2 m extension\nk = 10 ÷ 0.2 = 50 N/m",difficulty:2,category:"application"},

  // ── Science: Health: Effects of Drugs ───────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-65-1",islandId:"island-65",front:"What is a drug and how are drugs classified?",
   back:"A DRUG is any substance that changes the way the body or mind works.\n\nTypes of drugs:\n1. MEDICINES — used to treat or prevent illness (e.g. painkillers, antibiotics)\n2. RECREATIONAL DRUGS — taken for their effects on mood/feelings\n   • Legal: alcohol, tobacco, caffeine\n   • Illegal: cannabis, cocaine, ecstasy (classified under the Misuse of Drugs Act)\n\nDrug effects:\n• STIMULANTS — speed up the nervous system (caffeine, nicotine)\n• DEPRESSANTS — slow down the nervous system (alcohol)\n• PAINKILLERS — reduce pain signals (paracetamol, aspirin)\n• HALLUCINOGENS — distort senses and perception\n\nLegal does NOT mean safe — alcohol and tobacco cause more harm than many illegal drugs.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-65-2",islandId:"island-65",front:"What are the effects of alcohol and tobacco on the body?",
   back:"ALCOHOL (a depressant):\nShort-term: slower reactions, impaired judgement, loss of coordination, reduced self-control\nLong-term:\n• LIVER DISEASE (cirrhosis — scarring of liver tissue)\n• Brain damage and memory problems\n• Heart disease\n• Weight gain\n• Addiction (dependence)\n\nTOBACCO (contains nicotine — a stimulant):\n• NICOTINE — highly addictive; reaches brain in seconds\n• TAR — coats lungs, damages cilia, causes lung cancer and bronchitis\n• CARBON MONOXIDE — binds to haemoglobin, reduces oxygen in blood, strains heart\n• Linked to: lung cancer, heart disease, emphysema, stroke\n\nPassive smoking (breathing others' smoke) is also harmful.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-65-3",islandId:"island-65",front:"Why is substance misuse dangerous?",
   back:"TOLERANCE:\n• Body adapts → more of the drug is needed for the same effect\n• Leads to taking dangerously high doses\n\nDEPENDENCE (addiction):\n• Person feels unable to function without the drug\n• Stopping causes WITHDRAWAL symptoms (anxiety, shaking, nausea)\n• Physical and/or psychological\n\nOVERDOSE:\n• Taking too much can be fatal\n• Risk increases with tolerance (need larger doses)\n\nYOUNG PEOPLE — extra risks:\n• Brain still developing until mid-20s\n• Drugs can cause lasting damage to brain development\n• Affects learning, memory, mental health\n\nOther risks:\n• Impaired judgement → risky behaviour\n• Impact on relationships, school, work\n• Financial problems\n• Legal consequences (for illegal drugs)",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── Science: Distance–Time Graphs ───────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-66-1",islandId:"island-66",front:"How do you read and interpret a distance–time graph?",
   back:"A distance–time graph has:\n• X-axis = TIME (seconds, minutes or hours)\n• Y-axis = DISTANCE from the starting point (metres, km)\n\nWhat the line tells you:\n• FLAT (horizontal) LINE → object is STATIONARY (not moving)\n• STRAIGHT DIAGONAL LINE → object is moving at CONSTANT SPEED\n• STEEPER line → FASTER speed\n• CURVE getting steeper → object is ACCELERATING\n• CURVE getting shallower → object is DECELERATING\n\nSpeed = gradient = distance ÷ time\n\nThe graph shows the TOTAL distance from the start, not the distance covered in each section.\n\nTo compare journeys: steeper gradient = faster speed.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-66-2",islandId:"island-66",front:"How do you calculate speed from a distance–time graph?",
   back:"Speed = gradient of the line\nSpeed = change in distance ÷ change in time\n\nFor a STRAIGHT LINE:\n1. Pick two points on the line\n2. Calculate: (distance₂ − distance₁) ÷ (time₂ − time₁)\n\nExample:\nPoint 1: (0 s, 0 m), Point 2: (10 s, 50 m)\nSpeed = (50 − 0) ÷ (10 − 0) = 50 ÷ 10 = 5 m/s\n\nFor a CURVED line:\n• The speed is changing\n• You would need to draw a tangent to find the speed at a specific point (more advanced)\n\nUnits of speed: m/s, km/h, mph\n\nRemember: steeper gradient = higher speed.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-66-3",islandId:"island-66",front:"Describe a distance–time graph for a typical journey with stops.",
   back:"Example journey: walk to a shop, stop, walk home.\n\nSection 1: STRAIGHT DIAGONAL LINE upwards\n→ Walking TO the shop at constant speed\n→ Gradient gives the speed\n\nSection 2: FLAT (horizontal) LINE\n→ STOPPED at the shop (time passes but distance stays the same)\n\nSection 3: STRAIGHT DIAGONAL LINE upwards (if distance is total)\nor downwards (if 'distance from home')\n→ Walking back\n→ If steeper than section 1 → walking faster on the way home\n→ If shallower → walking slower\n\nTotal distance = sum of all distances covered\nTotal time = time at the end of the graph\nAverage speed = total distance ÷ total time",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── History: The Crusades ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-31-1",islandId:"island-31",front:"Why did Christian Europeans launch the First Crusade (1096)?",
   back:"Religious motives:\n• Pope Urban II called for the Crusade in 1095 at Clermont\n• The Holy Land (Jerusalem) was under Muslim Seljuk Turk control\n• Christians believed recapturing Jerusalem would guarantee a place in heaven\n• Offered plenary indulgence (forgiveness of all sins)\n\nPolitical motives:\n• Byzantine Emperor asked for military help against the Turks\n• Nobles saw a chance for land and wealth\n• Kings wanted to get rid of troublesome knights\n\nThe First Crusade captured Jerusalem in 1099 after a brutal siege.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-31-2",islandId:"island-31",front:"How did Saladin and Richard I differ as leaders?",
   back:"Saladin (Salah ad-Din):\n• Sultan of Egypt and Syria; Muslim military leader\n• Recaptured Jerusalem in 1187\n• Respected by Crusaders for his chivalry — allowed Christian civilians to leave safely\n• Seen as merciful even by his enemies\n\nRichard I ('the Lionheart'):\n• English king; fierce warrior, led the Third Crusade\n• Won battles but could not retake Jerusalem\n• Negotiated a treaty (1192) allowing Christian pilgrims to visit Jerusalem\n• Was captured and ransomed on his way home\n\nBoth leaders were admired — even by their opponents.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-31-3",islandId:"island-31",front:"What was the long-term impact of the Crusades?",
   back:"Negative impacts:\n• Enormous loss of life on both sides\n• Increased hostility between Christians and Muslims\n• Persecution of Jewish communities in Europe\n\nPositive/unexpected impacts:\n• Trade expanded — Europeans encountered silk, spices, paper, mathematics\n• Islamic learning (medicine, astronomy, philosophy) transferred to Europe\n• Helped spark the Renaissance\n• Cultural exchange — Arabic words entered European languages\n\nHistorians debate significance: the Crusades ultimately failed militarily but had enormous cultural consequences.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-31-4",islandId:"island-31",front:"What did Europe learn from the Islamic world through the Crusades?",
   back:"The Islamic world was FAR MORE ADVANCED than medieval Europe.\n\nEurope gained:\n• Arabic numerals (0–9) — replaced clumsy Roman numerals\n• Algebra and mathematics\n• Advances in medicine and surgery\n• Astronomy and navigation\n• New foods: sugar, spices, citrus fruits, rice\n• Architectural techniques: pointed arches, domes\n• Superior textiles: silk, cotton\n• Paper-making\n\nIslamic cities like Baghdad, Cairo and Córdoba had UNIVERSITIES, HOSPITALS and LIBRARIES when most European towns had none.\n\nThis knowledge transfer helped spark the later Renaissance.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-31-5",islandId:"island-31",front:"How are the Crusades interpreted differently today?",
   back:"TRADITIONAL WESTERN VIEW:\n• Heroic Christian knights fighting for a noble cause\n• Focus on bravery, chivalry, adventure\n• This was the dominant view for centuries\n\nISLAMIC PERSPECTIVE:\n• The Crusaders were brutal foreign invaders\n• The massacre at Jerusalem in 1099 is a central event\n• Saladin is a hero of Muslim resistance\n\nMODERN HISTORICAL VIEW:\n• Both sides had mixed motives\n• Violence was committed by both sides\n• Multiple perspectives must be considered\n• The Crusades remain a sensitive topic in interfaith relations\n\nGood historians consider MULTIPLE PERSPECTIVES, not just one side's story.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── History: The Renaissance & Reformation ────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-32-1",islandId:"island-32",front:"What was the Renaissance and what ideas drove it?",
   back:"The Renaissance ('rebirth') = a cultural and intellectual movement beginning in Italy (~1300s–1600s).\n\nKey ideas:\n• Humanism — focus on human potential, not just religious life\n• Looking back to ancient Greek and Roman learning\n• Observation and evidence — challenging old ideas\n• New art techniques: perspective, chiaroscuro (light/shadow)\n\nKey figures: Leonardo da Vinci, Michelangelo, Galileo\n\nThe Printing Press (Gutenberg, 1450s) was crucial — it spread ideas rapidly across Europe for the first time.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-32-2",islandId:"island-32",front:"Why did Martin Luther challenge the Catholic Church?",
   back:"Luther's complaints (95 Theses, 1517):\n1. The Church sold 'indulgences' — payments to reduce time in purgatory\n2. The Pope had too much power and wealth\n3. The Bible should be in languages people could read (not just Latin)\n4. Salvation came from faith alone, not good deeds or payments\n\nHe nailed his 95 Theses to a church door in Wittenberg.\nThe Printing Press spread his ideas across Europe rapidly.\nThis sparked the Protestant Reformation — a permanent split in Western Christianity.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-32-3",islandId:"island-32",front:"Why did Henry VIII break with Rome and what were the consequences?",
   back:"Henry's reasons:\n• He wanted to divorce Catherine of Aragon (she had not produced a male heir)\n• Pope Clement VII refused to grant an annulment\n• Henry also wanted to seize the Church's wealth\n\nConsequences (Act of Supremacy, 1534):\n• Henry became Head of the Church of England\n• Dissolution of the Monasteries (1536–41) — Henry seized church land and wealth\n• England became Protestant (with complications under later monarchs)\n\nThis was driven by politics as much as religion — unlike Luther's theological challenge.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-32-4",islandId:"island-32",front:"What was the Counter-Reformation? How did the Catholic Church respond to Protestantism?",
   back:"The Counter-Reformation = the Catholic Church's response to Protestantism.\n\nKey elements:\n1. COUNCIL OF TRENT (1545–63):\n   • Clarified Catholic doctrine\n   • Banned the sale of indulgences\n   • Improved training of priests\n\n2. NEW RELIGIOUS ORDERS:\n   • The Jesuits (founded by Ignatius of Loyola) — focused on education, missions and winning back Protestant areas\n\n3. THE INQUISITION:\n   • Investigated and punished heresy\n   • Used to suppress Protestant ideas in Catholic countries\n\nResult: southern Europe stayed Catholic; northern Europe largely became Protestant.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-32-5",islandId:"island-32",front:"Name 4 key Renaissance figures and explain why each was important.",
   back:"1. LEONARDO DA VINCI (1452–1519):\n   • Painter (Mona Lisa), inventor, anatomist\n   • The ultimate 'Renaissance man' — curious about everything\n\n2. MICHELANGELO (1475–1564):\n   • Painted the Sistine Chapel ceiling\n   • Sculptor of David — showed human body in extraordinary detail\n\n3. COPERNICUS (1473–1543):\n   • Proposed the SUN is at the centre of the solar system (heliocentric theory)\n   • Challenged Church teaching that Earth was the centre\n\n4. GALILEO (1564–1642):\n   • Used a telescope to support Copernicus\n   • Put on trial by the Church for heresy\n   • Shows the tension between science and religious authority",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},

  // ── History: The Tudors & Elizabethan England ─────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-33-1",islandId:"island-33",front:"How did religion change under each Tudor monarch?",
   back:"Henry VIII — broke with Rome; kept Catholic practices but no Pope\nEdward VI — strongly Protestant; Book of Common Prayer; church simplified\nMary I — returned England to Catholicism; burned ~300 Protestants ('Bloody Mary')\nElizabeth I — Protestant 'middle way'; Church of England; moderate settlement\n\nThis pattern of back-and-forth religious change caused enormous instability and suffering.\n\nElizabeth's settlement was deliberately vague to include as many people as possible.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-33-2",islandId:"island-33",front:"What happened during the Spanish Armada (1588)?",
   back:"Why Spain attacked:\n• Philip II of Spain was Catholic and wanted to restore Catholicism to England\n• Elizabeth supported Dutch Protestants fighting Spain\n• English pirates (Drake) had raided Spanish treasure ships\n\nWhat happened:\n• Spain sent 130 ships (the Armada) to invade England\n• English fleet (smaller but faster) used fireships at Gravelines\n• Storms destroyed much of the Armada as it fled round Scotland\n• England survived — Elizabeth gave her famous Tilbury speech\n\nSignificance: England remained Protestant and became more confident as a sea power.",difficulty:1,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-33-3",islandId:"island-33",front:"How significant was Elizabeth I's reign?",
   back:"Arguments she WAS significant:\n• Brought religious stability after decades of upheaval\n• England became a major sea power (defeat of Armada, Drake's circumnavigation)\n• The arts flourished — Shakespeare, theatre, poetry\n• Long reign (45 years) — stability allowed England to grow in confidence\n\nArguments she was LESS significant:\n• She never married or produced an heir → succession crisis\n• Poverty and poor harvests caused suffering\n• Brutal repression of Irish rebellion\n\nHistorians use 'significance' criteria: impact, scale, duration, legacy.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-33-4",islandId:"island-33",front:"Did Mary I deserve the nickname 'Bloody Mary'? Consider both sides.",
   back:"ARGUMENTS FOR:\n• Burned ~300 Protestants at the stake (including Archbishop Cranmer)\n• Used public executions as a tool of religious terror\n• Name used by Protestant propagandists (John Foxe's 'Book of Martyrs')\n\nARGUMENTS AGAINST:\n• Henry VIII executed FAR MORE people (~72,000 including monks, rebels)\n• Elizabeth I executed over 100 Catholics\n• Mary was restoring what she believed was the TRUE faith\n• Her reputation was largely created by PROTESTANT PROPAGANDA\n• Other European monarchs (both Catholic and Protestant) did the same\n\nKey skill: evaluating whether a historical 'reputation' is fair or the result of bias in our sources.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-33-5",islandId:"island-33",front:"What were the Elizabethan Poor Laws? How did they treat the poor?",
   back:"The Poor Laws (1598 and 1601) were England's first SYSTEMATIC approach to poverty.\n\nThey divided the poor into:\n1. DESERVING POOR — sick, elderly, orphans, disabled\n   → Given poor relief (food, money, shelter from the parish)\n2. UNDESERVING POOR — able-bodied people who wouldn't work\n   → Sent to Houses of Correction (forced labour)\n3. VAGRANTS — wandering beggars\n   → Could be whipped, branded or imprisoned\n\nFunded by: local parish taxes (poor rates)\n\nWhy needed: rising population, inflation, enclosure of common land, failing harvests\n\nThese principles lasted until the Victorian era workhouses.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},

  // ── History: The Transatlantic Slave Trade ────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-34-1",islandId:"island-34",front:"Describe the triangular trade. What moved along each side of the triangle?",
   back:"Leg 1 — Britain to West Africa:\n• Ships carried manufactured goods (guns, cloth, alcohol) to exchange for enslaved people\n\nLeg 2 — The Middle Passage (West Africa to the Americas):\n• Enslaved Africans transported in horrific conditions\n• Journey took 6–12 weeks; up to 1 in 5 died\n\nLeg 3 — Americas back to Britain:\n• Ships returned with plantation goods: sugar, tobacco, cotton, rum\n\nBritain profited enormously. Cities like Bristol and Liverpool were built on this trade.\nAn estimated 12 million Africans were enslaved over ~400 years.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-34-2",islandId:"island-34",front:"Describe the conditions on the Middle Passage.",
   back:"The Middle Passage = the crossing from West Africa to the Caribbean/Americas.\n\nConditions:\n• People chained below decks in spaces too small to sit up\n• 400–600 people packed into a single ship\n• Disease (dysentery, typhus) spread rapidly\n• Little food or water; no sanitation\n• Up to 20% died during the crossing\n• Physical and psychological abuse from crew\n\nThose who survived faced enslavement on plantations — working 12–18 hour days, often in brutal conditions.\n\nThis was a deliberate, commercially organised system of human trafficking.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-34-3",islandId:"island-34",front:"How was the slave trade abolished in Britain? Who were the key figures?",
   back:"Key figures:\n• Olaudah Equiano — enslaved African who wrote his autobiography; powerful first-hand testimony\n• Granville Sharp — lawyer; fought legal cases against slavery in Britain\n• William Wilberforce — MP who campaigned for 20+ years in Parliament\n• The Clapham Sect — a group of Christian activists\n\nTimeline:\n• 1807 — Slave Trade Act abolished the TRADE (buying/selling enslaved people) in British territories\n• 1833 — Slavery Abolition Act freed enslaved people in British colonies\n\nNOTE: Slaveholders were compensated; enslaved people received nothing.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-34-4",islandId:"island-34",front:"Describe Africa BEFORE the slave trade. Name two thriving African kingdoms.",
   back:"Africa had thriving kingdoms and civilisations LONG BEFORE European contact:\n\n1. KINGDOM OF MALI (13th–16th century):\n   • One of the wealthiest empires in the world\n   • Mansa Musa's pilgrimage (1324) displayed legendary wealth\n   • Timbuktu was a centre of learning with a famous university\n\n2. KINGDOM OF BENIN (13th–19th century):\n   • Famous for sophisticated bronze sculptures\n   • Advanced governance and walled city\n   • Traded widely across West Africa\n\nAlso: Great Zimbabwe, Kingdom of Aksum (Ethiopia), ancient Egypt.\n\nThe myth that Africa had 'no history' was CONSTRUCTED to justify enslavement. It is completely false.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-34-5",islandId:"island-34",front:"Name two resistance figures and explain how enslaved people fought back.",
   back:"Enslaved people were ACTIVE AGENTS in their own liberation:\n\n1. TOUSSAINT LOUVERTURE:\n   • Led the Haitian Revolution (1791–1804)\n   • The ONLY fully successful slave revolt to create an independent nation\n   • Haiti became the first Black republic\n\n2. NANNY OF THE MAROONS:\n   • Jamaican freedom fighter (early 1700s)\n   • Led a community of escaped enslaved people in the mountains\n   • Used guerrilla warfare to resist the British\n   • Jamaican national hero\n\nOther forms of resistance:\n• Work slowdowns and sabotage\n• Maintaining African languages, music and culture\n• Escape and forming Maroon communities\n• Providing testimony for abolition campaigns (e.g. Equiano)",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── Geography: Biomes & Climate Zones ────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-35-1",islandId:"island-35",front:"What is a biome? Name 5 major global biomes.",
   back:"A biome = a large-scale ecosystem defined by its climate, vegetation and animal life.\n\n5 major biomes:\n1. Tropical rainforest — hot and wet all year; equatorial regions\n2. Hot desert — very hot days, cold nights; very little rain\n3. Tropical grassland (savanna) — warm, seasonal rainfall\n4. Coniferous forest (taiga) — cold, snowy; northern Canada, Russia\n5. Tundra — extreme cold, permafrost; Arctic regions\n\nBiome distribution follows latitude and climate zones — predictable global patterns.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-35-2",islandId:"island-35",image:"rainforest-layers",front:"Describe 3 adaptations of plants or animals in the tropical rainforest.",
   back:"1. Drip-tip leaves — pointed tips allow excess rain to run off quickly, preventing rot and fungal growth\n2. Buttress roots — wide roots spread out at ground level to support very tall trees in shallow soil\n3. Bromeliads — collect rainwater in their leaves to survive periods without direct rainfall\n\nAnimal examples:\n• Toucans' bright beaks — used to reach fruit in the dense canopy\n• Tree frogs — sticky toe pads for climbing in the wet, vertical environment\n\nThe rainforest has the greatest biodiversity on Earth — ~50% of all species.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-35-3",islandId:"island-35",front:"What are the main causes and effects of tropical deforestation?",
   back:"Causes:\n• Commercial logging for timber\n• Clearing land for cattle ranching (e.g. Amazon for beef exports)\n• Palm oil plantations (Indonesia, Malaysia)\n• Mining for minerals\n• Population growth — farming land\n\nEffects:\n• Loss of biodiversity — species extinction\n• Climate change — trees store CO₂; clearing releases it\n• Soil erosion — tree roots no longer hold soil\n• Loss of livelihoods for indigenous communities\n• Disruption of the water cycle\n\nRate: equivalent to a football pitch of rainforest lost every second.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-35-4",islandId:"island-35",image:"gersmehl-model",front:"Explain the Gersmehl model for the tropical rainforest. Why does deforestation break the nutrient cycle?",
   back:"The Gersmehl model shows nutrient cycling between three stores:\n1. BIOMASS (largest store in rainforest — the trees themselves)\n2. LITTER (dead leaves/organisms on the forest floor)\n3. SOIL (thin and nutrient-poor)\n\nIn the rainforest:\n• Litter decomposes RAPIDLY in warm, wet conditions\n• Nutrients return to soil but are IMMEDIATELY absorbed by roots\n• Most nutrients stay in the biomass, not the soil\n\nWhen trees are removed:\n• No roots to absorb nutrients\n• Heavy rain LEACHES (washes away) nutrients from soil\n• Land becomes INFERTILE within a few years\n• Farmers clear more forest → destructive cycle",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-35-5",islandId:"island-35",front:"Describe the key features of polar regions. How are animals adapted to survive?",
   back:"Polar regions (Arctic and Antarctic):\n• Extremely cold: −30°C to −50°C in winter\n• Low precipitation (technically cold deserts)\n• 24-hour daylight in summer, 24-hour darkness in winter\n• Vegetation: mosses, lichens, tough grasses (tundra)\n• Permafrost — permanently frozen ground below the surface\n\nAnimal adaptations:\n• Polar bear: thick white fur (camouflage + insulation), layer of blubber, large paws for walking on ice\n• Arctic fox: seasonal fur colour change (white in winter, brown in summer)\n• Penguin (Antarctic): huddle behaviour, streamlined body for swimming\n\nThreat: climate change is melting polar ice, destroying habitats and raising sea levels.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── Geography: Restless Earth & Tectonics ─────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-36-1",islandId:"island-36",image:"earth-structure-geo",front:"Describe the internal structure of the Earth.",
   back:"From outside to inside:\n\n1. Crust — thin outer layer; continental crust (thicker, less dense) and oceanic crust (thinner, denser)\n2. Mantle — thick layer of semi-molten rock; convection currents drive plate movement\n3. Outer core — liquid iron and nickel; generates Earth's magnetic field\n4. Inner core — solid iron and nickel; temperatures up to 5,000°C\n\nThickness: crust ~5–70 km, mantle ~2,900 km, core ~3,500 km radius.\n\nTectonic plates float on the mantle like rafts on very thick treacle.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-36-2",islandId:"island-36",image:"plate-boundaries",front:"What happens at constructive, destructive and conservative plate boundaries?",
   back:"Constructive (plates move APART):\n• Magma rises and fills the gap → new crust formed\n• Volcanoes and mid-ocean ridges (e.g. Iceland on Mid-Atlantic Ridge)\n\nDestructive (plates move TOGETHER):\n• Denser oceanic plate subducts under continental plate → melts\n• Volcanoes and fold mountains (e.g. Andes, Japan)\n• Earthquakes as plates grind together\n\nConservative (plates slide PAST each other):\n• No new crust; no destruction\n• Massive earthquakes (e.g. San Andreas Fault, California)\n• NO volcanoes here",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-36-3",islandId:"island-36",front:"What is the difference between the focus and epicentre of an earthquake?",
   back:"Focus (or hypocentre):\n• The point UNDERGROUND where the earthquake originates\n• Where the rock fractures and energy is released\n• Can be shallow (< 70 km) or deep (up to 700 km)\n\nEpicentre:\n• The point on the SURFACE directly above the focus\n• Where shaking is usually most intense\n• This is the point given in earthquake reports\n\nSeismic waves radiate outward from the focus in all directions.\nIntensity decreases with distance from the epicentre.\nMeasured on the Richter scale (logarithmic — each step is ×10 more ground shaking and ~32× more energy).",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-36-4",islandId:"island-36",front:"How do tsunamis form? Why are they so destructive?",
   back:"Formation:\n1. Earthquake or volcanic eruption occurs UNDER THE OCEAN\n2. The sea floor shifts, displacing a massive volume of water\n3. Waves spread outward in all directions\n4. In deep ocean: waves are fast (~800 km/h) but LOW (barely noticeable)\n5. Near coast: waves SLOW DOWN but BUILD UP in height (up to 30+ metres)\n\nWhy so destructive:\n• Enormous force and volume of water\n• Little warning time for coastal communities\n• Travels far inland, destroying buildings and infrastructure\n\nExample: 2004 Indian Ocean tsunami — 230,000+ deaths across 14 countries.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-36-5",islandId:"island-36",front:"Why does the same earthquake cause more deaths in an LIC than an HIC?",
   back:"HIC (e.g. Japan):\n• Earthquake-proof buildings (flexible steel frames)\n• Early warning systems and tsunami alerts\n• Regular disaster drills — population knows what to do\n• Well-funded emergency services\n• Insurance for rebuilding\n\nLIC (e.g. Nepal, Haiti):\n• Weaker buildings — collapse easily\n• Limited or no warning systems\n• Fewer emergency services; slower response\n• Remote areas cut off by damaged roads\n• Dependent on international aid\n\nKey point: the HAZARD is natural; the DISASTER is shaped by human factors (wealth, preparation, infrastructure).",difficulty:2,category:"application"},

  // ── Geography: Africa: Development & Diversity ────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-37-1",islandId:"island-37",front:"What is the Human Development Index (HDI)? What does it measure?",
   back:"HDI = a composite measure of development (score 0–1; closer to 1 = more developed).\n\nIt combines THREE indicators:\n1. Life expectancy — how long people live (health)\n2. Education — years of schooling, literacy rate\n3. Gross National Income (GNI) per capita — standard of living\n\nAdvantage over GDP alone: captures quality of life, not just wealth.\n\nHigh HDI countries: Norway, Switzerland, Germany\nLower HDI countries: Niger, Chad, South Sudan\n\nBUT HDI is an average — it hides inequality within a country.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-37-2",islandId:"island-37",front:"What are common misconceptions about Africa? What is the reality?",
   back:"Misconception → Reality:\n\n'Africa is one country' → Africa is a continent of 54 countries with enormous diversity\n'Africa is mostly jungle' → Africa has deserts, grasslands, mountains, forests, cities and coastlines\n'Africa is uniformly poor' → Countries like South Africa, Kenya and Egypt have significant middle classes\n'Africa has no history before colonisation' → Africa had great kingdoms: Mali, Benin, Great Zimbabwe, Egypt\n\nWhy misconceptions matter:\n• They distort foreign policy and aid decisions\n• They disrespect Africa's cultures and histories\n• They ignore Africa as one of the world's fastest-growing economic regions",difficulty:1,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-37-3",islandId:"island-37",front:"What are the benefits and costs of tourism in Africa (e.g. Kenya)?",
   back:"Benefits (economic):\n• Foreign exchange earnings for the government\n• Jobs for local people (guides, hotels, transport)\n• Investment in infrastructure (roads, airports)\n\nBenefits (environmental):\n• Funding for national parks and conservation\n• Incentive to protect wildlife\n\nCosts:\n• Profit often goes to foreign companies ('leakage')\n• Environmental damage — litter, pollution, habitat disturbance\n• Cultural erosion — traditions commercialised for tourists\n• Seasonal jobs only — income is not reliable\n\nSustainable tourism tries to maximise benefits and minimise harm.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-37-4",islandId:"island-37",front:"What is Fairtrade? How does it help producers in Africa?",image:"types-of-aid",
   back:"Fairtrade = a certification system guaranteeing a FAIR MINIMUM PRICE for goods (e.g. coffee, cocoa, bananas).\n\nHow it helps:\n• Farmers get a stable income even when world market prices fall\n• A FAIRTRADE PREMIUM (extra money) is paid for community projects — schools, wells, healthcare\n• Encourages sustainable farming practices\n• Empowers cooperatives (farmers' groups)\n\nLimitations:\n• Only helps farmers who are part of Fairtrade cooperatives\n• Premium doesn't always reach the poorest workers\n• Fairtrade products cost more — not all consumers will pay extra\n\nLook for the Fairtrade logo when shopping!",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-37-5",islandId:"island-37",front:"How did colonialism contribute to Africa's development gap?",
   back:"European colonisation of Africa (mainly late 1800s–1960s):\n\n1. RESOURCE EXTRACTION — minerals, crops and enslaved people taken for European profit\n2. ARTIFICIAL BORDERS — drawn by Europeans at the Berlin Conference (1884), ignoring ethnic/cultural groups → led to conflict\n3. CASH CROPS — economies forced to grow exports (coffee, cotton) instead of food for local people\n4. WEAK INSTITUTIONS — colonial governments didn't invest in education or governance for Africans\n5. INDEPENDENCE — when countries became independent (1950s–60s), they inherited struggling economies and political instability\n\nKey point: colonialism is NOT the only factor, but it is a significant HISTORICAL CAUSE of the development gap. Africa's story also includes resilience, innovation and rapid growth.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── Introduction to Geography ────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-48-1",islandId:"island-48",front:"What is geography? What is the difference between physical and human geography?",
   back:"Geography is the study of the Earth's landscapes, peoples, places and environments — both natural and human-made.\n\nPhysical geography = the natural world:\n• Rivers, mountains, volcanoes, weather, biomes, rocks\n\nHuman geography = people and their activities:\n• Population, cities, migration, trade, development\n\nMany topics combine both — e.g. flooding involves physical processes (rainfall, rivers) AND human decisions (where we build, how we manage land).\n\nGeography answers the big question: 'Why is this place like this?'",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-48-2",islandId:"island-48",front:"Name the seven continents and five oceans.",
   back:"Seven continents (largest to smallest):\n1. Asia\n2. Africa\n3. North America\n4. South America\n5. Antarctica\n6. Europe\n7. Oceania (Australia/Australasia)\n\nFive oceans (largest to smallest):\n1. Pacific Ocean\n2. Atlantic Ocean\n3. Indian Ocean\n4. Southern (Antarctic) Ocean\n5. Arctic Ocean\n\nMemory aid for continents: 'All Awesome Nerds Seem Absolutely Excellent Overall'",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-48-3",islandId:"island-48",image:"lat-long-globe",front:"What are latitude and longitude? Where is 0° for each?",
   back:"Latitude = imaginary horizontal lines running east–west around the globe.\n• Measured 0°–90° North or South\n• 0° latitude = the EQUATOR (divides Earth into Northern and Southern Hemispheres)\n\nLongitude = imaginary vertical lines running north–south.\n• Measured 0°–180° East or West\n• 0° longitude = the PRIME MERIDIAN (runs through Greenwich, London)\n\nTogether they create a grid that locates any point on Earth.\nMemory aid: 'Latitude = ladder (horizontal rungs); longitude = long (tall vertical lines)'",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},

  // ── UK Geography ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-49-1",islandId:"island-49",front:"Name the four countries of the UK and their capitals.",
   back:"1. England — London\n2. Scotland — Edinburgh\n3. Wales — Cardiff\n4. Northern Ireland — Belfast\n\nThe United Kingdom (UK) = England + Scotland + Wales + Northern Ireland.\nGreat Britain (GB) = England + Scotland + Wales (no NI).\nThe British Isles = UK + Republic of Ireland + surrounding smaller islands.\n\nLondon is the capital of both England and the UK.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-49-2",islandId:"island-49",front:"What is the North–South divide in the UK?",
   back:"The North–South divide describes the economic and social inequality between the wealthier South East of England and the rest of the UK, particularly the North.\n\nSouth East:\n• Higher wages, more jobs, higher house prices\n• London as a global financial centre\n\nNorth and other regions:\n• Historically dependent on industry (coal, steel, textiles) — many declined\n• Lower average wages and life expectancy\n• Ongoing regeneration efforts\n\nThe divide is a simplification — there are wealthy areas in the North and deprived areas in the South — but the overall pattern is real.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-49-3",islandId:"island-49",image:"uk-physical-regions",front:"Name three major physical regions of the UK and describe their key features.",
   back:"1. SCOTTISH HIGHLANDS:\n• Mountainous with rugged peaks (Ben Nevis — UK's highest at 1,345 m)\n• Glaciated landscapes: lochs, U-shaped valleys\n• Sparse population, tourism and farming\n\n2. LAKE DISTRICT (NW England):\n• National Park with England's largest lakes and highest peaks\n• Formed by glaciation; popular for outdoor recreation\n\n3. THE FENS (East England):\n• Flat, low-lying wetland — some areas below sea level\n• Drained for farming — some of the most productive arable land in the UK\n\nOther key features: Pennines ('backbone of England'), Snowdonia (Wales), Severn (longest river), Thames (London's river).",difficulty:2,category:"application"},

  // ── Rocks, Weathering & Soils ────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-50-1",islandId:"island-50",front:"Name the three types of rock and explain how each is formed.",
   back:"1. IGNEOUS — formed when magma or lava COOLS AND SOLIDIFIES.\n• Intrusive (cools slowly underground) → large crystals (e.g. granite)\n• Extrusive (cools quickly on surface) → small crystals (e.g. basalt)\n\n2. SEDIMENTARY — formed when layers of sediment are COMPRESSED over millions of years.\n• Often contain fossils\n• Examples: limestone, sandstone, chalk, mudstone\n\n3. METAMORPHIC — formed when existing rocks are changed by HEAT AND PRESSURE.\n• Examples: marble (from limestone), slate (from mudite/shale)\n\nAll three types are connected through the ROCK CYCLE.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-50-2",islandId:"island-50",image:"rock-cycle",front:"Describe the rock cycle. How can one rock type become another?",
   back:"The rock cycle shows how rocks are constantly recycled over millions of years:\n\n• Igneous rock is WEATHERED and ERODED → sediment\n• Sediment is DEPOSITED, COMPACTED and CEMENTED → sedimentary rock\n• Sedimentary rock is subjected to HEAT and PRESSURE → metamorphic rock\n• Metamorphic rock MELTS → magma → COOLS → igneous rock\n\nAny rock type can become any other — the cycle has no fixed starting point.\n\nKey idea: the Earth's rocks are not permanent — they are constantly being destroyed and reformed, just very slowly.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-50-3",islandId:"island-50",front:"What is the difference between mechanical, chemical and biological weathering? Give one example of each.",
   back:"Weathering = the breakdown of rock IN SITU (in place — not transported).\n\n1. MECHANICAL (physical) weathering — rock breaks without changing chemically.\n• Example: FREEZE-THAW — water enters cracks, freezes and expands (by 9%), forcing the crack wider. Repeated cycles shatter the rock.\n\n2. CHEMICAL weathering — rock is changed by chemical reactions.\n• Example: ACID RAIN dissolves limestone (calcium carbonate reacts with weak carbonic acid in rainwater).\n\n3. BIOLOGICAL weathering — living organisms break down rock.\n• Example: TREE ROOTS grow into cracks and gradually force them apart.\n\nWeathering is different from erosion — erosion involves TRANSPORT of material.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},

  // ── Geographical Skills & Fieldwork ──────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-51-1",islandId:"island-51",front:"What is GIS? Give two examples of how it is used.",
   back:"GIS = Geographical Information Systems — computer software that stores, analyses and displays LAYERS of geographical data on digital maps.\n\nExamples of use:\n1. FLOOD RISK MAPPING — the Environment Agency overlays flood zones with population data to identify areas at greatest risk\n2. URBAN PLANNING — councils layer transport, housing, green space and pollution data to make decisions about where to build\n\nOther uses: tracking disease outbreaks, route planning, environmental monitoring, retail location analysis.\n\nKey advantage: you can overlay multiple datasets and spot PATTERNS that aren't visible on a single map.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-51-2",islandId:"island-51",front:"What are the steps of a geographical fieldwork enquiry?",image:"fieldwork-enquiry",
   back:"1. QUESTION — what do you want to find out? (e.g. 'Does river width increase downstream?')\n2. HYPOTHESIS — a testable prediction based on theory (e.g. 'River width will increase downstream because tributaries add water')\n3. DATA COLLECTION — choose appropriate methods (measuring, surveying, sampling)\n4. DATA PRESENTATION — display using graphs, charts, maps or diagrams\n5. ANALYSIS — describe patterns and trends in your data\n6. CONCLUSION — does the data support your hypothesis?\n7. EVALUATION — was your method reliable? What could you improve?\n\nGood fieldwork is SYSTEMATIC, REPEATABLE and uses PRIMARY data (data you collect yourself).",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-51-3",islandId:"island-51",front:"What is the difference between primary and secondary data in geography?",
   back:"PRIMARY data = data you collect YOURSELF in the field.\n• Examples: measuring river depth, counting pedestrians, conducting surveys\n• Advantages: specific to your enquiry, up to date\n• Disadvantages: time-consuming, small sample size\n\nSECONDARY data = data collected by someone else.\n• Examples: census data, weather records, OS maps, satellite images\n• Advantages: large-scale, easy to access, collected professionally\n• Disadvantages: may not exactly match your needs, could be outdated\n\nBest practice: use BOTH primary and secondary data to strengthen your enquiry.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},

  // ── Globalisation ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-52-1",islandId:"island-52",front:"What is globalisation? Name three things that have caused it.",
   back:"Globalisation = the increasing interconnection of the world's economies, cultures and populations through trade, migration, technology and communication.\n\nThree key causes:\n1. TRANSPORT — containerisation, jet aircraft and motorways make moving goods and people faster and cheaper\n2. COMMUNICATION — the internet, smartphones and social media allow instant global connection\n3. TRANSNATIONAL CORPORATIONS (TNCs) — companies like Apple, Nike and Unilever operate in many countries, linking economies together\n\nGlobalisation means that events in one part of the world increasingly affect people everywhere else.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-52-2",islandId:"island-52",image:"supply-chain-map",front:"What are food miles? Why do they matter?",
   back:"Food miles = the distance food travels from where it is produced to where it is consumed.\n\nExamples:\n• Kenyan green beans flown to UK supermarkets = ~6,800 km\n• New Zealand lamb shipped to UK = ~18,000 km\n\nWhy they matter:\n• Transport (especially air freight) produces CO₂ → contributes to climate change\n• However, it's more complex — growing food locally in heated greenhouses can use MORE energy than importing from warmer countries\n\nBalancing act: supporting local farmers vs. providing income for producers in developing countries.\n\nLook at labels: 'Produce of…' tells you where food was grown.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-52-3",islandId:"island-52",front:"What is a TNC? Give an example and explain one benefit and one cost.",
   back:"TNC = Transnational Corporation — a company that operates in MORE THAN ONE COUNTRY.\n\nExample: Unilever — headquartered in London, operates in 190+ countries.\n\nBenefit:\n• Creates JOBS in developing countries → wages, skills training, tax revenue for the government\n\nCost:\n• PROFIT LEAKAGE — most profits go back to the HQ country, not staying in the local economy\n• May pay low wages and offer poor working conditions\n• Can drive local businesses out of competition\n\nOther examples: Apple, Nike, Toyota, McDonald's, Samsung.\n\nTNCs are one of the main drivers of globalisation.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── Pre-1066 Britain ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-53-1",islandId:"island-53",front:"Who were the Anglo-Saxons? Name their main kingdoms.",
   back:"The Anglo-Saxons were Germanic peoples (Angles, Saxons, Jutes) who migrated to Britain from the 5th century after the Romans left (~410 AD).\n\nMain kingdoms (the Heptarchy):\n1. Wessex (south-west) — became the most powerful under Alfred the Great\n2. Mercia (midlands) — powerful under King Offa (Offa's Dyke)\n3. Northumbria (north) — early centre of learning (Lindisfarne)\n4. East Anglia (east)\n5. Essex, Sussex, Kent (south-east)\n\nAnglo-Saxon England lasted roughly 600 years (c. 450–1066).\nThey gave England its name: 'Angle-land'.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-53-2",islandId:"island-53",front:"Why is Alfred the Great considered so important in English history?",
   back:"Alfred the Great (r. 871–899), King of Wessex, is the only English monarch called 'the Great'.\n\nAchievements:\n1. MILITARY — defeated the Vikings at the Battle of Edington (878) and negotiated the Danelaw boundary\n2. DEFENCE — built a network of fortified towns (BURHS) to defend against Viking raids\n3. LAW — created a written law code combining Anglo-Saxon and Christian laws\n4. EDUCATION — promoted literacy and learning; translated key texts into English\n5. NAVY — built a fleet of ships — sometimes called the founder of the English navy\n\nAlfred united the Anglo-Saxon resistance and laid the foundations for a unified England.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-53-3",islandId:"island-53",front:"What was the Danelaw? Why is it significant?",
   back:"The Danelaw was the area of England under Viking (Danish) law and control, established by the Treaty of Wedmore (878) between Alfred the Great and the Viking leader Guthrum.\n\nExtent: roughly the north and east of England (north of a line from London to Chester).\n\nSignificance:\n• Showed England was DIVIDED between Anglo-Saxon and Viking rule\n• Viking settlers brought their own language, customs and place names\n• Many English place names have Viking origins: -by (farm/village: Derby, Whitby), -thorpe (settlement: Cleethorpes), -thwaite (clearing: Braithwaite)\n• The Danelaw was gradually reconquered by Alfred's descendants, leading to a unified English kingdom by the mid-10th century.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── The Peasants' Revolt ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-54-1",islandId:"island-54",front:"What were the main causes of the Peasants' Revolt (1381)?",
   back:"LONG-TERM causes:\n1. Black Death (1348–49) killed ~1/3 of population → LABOUR SHORTAGE\n2. Surviving peasants demanded higher wages\n3. STATUTE OF LABOURERS (1351) — froze wages at pre-plague levels, banned peasants from moving\n4. Growing resentment against the feudal system\n\nSHORT-TERM cause:\n5. The POLL TAX (1380) — a flat-rate tax of 1 shilling per person, regardless of wealth\n• Deeply unfair: a poor peasant paid the same as a wealthy lord\n• This was the spark that ignited the revolt\n\nUnderlying theme: peasants were becoming more aware of their rights and value after the Black Death.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-54-2",islandId:"island-54",front:"Who were Wat Tyler and John Ball? What role did each play?",
   back:"WAT TYLER:\n• Leader of the revolt from Kent\n• Led the march on London in June 1381\n• Met Richard II at Smithfield to present peasant demands\n• Killed during the meeting — stabbed by the Lord Mayor of London\n\nJOHN BALL:\n• A radical priest who preached equality\n• Famous saying: 'When Adam delved and Eve span, who was then the gentleman?'\n• Argued that God created all people equal — the feudal system was against God's will\n• Executed after the revolt failed\n\nTogether they represent the two forces behind the revolt: practical grievance (Tyler) and radical ideology (Ball).",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-54-3",islandId:"island-54",front:"Was the Peasants' Revolt a success or a failure? Give evidence for both sides.",
   back:"FAILURE in the short term:\n• Richard II broke ALL his promises (to abolish serfdom, reduce taxes)\n• Leaders were hunted down and executed (Wat Tyler, John Ball)\n• The poll tax was collected\n• Harsh punishments deterred further immediate rebellion\n\nSUCCESS in the long term:\n• No government tried another poll tax for centuries\n• Serfdom gradually DIED OUT over the next 100 years\n• Showed that ordinary people could challenge authority\n• Proved the feudal system was weakening\n• Influenced later protest movements\n\nVerdict: the revolt failed immediately, but the CAUSE it fought for — freedom from serfdom — was ultimately won.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── Medieval Church & Religion ───────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-55-1",islandId:"island-55",front:"Why was the Catholic Church so powerful in medieval England?",
   back:"The Church was the most powerful institution in medieval Europe:\n\n1. SPIRITUAL POWER — people believed the Church controlled access to heaven and hell. Fear of damnation meant obedience.\n2. WEALTH — collected TITHES (10% of everyone's income), owned ~1/3 of all land\n3. EDUCATION — ran the only schools; monks were among the few who could read and write\n4. HEALTHCARE — ran hospitals and cared for the sick and poor\n5. LAW — had its own courts; could try clergy separately from royal courts\n6. POLITICAL POWER — the Pope could EXCOMMUNICATE kings (cut them off from God) or place a country under INTERDICT (ban all church services)\n\nThe Church touched EVERY aspect of daily life from birth (baptism) to death (last rites).",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-55-2",islandId:"island-55",front:"What happened between Thomas Becket and Henry II? Why does it matter?",
   back:"CONTEXT: Henry II appointed his friend Thomas Becket as Archbishop of Canterbury (1162), expecting him to be loyal.\n\nTHE CONFLICT: Becket defended the Church's independence — refused to let clergy be tried in royal courts.\n\nTHE MURDER: Henry reportedly said 'Will no one rid me of this turbulent priest?' Four knights travelled to Canterbury Cathedral and MURDERED Becket (29 December 1170).\n\nAFTERMATH:\n• Becket was made a SAINT within three years\n• Canterbury became England's most important pilgrimage site\n• Henry did public PENANCE — walked barefoot and was whipped by monks\n• The Church KEPT its separate courts\n\nSignificance: showed the LIMITS of royal power against the Church — even kings couldn't easily defeat it.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-55-3",islandId:"island-55",front:"What was daily life like in a medieval monastery?",
   back:"Monks followed a strict daily routine centred on PRAYER and WORK:\n\nDaily routine (the Horarium):\n• 2:00 AM — Matins (first prayers of the day)\n• Throughout the day — 7 more prayer services (Lauds, Prime, Terce, Sext, None, Vespers, Compline)\n• Between prayers: work, study, meals\n\nMonks also:\n• Copied manuscripts by hand (ILLUMINATED manuscripts)\n• Grew food and brewed ale\n• Ran hospitals and schools\n• Gave charity to the poor (almsgiving)\n• Took vows of POVERTY, CHASTITY and OBEDIENCE\n\nMonasteries were centres of learning, healthcare and charity — the closest thing medieval England had to a welfare state.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},

  // ── Wars of the Roses ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-56-1",islandId:"island-56",front:"What were the Wars of the Roses? Who were the two sides?",
   back:"The Wars of the Roses (1455–1487) were a series of civil wars for the English throne between two branches of the royal family:\n\n🔴 HOUSE OF LANCASTER (red rose):\n• Descended from John of Gaunt (son of Edward III)\n• Key king: Henry VI (weak, suffered mental illness)\n\n⚪ HOUSE OF YORK (white rose):\n• Descended from Edmund of Langley (another son of Edward III)\n• Key king: Edward IV (strong military leader)\n\nBoth sides had a legitimate claim to the throne through Edward III.\n\nThe wars ended when Henry Tudor (Lancaster) defeated Richard III (York) at the Battle of Bosworth (1485) and united the two houses.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-56-2",islandId:"island-56",front:"What happened at the Battle of Bosworth (1485)? Why is it significant?",
   back:"The Battle of Bosworth Field (22 August 1485):\n\n• Richard III (York) vs Henry Tudor (Lancaster)\n• Richard had the larger army but key allies SWITCHED SIDES during the battle (the Stanley family)\n• Richard III was KILLED in battle — the last English king to die in combat\n• Henry Tudor was crowned HENRY VII on the battlefield\n\nSignificance:\n• Ended the Wars of the Roses\n• Founded the TUDOR DYNASTY (lasted until 1603)\n• Henry married Elizabeth of York → united Lancaster and York\n• Created the Tudor rose: red and white combined 🌹\n• Marked the traditional end of the medieval period in England",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-56-3",islandId:"island-56",front:"Who were the 'Princes in the Tower'? Why is this still a mystery?",
   back:"The Princes in the Tower were:\n• Edward V (aged 12) — briefly king after Edward IV died\n• Richard of Shrewsbury (aged 9) — his younger brother\n\nBoth were placed in the Tower of London by their uncle, Richard Duke of Gloucester, who then declared himself RICHARD III (1483).\n\nThe princes DISAPPEARED and were never seen again.\n\nMain theories:\n1. Richard III had them murdered to secure his throne (most common view)\n2. Henry VII had them killed after Bosworth to remove rival claimants\n3. They died of illness in the Tower\n\nIn 1674, two children's skeletons were found in the Tower — but DNA testing has never been conclusively performed.\n\nThis remains one of England's greatest historical mysteries.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  // ── English Campaigns: Wales & Scotland ──────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-57-1",islandId:"island-57",front:"How did Edward I conquer Wales? What role did castles play?",
   back:"Edward I conquered Wales in two campaigns (1277 and 1282–83):\n\n1277: forced the Welsh prince Llywelyn ap Gruffudd to submit and give up most of his land\n1282–83: Llywelyn was killed in battle; his brother Dafydd was executed → Welsh independence ended\n\nCASTLES were central to Edward's strategy:\n• Built a ring of massive CONCENTRIC CASTLES around Snowdonia to control the Welsh:\n  - Caernarfon, Conwy, Harlech, Beaumaris\n• Designed by Master James of St George\n• Among the most expensive building projects of the Middle Ages\n• Served as military strongholds AND symbols of English power\n\nEdward declared his son 'Prince of Wales' (1301) — a title held by the heir to the English throne ever since.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},
  {id:"card-57-2",islandId:"island-57",front:"Who was William Wallace? Why is he significant in Scottish history?",
   back:"William Wallace (c. 1270–1305) was a Scottish knight who led resistance against English rule.\n\nKey events:\n• Battle of STIRLING BRIDGE (1297) — Wallace defeated a much larger English army by using clever tactics on a narrow bridge\n• Appointed GUARDIAN OF SCOTLAND\n• Battle of FALKIRK (1298) — defeated by Edward I's longbowmen\n• Went into hiding; captured in 1305\n• Executed in London: hanged, drawn and quartered as a traitor\n\nSignificance:\n• National hero of Scotland — symbol of resistance against oppression\n• Inspired Robert the Bruce to continue the fight\n• Demonstrated that a smaller force could defeat a larger one with better tactics",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-57-3",islandId:"island-57",front:"What happened at the Battle of Bannockburn (1314)? Why was it important?",
   back:"The Battle of Bannockburn (23–24 June 1314):\n\n• Robert the Bruce (Scotland) vs Edward II (England)\n• Bruce chose the battlefield carefully — boggy ground that neutralised English cavalry\n• Scottish SCHILTRONS (formations of spearmen) held firm\n• Decisive Scottish VICTORY — Edward II fled\n\nImportance:\n• Secured Scottish INDEPENDENCE for the next 300 years\n• Led to the Declaration of Arbroath (1320) — asserted Scotland's right to self-determination\n• One of the most significant battles in British history\n• Bruce became one of Scotland's greatest heroes\n• England did not formally recognise Scottish independence until the Treaty of Edinburgh–Northampton (1328)",difficulty:2,category:"application"},

  // ── Medieval Towns, Trade & Economy ──────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-58-1",islandId:"island-58",front:"How did medieval towns grow? What was a town charter?",
   back:"Medieval towns grew from the 11th century onwards, driven by:\n• Increased TRADE after the Norman Conquest\n• Population growth (before the Black Death)\n• Markets attracting people to settle\n\nA TOWN CHARTER was a document granted by the king or local lord giving a town special privileges:\n• The right to hold a MARKET (usually weekly)\n• Freedom from some feudal duties\n• The right to elect a town council\n• BURGESSES (townspeople) gained personal freedom — 'Town air makes you free'\n\nIf a serf could live in a chartered town for a year and a day without being reclaimed, they became legally FREE.\n\nThis made towns engines of social change.",difficulty:1,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-58-2",islandId:"island-58",front:"What were guilds? Why were they important in medieval towns?",
   back:"Guilds were powerful associations of craftsmen or merchants in medieval towns.\n\nTwo main types:\n1. MERCHANT GUILDS — controlled trade in a town; set prices and standards\n2. CRAFT GUILDS — controlled a specific trade (e.g. weavers, blacksmiths, bakers)\n\nHow craft guilds worked:\n• APPRENTICE (7+ years learning the trade from a master)\n• JOURNEYMAN (qualified worker, paid daily — 'journée' = day)\n• MASTER (could run own workshop; had to produce a 'masterpiece')\n\nGuilds:\n• Maintained QUALITY STANDARDS\n• Set fair prices and wages\n• Cared for members who fell ill\n• Funded churches and public buildings\n\nGuilds were medieval England's version of trade unions and professional bodies.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"},
  {id:"card-58-3",islandId:"island-58",front:"Why was the wool trade so important to medieval England?",
   back:"Wool was medieval England's most valuable export — the foundation of the economy.\n\nKey facts:\n• England produced the finest wool in Europe (especially from Cotswold and Lincoln sheep)\n• Exported mainly to FLANDERS (modern Belgium) for weaving into cloth\n• The WOOL TAX was the king's biggest source of revenue — funded wars (especially the Hundred Years' War)\n• Wealthy wool merchants built grand churches (the 'wool churches' of the Cotswolds and East Anglia)\n\nThe WOOLSACK:\n• The Lord Speaker in the House of Lords still sits on a red woolsack — a symbol of wool's importance to England's medieval prosperity\n\nWool made England rich and connected it to European trade networks.",difficulty:2,category:"application"},

  // ── The Islamic Golden Age ───────────────────────────────────────────────
  {id:"card-59-1",islandId:"island-59",front:"What was the Islamic Golden Age? When and where did it take place?",
   back:"The Islamic Golden Age (c. 750–1258 AD) was a period when the Islamic world was the global leader in science, medicine, mathematics and culture.\n\nKey centres:\n• BAGHDAD (capital of the Abbasid Caliphate) — the world's largest and most advanced city\n• CAIRO — centre of learning in North Africa\n• CÓRDOBA (Islamic Spain) — famous for its libraries and religious tolerance\n\nThe Islamic world stretched from Spain to Central Asia, connecting diverse peoples and traditions.\n\nWhy it flourished:\n• The Quran encouraged the pursuit of knowledge\n• Trade brought wealth and ideas from many civilisations\n• The HOUSE OF WISDOM (Bayt al-Hikma) in Baghdad translated and preserved Greek, Persian and Indian texts\n\nEnded with the Mongol destruction of Baghdad in 1258.",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-59-2",islandId:"island-59",front:"Name three key scholars of the Islamic Golden Age and their achievements.",
   back:"1. AL-KHWARIZMI (c. 780–850):\n• 'Father of Algebra' — his book gave us the word 'algebra' (al-jabr)\n• Developed algorithms (the word comes from his name!)\n• Helped introduce Hindu-Arabic numerals (0–9) to the wider world\n\n2. IBN SINA / AVICENNA (980–1037):\n• Wrote 'The Canon of Medicine' — a medical textbook used in Europe for 500 years\n• Classified diseases, described contagion, promoted clinical trials\n\n3. AL-IDRISI (1100–1165):\n• Created one of the most accurate world maps of the medieval period\n• His 'Book of Roger' described the geography of the known world\n\nOther key figures: Ibn al-Haytham (optics), Al-Razi (chemistry/medicine), Omar Khayyam (mathematics/poetry).",difficulty:2,category:"definition"},
  {id:"card-59-3",islandId:"island-59",front:"How did the Islamic Golden Age influence medieval Europe and the modern world?",
   back:"The Islamic world preserved AND advanced knowledge that Europe had lost after the fall of Rome:\n\nDirect influences:\n• MATHEMATICS — Arabic numerals (0–9) replaced Roman numerals; algebra became essential\n• MEDICINE — Ibn Sina's Canon taught European doctors for centuries; hospitals as institutions\n• SCIENCE — optics, chemistry (al-chemy → alchemy → chemistry), astronomy\n• TECHNOLOGY — paper-making, water clocks, astrolabes\n• PHILOSOPHY — Islamic scholars preserved Aristotle and Plato; transmitted them to Europe → sparked the Renaissance\n\nThe Crusades and trade in Spain and Sicily were the main channels of knowledge transfer.\n\nModern legacy: every time you use algebra, Arabic numerals, or visit a hospital, you benefit from Islamic Golden Age scholarship.",difficulty:2,category:"concept"}
);

Object.assign(QUESTIONS, {
  "island-1":[
    {q:"Calculate: 3 + 4 × 2",opts:["14","11","10","7"],c:1,e:"BODMAS: do multiplication before addition. 4 × 2 = 8, then 3 + 8 = 11. If you got 14, you added first — a very common mistake!"},
    {q:"Round 4,732 to the nearest hundred.",opts:["4,700","4,730","4,800","5,000"],c:0,e:"Look at the tens digit (3). Since 3 < 5, round DOWN. The hundreds digit (7) stays, and everything after becomes 0: 4,700."},
    {q:"Which list is in order from smallest to largest?",opts:["−2, −5, 0, 3","−5, −2, 0, 3","0, −2, −5, 3","3, 0, −2, −5"],c:1,e:"On a number line, more negative = smaller (further left). −5 < −2 < 0 < 3 is the correct order."}
  ],
  "island-2":[
    {q:"What is 3/4 as a decimal?",opts:["0.34","0.43","0.7","0.75"],c:3,e:"Divide the numerator by the denominator: 3 ÷ 4 = 0.75. Or remember: ¾ = 75%."},
    {q:"What is 40% of 150?",opts:["40","60","90","110"],c:1,e:"10% of 150 = 15. So 40% = 4 × 15 = 60. Or: 150 × 0.4 = 60."},
    {q:"Which is the LARGEST value?",opts:["3/5","0.58","61%","0.6"],c:2,e:"Convert all to decimals: 3/5=0.60, 0.58, 61%=0.61, 0.6=0.60. Largest is 61% (0.61)."}
  ],
  "island-3":[
    {q:"What is the value of 5x − 3 when x = 2?",opts:["4","7","10","13"],c:1,e:"Substitute x=2: 5(2) − 3 = 10 − 3 = 7. Always put brackets around your substituted value."},
    {q:"The nth term of a sequence is 3n + 1. What is the 5th term?",opts:["6","11","16","19"],c:2,e:"Substitute n=5: 3(5) + 1 = 15 + 1 = 16."},
    {q:"Solve: 2x + 5 = 13",opts:["x = 2","x = 3","x = 4","x = 9"],c:2,e:"Subtract 5 from both sides: 2x = 8. Divide by 2: x = 4. Check: 2(4)+5 = 13 ✓"}
  ],
  "island-4":[
    {q:"What do angles in a triangle always add up to?",opts:["90°","180°","270°","360°"],c:1,e:"The three interior angles of ANY triangle always sum to exactly 180°. This is true for all triangles — equilateral, isosceles, scalene and right-angled."},
    {q:"A rectangle has width 4 cm and length 7 cm. What is its perimeter?",opts:["11 cm","22 cm","28 cm","28 cm²"],c:1,e:"Perimeter = 2(l + w) = 2(7 + 4) = 2 × 11 = 22 cm. Note: perimeter is a length (cm), not an area (cm²)."},
    {q:"Which triangle has ALL THREE sides of different lengths?",opts:["Equilateral","Isosceles","Scalene","Right-angled"],c:2,e:"Scalene = all sides different, all angles different. Equilateral = all sides equal (60° each). Isosceles = two sides equal."}
  ],
  "island-5":[
    {q:"Find the mean of: 6, 8, 4, 10, 7",opts:["6","7","8","35"],c:1,e:"Mean = sum ÷ count = (6+8+4+10+7) ÷ 5 = 35 ÷ 5 = 7. Don't forget to divide by the number of values, not the total."},
    {q:"What is the median of: 3, 1, 8, 5, 2?",opts:["1","2","3","5"],c:2,e:"First order them: 1, 2, 3, 5, 8. The median is the middle value — there are 5 numbers, so the 3rd one is the median: 3."},
    {q:"In a bar chart, a bar reaches height 15 for the 'Sports' category. This means:",opts:["15% chose sport","15 people chose sport","The bar is 15 cm tall","15 is the mean"],c:1,e:"The bar height in a bar chart represents the FREQUENCY (count) for that category — 15 people chose sport."}
  ],
  "island-6":[
    {q:"A reader 'infers' something. This means they:",opts:["Copy text word for word","Use clues to work out what isn't directly stated","Read only the first paragraph","Skip difficult vocabulary"],c:1,e:"Inference = reading between the lines. You use evidence from the text PLUS your own knowledge to reach a conclusion the author hasn't stated outright."},
    {q:"Which of these is an OPINION?",opts:["Shakespeare was born in 1564","Water boils at 100°C","Romeo and Juliet is Shakespeare's greatest play","London has a population of about 9 million"],c:2,e:"'Greatest play' is a judgement — it cannot be proven true or false. It's a personal view. The others are facts that can be verified."},
    {q:"Non-fiction texts are written to:",opts:["Tell imaginary stories only","Entertain only","Inform, persuade, argue, or instruct","Create fictional characters"],c:2,e:"Non-fiction deals with real information. Different non-fiction text types have different purposes: news articles (inform), speeches (persuade), instruction manuals (instruct)."}
  ],
  "island-7":[
    {q:"Which story opening is MOST effective at creating tension?",opts:["My name is James and I am 12.","It was a Monday morning.","The letter arrived sealed in red wax, long after midnight.","This is a story about a boy."],c:2,e:"A great opening creates immediate atmosphere and raises questions. 'Sealed in red wax, long after midnight' is mysterious and intriguing. The other options are dull and tell the reader nothing interesting."},
    {q:"'Show, don't tell' means:",opts:["Use images alongside writing","Reveal emotion through action and detail, not direct statement","Write only short sentences","Use dialogue instead of description"],c:1,e:"'She was nervous' TELLS us. 'Her hands trembled as she reached for the handle' SHOWS us. The second is more vivid and engaging — the reader infers the emotion."},
    {q:"The 'climax' on the story mountain is:",opts:["The opening scene","Where characters are introduced","The most exciting or tense turning point","The final line of the story"],c:2,e:"The climax is at the peak of the story mountain — the moment of greatest tension or conflict. Everything builds toward it, and the resolution comes after."}
  ],
  "island-8":[
    {q:"Which sentence is correctly punctuated?",opts:["the dog ran fast","The dog ran fast.","The dog ran, fast","the Dog ran fast."],c:1,e:"Sentences must start with a capital letter and end with a full stop (or ! or ?). 'The dog ran fast.' is the only option that follows both rules."},
    {q:"The apostrophe in 'the girl's bag' shows:",opts:["There are several girls","A letter is missing","The bag belongs to the girl","A question is being asked"],c:2,e:"This is a POSSESSIVE apostrophe — it shows ownership. One girl owns the bag: the girl's bag. (Compare: the girls' bags = bags belonging to multiple girls.)"},
    {q:"A semicolon is used to:",opts:["Introduce a list","Join two related main clauses","Show a missing letter","End a sentence with emotion"],c:1,e:"A semicolon joins two COMPLETE, related sentences: 'It was cold; she wore her coat.' Both halves must be able to stand alone as sentences."}
  ],
  "island-9":[
    {q:"'The moon is a silver coin' is an example of:",opts:["Simile","Alliteration","Metaphor","Onomatopoeia"],c:2,e:"A METAPHOR directly says one thing IS another, without using 'like' or 'as'. A simile would be: 'The moon is LIKE a silver coin.'"},
    {q:"Alliteration is the repetition of:",opts:["Rhyming words at line ends","The same consonant sound at the start of nearby words","Words that sound like what they describe","Ideas across a whole poem"],c:1,e:"Alliteration: 'the cold, cruel cliffs crashed.' The same consonant sound (c) is repeated at the start of nearby words. It creates rhythm and can reinforce mood."},
    {q:"'The angry clouds growled overhead.' Which device is this?",opts:["Simile","Alliteration","Rhyme","Personification"],c:3,e:"Personification gives a human quality (growling) to something non-human (clouds). Clouds cannot really growl — giving them this ability makes the description more vivid and atmospheric."}
  ],
  "island-10":[
    {q:"Which is the BEST advice before giving a presentation?",opts:["Read word-for-word from a script","Memorise every single word precisely","Practise out loud multiple times","Leave preparation until the day"],c:2,e:"Practising OUT LOUD (not just in your head) helps you hear how it sounds, build genuine confidence, and spot parts that feel unnatural or hard to say."},
    {q:"Formal language should be used when:",opts:["Texting friends","Chatting at lunch","Speaking in a school presentation or interview","Writing a personal diary"],c:2,e:"Formal language is appropriate in academic, professional and public contexts. It avoids slang, uses complete sentences and standard grammar. Match your language to your audience and purpose."},
    {q:"Active listening means:",opts:["Planning your reply while the person speaks","Nodding and making eye contact to show understanding, then asking questions","Waiting in silence for your turn","Writing notes without making eye contact"],c:1,e:"Active listeners focus FULLY on the speaker — they show engagement through body language (nodding, eye contact) and ask questions to check understanding. Planning your reply while someone talks is the opposite of active listening."}
  ],
  "island-11":[
    {q:"What does the nucleus of a cell do?",opts:["Produces energy for the cell","Controls the cell and contains DNA","Carries out photosynthesis","Provides structural support"],c:1,e:"The nucleus is the control centre. It contains the cell's DNA — the genetic instructions for everything the cell does."},
    {q:"MRS GREN is an acronym for:",opts:["Parts of the cell","The 7 characteristics of all living things","Types of reproduction","Parts of a food chain"],c:1,e:"MRS GREN: Movement, Respiration, Sensitivity, Growth, Reproduction, Excretion, Nutrition — the 7 life processes that ALL living things must carry out."},
    {q:"Which structure is found in plant cells but NOT in animal cells?",opts:["Nucleus","Cell membrane","Cytoplasm","Cell wall"],c:3,e:"Plant cells have: cell wall (cellulose), chloroplasts and a large vacuole — none found in animal cells. Both cell types share: nucleus, membrane, cytoplasm, and mitochondria."},
    {q:"What is the main function of mitochondria?",opts:["To carry out photosynthesis","To control cell division","To release energy through aerobic respiration","To provide structural support"],c:2,e:"Mitochondria are the 'powerhouses' of the cell — they carry out aerobic respiration, releasing energy from glucose. Cells with high energy demands (like muscle cells) have many mitochondria."},
    {q:"Which of the following is present in BOTH plant and animal cells?",opts:["Chloroplast","Cell wall","Large permanent vacuole","Cell membrane"],c:3,e:"Both plant and animal cells have: a cell membrane, nucleus, cytoplasm and mitochondria. Only plant cells additionally have chloroplasts, a large vacuole and a cell wall."},
    {q:"Diffusion is best described as:",opts:["Movement of particles from low to high concentration","Movement of particles from high to low concentration","Movement of water only, across a membrane","Particles moving only when heated"],c:1,e:"Diffusion is the net movement of particles from an area of high concentration to an area of low concentration — down the concentration gradient. It requires no energy (passive process)."},
    {q:"A group of similar cells working together to perform the same function is called a:",opts:["Organ","Organism","Tissue","Organ system"],c:2,e:"Organisation level: Cell → Tissue → Organ → Organ System → Organism. A tissue is a group of similar cells (e.g. muscle tissue). An organ is made of different tissues working together (e.g. the heart)."},
    {q:"Which specialised animal cell has NO nucleus?",opts:["Nerve cell","Sperm cell","Red blood cell","Muscle cell"],c:2,e:"Red blood cells have no nucleus — removing it allows more space for haemoglobin (the oxygen-carrying pigment). They also have a biconcave disc shape, maximising surface area for gas exchange."},
    {q:"The life process by which organisms remove waste products made by chemical reactions is:",opts:["Nutrition","Reproduction","Excretion","Sensitivity"],c:2,e:"Excretion = removal of metabolic waste products. In humans: CO₂ is excreted by the lungs; urea (from protein breakdown) is excreted by the kidneys as urine. Don't confuse with egestion (removing undigested food)."}
  ],
  "island-12":[
    {q:"In a food chain, what do the arrows represent?",opts:["What eats what","The direction of energy transfer","Where animals live","The relative sizes of organisms"],c:1,e:"Arrows show ENERGY flowing from one organism to the next. 'Grass → Rabbit → Fox' means energy passes from grass to rabbit to fox. The arrow points away from what is eaten."},
    {q:"A 'producer' in an ecosystem is:",opts:["An animal that hunts","An organism that makes its own food through photosynthesis","A decomposer breaking down dead matter","A secondary consumer"],c:1,e:"Producers (plants, algae) make their own food using sunlight (photosynthesis). They always come first in a food chain and provide energy for all other organisms."},
    {q:"What makes an adaptation different from just any feature?",opts:["It must be very unusual","It is an inherited feature that helps survival and reproduction","It only applies to animals in extreme environments","It is learned during the organism's lifetime"],c:1,e:"Adaptations are INHERITED (passed through genes) and specifically help an organism survive and reproduce in its particular environment. They are not learned or acquired during life."},
    {q:"Decomposers play an important role in ecosystems by:",opts:["Producing food through photosynthesis","Hunting and eating primary consumers","Breaking down dead organisms and recycling nutrients into the soil","Competing with producers for sunlight"],c:2,e:"Decomposers (bacteria and fungi) break down dead organisms and waste, releasing nutrients back into the soil. Without decomposers, nutrients would remain locked in dead material and plants could not grow."},
    {q:"If the population of a predator suddenly increases, what is MOST likely to happen to its prey population in the short term?",opts:["Increase, as prey breed faster in response","Decrease, as more prey are eaten","Stay exactly the same","Increase, as the predator brings new food"],c:1,e:"More predators = more predation = prey population decreases. This is predator-prey dynamics. The decrease in prey will eventually limit the predator population too (less food available), creating natural population cycles."},
    {q:"The term for all organisms of the SAME SPECIES living in the same area at the same time is:",opts:["Community","Ecosystem","Habitat","Population"],c:3,e:"A population is a group of the same species in one area. A community = all species in that area. An ecosystem = community + its physical environment. A habitat = the place where an organism lives."},
    {q:"A pyramid of biomass shows:",opts:["The number of organisms at each level of a food chain","The total mass of living organisms at each level of a food chain","The speed at which energy moves through a food chain","How tall each type of organism grows"],c:1,e:"A pyramid of biomass shows the total mass of living material at each trophic level. It is nearly always wider at the bottom because energy (and mass) is lost at each step — only about 10% is transferred to the next level."},
    {q:"Why does energy decrease at each level of a food chain?",opts:["Animals share energy with each other","Energy is used in movement, heat and growth — not all is passed to the next level","Energy is destroyed by predators","Producers store all energy permanently"],c:1,e:"At each trophic level, energy is used for the organism's own life processes (movement, respiration, keeping warm). Only about 10% of the energy is passed on to the next level. This is why food chains rarely have more than 4–5 links."},
    {q:"Which of these is a correct example of a food chain?",opts:["Fox → Rabbit → Grass","Sun → Grass → Rabbit → Fox","Grass ← Rabbit ← Fox","Rabbit → Grass → Fox → Sun"],c:1,e:"A food chain starts with a producer (plant) and arrows show the direction of energy transfer. Sun → Grass (producer) → Rabbit (primary consumer) → Fox (secondary consumer). The arrow always points FROM what is eaten TO what eats it."}
  ],
  "island-13":[
    {q:"In which state are particles furthest apart and moving fastest?",opts:["Solid","Liquid","Gas","Plasma"],c:2,e:"Gas particles are spread far apart and move very quickly in all directions. This is why gases fill any container and can be compressed."},
    {q:"When water freezes to form ice, this is called:",opts:["Melting","Condensing","Evaporating","Freezing/Solidifying"],c:3,e:"Freezing (or solidifying) = liquid → solid. Water freezes at 0°C. Melting is the reverse (solid → liquid). Evaporation = liquid → gas. Condensation = gas → liquid."},
    {q:"What happens to particles when a substance is heated?",opts:["They get heavier","They become larger in size","They gain energy and move faster","They disappear into the surroundings"],c:2,e:"Heating gives particles more KINETIC ENERGY — they vibrate more (solids) or move faster (liquids/gases). This causes expansion and eventually changes of state."},
    {q:"Water boils at:",opts:["0°C","37°C","100°C","212°C"],c:2,e:"Water boils (liquid → gas) at 100°C at normal atmospheric pressure. Water freezes at 0°C. These fixed temperatures are the boiling point and melting point of pure water — mixtures boil over a range rather than at a single temperature."},
    {q:"Diffusion is the movement of particles from:",opts:["Low concentration to high concentration","High concentration to low concentration","Solid to liquid only","Liquid to gas only"],c:1,e:"Diffusion = movement of particles down a concentration gradient (from where there are more particles to where there are fewer). It requires no energy (passive). Examples: smell spreading through a room, oxygen diffusing into the blood."},
    {q:"Evaporation is different from boiling because:",opts:["Evaporation only happens at one fixed temperature","Evaporation happens at the liquid's surface at any temperature; boiling happens throughout the liquid at its boiling point","Evaporation produces a solid","They are exactly the same process"],c:1,e:"Evaporation occurs at the surface when faster-moving particles escape — it can happen at any temperature. Boiling happens throughout the liquid at a specific temperature (the boiling point), producing bubbles of vapour inside the liquid."},
    {q:"A PURE substance has:",opts:["More than one type of particle mixed together","A fixed, sharp melting and boiling point","No colour","A very high melting point"],c:1,e:"A pure substance contains only one type of element or compound. It melts and boils at one sharp, fixed temperature. Impurities lower the melting point and broaden the melting range — this property is used in purity testing."},
    {q:"Sublimation is when a substance changes directly from:",opts:["Liquid to gas","Solid to liquid","Solid to gas without passing through the liquid state","Gas to solid"],c:2,e:"Sublimation = solid → gas (no liquid stage). Dry ice (solid CO₂) sublimates at room temperature. Iodine crystals also sublime when heated. The reverse (gas → solid directly) is called deposition."},
    {q:"Why can gases be compressed but solids cannot?",opts:["Gas particles are much smaller than solid particles","Gas particles have large empty spaces between them; solid particles are already tightly packed","Gas particles move faster so they push back","Solid particles are much heavier"],c:1,e:"In a gas, there is a large amount of empty space between particles — pressure pushes them closer together. In a solid, particles are already tightly packed and cannot be compressed much. This is why gases are used in pneumatic systems."}
  ],
  "island-14":[
    {q:"Forces are measured in:",opts:["Kilograms","Metres per second","Newtons","Joules"],c:2,e:"Forces are measured in Newtons (N), named after Sir Isaac Newton. Mass is in kg; speed in m/s; energy in Joules."},
    {q:"A book sits on a table without moving. The forces on it are:",opts:["Unbalanced","Zero","Balanced","Only gravity"],c:2,e:"Weight (gravity pulling down) equals the normal reaction force (table pushing up). Balanced forces mean NO change in motion — the book stays still."},
    {q:"Friction is a force that:",opts:["Always speeds objects up","Opposes motion between surfaces in contact","Only acts on objects in water","Pulls objects towards Earth"],c:1,e:"Friction acts in the OPPOSITE direction to motion. It can be useful (grip, brakes) or unhelpful (energy wasted in engines). It is reduced by smooth surfaces and lubrication."},
    {q:"An object has a mass of 5 kg. What is its weight on Earth? (g = 10 N/kg)",opts:["5 N","10 N","50 N","500 N"],c:2,e:"Weight = mass × gravitational field strength = 5 × 10 = 50 N. Mass is measured in kg and never changes. Weight is a force (Newtons) and changes with gravity. On the Moon (g = 1.6 N/kg), the same object would weigh only 8 N."},
    {q:"Newton's First Law states that an object will remain still or keep moving at constant speed unless:",opts:["It is very heavy","An unbalanced (resultant) force acts on it","It is on a smooth surface","It has been moving for a long time"],c:1,e:"Newton's First Law (Law of Inertia): objects resist changes to their motion. An unbalanced resultant force is needed to change speed or direction. This explains why you lurch forwards when a car brakes suddenly — your body 'wants' to keep moving."},
    {q:"A skydiver reaches terminal velocity. This means:",opts:["They have run out of fuel","Their weight equals air resistance, so they fall at a constant speed","They are accelerating at maximum rate","They have reached the ground"],c:1,e:"Terminal velocity = the constant maximum speed reached when the driving force (weight) equals the resistive force (air resistance). Net force = zero. Opening a parachute increases air resistance, reducing terminal velocity to a safe landing speed."},
    {q:"Speed is calculated using:",opts:["Speed = distance × time","Speed = time ÷ distance","Speed = distance ÷ time","Speed = force × mass"],c:2,e:"Speed = distance ÷ time (S = D ÷ T). If distance is in metres and time in seconds, speed is in m/s. Example: 100 m in 10 s → speed = 10 m/s. Use the SDT triangle to rearrange — cover the variable you want."},
    {q:"Gravity is best described as:",opts:["A contact force between touching surfaces","A non-contact attractive force between any two objects with mass","A force that only acts in water","A force that only Earth exerts"],c:1,e:"Gravity is a non-contact attractive force acting between ANY two objects with mass — no direct contact needed. The more massive the objects and the closer they are, the stronger the gravitational force. Earth's gravity gives objects a weight of 10 N per kg of mass."},
    {q:"A force of 20 N acts on an area of 4 m². What is the pressure?",opts:["80 Pa","5 Pa","16 Pa","24 Pa"],c:1,e:"Pressure = Force ÷ Area = 20 ÷ 4 = 5 Pa (Pascals, or N/m²). Greater area = lower pressure for the same force. This explains why snowshoes spread weight over a large area so you don't sink into snow."}
  ],
  "island-15":[
    {q:"Light travels:",opts:["In curved lines that bend around objects","In straight lines","In circles outward from its source","Randomly in all directions simultaneously"],c:1,e:"Light travels in straight lines (rectilinear propagation). This is why shadows have sharp edges and why you cannot see around corners."},
    {q:"Sound CANNOT travel through:",opts:["Water","Steel","A vacuum (space)","Air"],c:2,e:"Sound needs particles to vibrate through — it cannot travel through a vacuum (empty space). This is why space is completely silent, even near explosions."},
    {q:"Why do we see lightning before we hear thunder?",opts:["Lightning is always closer to us","Thunder is much quieter than lightning","Light travels much faster than sound","Thunder starts a few seconds after lightning"],c:2,e:"Light travels at 300,000 km/s; sound travels at ~340 m/s. Light reaches your eyes almost instantly; sound from the same event takes about 3 seconds per kilometre to arrive."},
    {q:"The law of reflection states that the angle of incidence equals the angle of reflection. Both angles are measured from:",opts:["The mirror surface","The normal — a line perpendicular to the mirror at the point of contact","The horizontal","The edge of the mirror"],c:1,e:"Both angles are measured from the NORMAL — an imaginary line at 90° to the mirror surface at the point where light hits. 'Angle of incidence = angle of reflection' is the law of reflection."},
    {q:"Refraction of light occurs when:",opts:["Light bounces off a mirror","Light bends as it crosses a boundary between two different materials","Light is absorbed by a coloured surface","Light travels through a vacuum"],c:1,e:"Refraction = bending of light as it crosses a boundary between two materials of different density (e.g. air to glass). The change in speed causes the direction to change. Refraction explains why objects look bent when partly submerged in water."},
    {q:"A sound with a HIGH frequency would be perceived as:",opts:["Very loud","Very quiet","High-pitched","Low-pitched"],c:2,e:"Frequency = number of vibrations per second (Hz). High frequency → high pitch (e.g. a whistle, ~2000 Hz). Low frequency → low pitch (e.g. a bass drum, ~50 Hz). Loudness is related to amplitude, not frequency."},
    {q:"How can you increase the LOUDNESS of a sound?",opts:["Increase its frequency","Increase its amplitude — make the vibrations bigger","Decrease its wavelength","Slow down the speed of sound"],c:1,e:"Loudness is determined by amplitude — the size of the vibration. Bigger amplitude = louder sound. Frequency controls pitch, not loudness. A whisper has small amplitude; a shout has large amplitude."},
    {q:"An object appears blue because it:",opts:["Emits blue light of its own","Reflects blue light and absorbs all other colours","Reflects all colours except blue","Transmits only blue light"],c:1,e:"Objects appear coloured because they reflect certain wavelengths and absorb others. A blue object absorbs all colours except blue, which it reflects into your eye. A white object reflects all colours; a black object absorbs all colours (reflecting none)."},
    {q:"Sound is produced by:",opts:["Bending of light waves","Vibrating objects transferring energy through a medium","A form of electromagnetic radiation","Light waves bouncing off surfaces"],c:1,e:"Sound is produced by vibrating objects (e.g. guitar strings, vocal cords, loudspeaker cones). The vibrations cause compressions and rarefactions in the surrounding medium, creating a longitudinal wave. Sound always needs a medium to travel through."}
  ],
  "island-16":[
    {q:"Who won the Battle of Hastings in 1066?",opts:["Harald Hardrada","Harold Godwinson","William of Normandy","Edgar Atheling"],c:2,e:"William of Normandy defeated Harold Godwinson on 14 October 1066. Harold was killed during the battle and William was crowned King of England on Christmas Day 1066."},
    {q:"The Domesday Book (1086) was primarily created to:",opts:["Record the battles of 1066","List all the churches in England","Survey land and wealth to calculate taxation","Record the names of all Norman soldiers"],c:2,e:"William ordered the Domesday Book to find out exactly who owned what, and therefore how much tax they owed. It also demonstrated his complete ownership of England."},
    {q:"Why did William build castles across England after 1066?",opts:["As places of worship for Normans","To provide homes for peasants","To control the English population and display Norman power","To serve as market places for trade"],c:2,e:"Castles were military strongholds that allowed William and his lords to dominate the surrounding area, respond quickly to rebellions, and demonstrate that the Normans were in charge."},
    {q:"Harold Godwinson was killed at the Battle of Hastings. According to tradition, how did he die?",opts:["He drowned crossing a river","He was struck by an arrow in the eye","He fell from his horse during a charge","He was poisoned before the battle"],c:1,e:"The Bayeux Tapestry appears to show Harold being struck in the eye by an arrow, though historians debate whether this is accurate. What is certain is that Harold died during the battle on 14 October 1066."},
    {q:"Which battle did Harold Godwinson fight just days BEFORE Hastings?",opts:["Battle of Stamford Bridge","Battle of Bosworth","Battle of Crécy","Battle of Bannockburn"],c:0,e:"Harold defeated the Viking king Harald Hardrada at Stamford Bridge (25 September 1066) in Yorkshire, then marched his exhausted army 250 miles south to face William at Hastings just 19 days later."},
    {q:"Who had the strongest claim to the English throne in 1066?",opts:["Only William of Normandy","Only Harold Godwinson","Only Harald Hardrada","All three claimants believed they had a legitimate right"],c:3,e:"William claimed Edward the Confessor had promised him the throne; Harold said Edward chose him on his deathbed; Harald Hardrada had a claim through earlier agreements with Scandinavian rulers. The disputed succession caused the crisis of 1066."},
    {q:"What was the 'Harrying of the North' (1069-70)?",opts:["A celebration to welcome Norman settlers","William's brutal destruction of northern England to crush rebellion","A trade agreement between York and London","A Viking raid on southern England"],c:1,e:"After northern rebellions, William ordered crops burned, livestock slaughtered, and villages destroyed across Yorkshire and beyond. Thousands died of famine. It was one of the most devastating acts of the Norman Conquest."},
    {q:"The Bayeux Tapestry is an important historical source because it:",opts:["Is a written account by Harold Godwinson","Provides a visual narrative of events leading up to and including the Battle of Hastings","Was created by William himself","Contains a map of Norman castles"],c:1,e:"The Bayeux Tapestry is an embroidered cloth nearly 70 metres long, depicting events from 1064 to the Battle of Hastings. Made soon after 1066, it is a unique visual primary source, though it tells the Norman version of events."},
    {q:"What language did the Norman rulers speak?",opts:["English","Latin only","Norman French","Welsh"],c:2,e:"The Normans spoke Norman French, which became the language of the royal court, law and government. English remained the language of the common people. Many modern English words (e.g. 'justice', 'parliament', 'castle') come from Norman French."},
    {q:"How did William reward his followers after the Conquest?",opts:["He paid them in gold coins","He granted them large estates of English land","He let them return to Normandy","He gave them positions in the English Church only"],c:1,e:"William redistributed almost all English land to his Norman supporters. By 1086 (Domesday Book), only about 5% of land was still held by English landowners. This massive transfer of wealth cemented Norman control over England."}
  ],
  "island-17":[
    {q:"In the feudal system, who was at the very top?",opts:["The Pope","Barons","Knights","The King"],c:3,e:"The King owned ALL land in England. He sat at the top of the feudal pyramid, granting land to lords in exchange for their loyalty and military service."},
    {q:"What was a 'tithe' in medieval England?",opts:["A type of early castle","A 10% tax paid to the Church","A medieval tournament","A peasant's plot of land"],c:1,e:"A tithe was one-tenth (10%) of a person's annual income or produce, compulsorily paid to the local church. This made the Church enormously wealthy."},
    {q:"What were motte-and-bailey castles?",opts:["Roman stone fortifications","Early Norman wooden castles built on a raised mound","Castles built entirely underground","Coastal forts facing France"],c:1,e:"Motte = a raised earthen mound with a wooden tower on top. Bailey = a fenced courtyard below. These were quick to build and appeared all over England after 1066. Later replaced by permanent stone keeps."},
    {q:"What was a villein in the feudal system?",opts:["A criminal or outlaw","A peasant legally tied to the land they worked on","A type of Norman knight","A travelling merchant"],c:1,e:"Villeins were unfree peasants bound to their lord's manor. They could not leave without permission and had to work on the lord's land for several days each week. In return, they were given strips of land to grow their own food."},
    {q:"In the open field system, peasants farmed their land in:",opts:["One large enclosed field","Scattered strips across two or three large fields","Private fenced gardens","Underground tunnels"],c:1,e:"The open field system divided land into two or three large fields, each containing strips belonging to different peasants. This shared risk — everyone had some good and some poor soil. Fields were rotated (one left fallow each year) to maintain fertility."},
    {q:"What did barons owe the king in return for their land?",opts:["Only prayer and church attendance","Military service — providing knights and soldiers when the king demanded","Free food and clothing","Nothing — the land was a free gift"],c:1,e:"The feudal system was based on land for loyalty. Barons (tenants-in-chief) held land from the king in exchange for providing armed knights for military service, paying taxes, and giving counsel. This was the basis of feudal obligation."},
    {q:"What was the role of the medieval parish priest?",opts:["To collect taxes for the king","To lead local worship, baptisms, marriages and burials","To command the army in battle","To teach reading to the nobility only"],c:1,e:"The parish priest served the local community — conducting church services, performing baptisms, marriages and funerals, and caring for the sick and poor. The Church touched every aspect of medieval life from birth to death."},
    {q:"Why were knights important in the feudal system?",opts:["They grew food for the whole kingdom","They provided military service to their lord in exchange for land","They collected tithes for the Church","They ran the king's treasury"],c:1,e:"Knights were trained warriors who served their lord (baron) in battle. In return they received a fief (land grant). A knight was expected to serve around 40 days of military service per year and follow the code of chivalry."},
    {q:"Which statement about medieval peasant life is TRUE?",opts:["Peasants could freely choose where to live and work","Most peasants never travelled more than a few miles from their village","Peasants owned the land they farmed","Peasants worked only in summer months"],c:1,e:"Most medieval peasants spent their entire lives within a few miles of their village. They worked the land year-round, paid rent and taxes to their lord, gave tithes to the Church, and had very little freedom or education."},
    {q:"What was the main purpose of the feudal system?",opts:["To promote democracy and voting","To provide military defence and maintain social order through a hierarchy of land and loyalty","To encourage trade between towns","To spread Christianity to other countries"],c:1,e:"The feudal system provided a structure for governing and defending England. The king granted land to barons, who provided knights, who protected peasants. Each level owed duties to the one above — creating a rigid but effective system of control."}
  ],
  "island-18":[
    {q:"What was the main cause of the Black Death?",opts:["A virus spread by dirty water","The bacterium Yersinia pestis, spread mainly by fleas on rats","Breathing cold air in winter","Eating rotten food"],c:1,e:"The Black Death was caused by the bacterium Yersinia pestis. Fleas on black rats carried the disease and transmitted it to humans through bites. Medieval people had no knowledge of bacteria."},
    {q:"Approximately what fraction of Europe's population died in the Black Death?",opts:["1 in 10","1 in 4","1 in 3","1 in 2"],c:2,e:"The Black Death killed roughly 30-50% of Europe's population between 1347 and 1351 — one of the greatest disasters in human history. In some areas, the death rate was even higher."},
    {q:"One long-term consequence of the Black Death was:",opts:["The Church became even more powerful","The feudal system became stronger","Peasants gained more bargaining power due to labour shortages","Trade permanently collapsed across Europe"],c:2,e:"With so many people dead, there were fewer workers. Surviving peasants could demand higher wages and better conditions. This eventually weakened the feudal system and contributed to the Peasants' Revolt of 1381."},
    {q:"The Black Death first reached England in:",opts:["1066","1215","1348","1381"],c:2,e:"The plague arrived in England in June 1348, probably through the port of Melcombe Regis (Weymouth) in Dorset. It had spread westward from Central Asia along trade routes, reaching Sicily in 1347."},
    {q:"Which group was wrongly blamed and persecuted during the Black Death?",opts:["Merchants","Knights","Jewish communities","Monks"],c:2,e:"Jewish communities across Europe were falsely accused of poisoning wells to spread the plague. Thousands were massacred in pogroms. This scapegoating reflected deep-seated prejudice rather than any evidence."},
    {q:"What were flagellants?",opts:["Doctors who treated plague victims","People who whipped themselves publicly to beg God's forgiveness","Priests who fled their parishes","Merchants who sold fake cures"],c:1,e:"Flagellants travelled in groups, publicly whipping themselves to atone for the sins they believed had caused God to send the plague. The Church eventually condemned them, but they reflected the desperation and religious fervour of the time."},
    {q:"Which medieval medical theory did doctors use to explain the Black Death?",opts:["Germ theory — bacteria spread disease","Miasma theory — bad air and foul smells caused illness","DNA mutations caused the plague","Radiation from the Sun"],c:1,e:"Medieval doctors believed in miasma theory — that disease was caused by poisonous vapours (bad air). They recommended carrying flowers or herbs to ward off the smell. The true cause (bacteria carried by fleas) was not understood until the late 19th century."},
    {q:"What were common symptoms of the bubonic plague?",opts:["Only a mild cough","Painful swellings (buboes) in the groin, armpits or neck, fever, and dark blotches on the skin","Broken bones and bruising","Blindness and deafness"],c:1,e:"Bubonic plague caused painful egg-sized swellings called buboes in the lymph nodes (groin, armpits, neck), high fever, headaches, and dark blotches on the skin from internal bleeding. Most victims died within a week."},
    {q:"How did the Black Death affect the power of the Church?",opts:["The Church became much stronger","Many people lost faith because the Church could not explain or stop the plague","The Church banned all religious services","The Pope fled to Africa"],c:1,e:"The Church's inability to prevent or cure the plague led many to question its authority. Priests who stayed to tend the sick often died themselves, while some fled their parishes. People's faith was shaken, weakening the Church's moral authority."},
    {q:"Why did the Black Death spread so quickly in medieval towns?",opts:["Towns were cold, which helped the disease survive","Towns were clean and well-ventilated","Towns were overcrowded with poor sanitation, and rats thrived in filthy conditions","Towns had excellent medical facilities that attracted the sick"],c:2,e:"Medieval towns were cramped and dirty — rubbish and sewage filled the streets, attracting rats whose fleas carried the plague. People lived close together, helping the disease spread rapidly. There was no understanding of hygiene or quarantine."}
  ],
  "island-19":[
    {q:"The Magna Carta was signed in:",opts:["1066","1215","1348","1381"],c:1,e:"King John signed the Magna Carta at Runnymede on 15 June 1215, under pressure from rebelling barons who marched on London."},
    {q:"What was the KEY principle of the Magna Carta?",opts:["The king could do whatever he wished","All land belonged to the Church","The king must obey the law","Peasants had the right to vote"],c:2,e:"For the first time, a king was made legally subject to the rule of law. Magna Carta stated that even the king had to follow agreed rules and could not imprison people without fair trial."},
    {q:"Simon de Montfort's Parliament (1265) was significant because:",opts:["Women gained the right to vote","It abolished the monarchy","It included knights and town representatives, not just barons","It replaced the Magna Carta entirely"],c:2,e:"De Montfort widened who was represented in Parliament — beyond just barons to include knights and burgesses (town representatives). This was a key step toward the modern democratic Parliament."},
    {q:"Where was the Magna Carta signed?",opts:["Westminster Abbey","The Tower of London","Runnymede, near the River Thames","Canterbury Cathedral"],c:2,e:"King John met the rebel barons at Runnymede, a meadow beside the Thames in Surrey, on 15 June 1215. The location was chosen as neutral ground between Windsor (the king's castle) and London (held by the barons)."},
    {q:"Why did the barons rebel against King John?",opts:["He refused to go on Crusade","He raised excessive taxes, lost lands in France, and abused his power","He tried to abolish Christianity","He gave too much land to peasants"],c:1,e:"John was deeply unpopular: he taxed heavily to fund failed wars in France, quarrelled with the Pope (leading to England being placed under interdict), and imprisoned barons without trial. The barons finally forced him to accept limits on royal power."},
    {q:"What does the principle of 'habeas corpus' in the Magna Carta protect?",opts:["The king's right to tax freely","The right not to be imprisoned without lawful judgement","The Church's right to collect tithes","Barons' right to own castles"],c:1,e:"Clause 39 of Magna Carta stated that no free man could be imprisoned, exiled, or harmed except by lawful judgement of his peers or the law of the land. This principle of habeas corpus remains a cornerstone of the legal system today."},
    {q:"What was the Model Parliament of 1295?",opts:["A parliament that only included the king","Edward I's parliament that included lords, clergy, knights AND burgesses","A parliament that met only once","A parliament that abolished the Magna Carta"],c:1,e:"Edward I summoned representatives from all social groups — lords, clergy, knights of the shires, and burgesses (townsmen). It became the 'model' for future parliaments because it represented a wider cross-section of society."},
    {q:"The Magna Carta originally applied to:",opts:["All people in England equally","Only the barons and free men, not villeins or women","Only the king","Only the Church"],c:1,e:"In 1215, the Magna Carta mainly protected the rights of barons and free men — a small minority. Villeins (unfree peasants) and women had no direct protection. Over centuries, its principles were reinterpreted to apply more broadly to everyone."},
    {q:"Why is the Magna Carta considered important today?",opts:["It is still the main law of England","Its principles of rule of law and limits on government power influenced constitutions worldwide","It created the first democracy in the world","It abolished the feudal system immediately"],c:1,e:"Although most of its 63 clauses are now obsolete, the Magna Carta established the principle that even rulers must obey the law. It influenced the US Constitution, the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, and remains a symbol of liberty and justice."},
    {q:"What is 'trial by jury', a concept linked to the Magna Carta?",opts:["The king personally judging every criminal case","Being judged by a group of ordinary people rather than by the king alone","A trial that can only happen in London","A trial conducted by the Church"],c:1,e:"Trial by jury means being judged by a group of one's peers (fellow citizens) rather than by a single ruler or judge. Magna Carta's insistence on lawful judgement helped establish this principle, which remains central to the justice system in England and many other countries."}
  ],
  "island-20":[
    {q:"When reading a 4-figure grid reference, which direction do you go first?",opts:["Up (northings first)","Diagonally","Along (eastings first)","It doesn't matter"],c:2,e:"'Along the corridor and up the stairs.' Go along the x-axis (eastings) first, then up the y-axis (northings). E.g. reference 2534: go along to 25, then up to 34."},
    {q:"Contour lines that are very close together on a map indicate:",opts:["A flat plain","A river valley","A steep slope","A forest"],c:2,e:"The closer contour lines are, the steeper the slope. Far apart = gentle slope. Circular contours closing in = a hill summit. They never cross."},
    {q:"On a 1:50,000 map, a measured distance of 2 cm represents:",opts:["50 metres","500 metres","1 kilometre","2 kilometres"],c:2,e:"1:50,000 means 1 cm = 50,000 cm = 500 m. Therefore 2 cm = 1,000 m = 1 km. Always convert cm to m or km when working with map scales."},
    {q:"A 6-figure grid reference is more precise than a 4-figure reference because it:",opts:["Uses a bigger map","Pinpoints a location within a 100m × 100m square rather than a 1km × 1km square","Only works on digital maps","Measures altitude as well as position"],c:1,e:"A 4-figure reference identifies a 1km × 1km square. A 6-figure reference subdivides that square into tenths, locating a point within a 100m × 100m area — ten times more precise. Essential for accurate navigation."},
    {q:"On an OS map, what does a blue line typically represent?",opts:["A motorway","A footpath","A river or stream","A railway line"],c:2,e:"Blue lines on Ordnance Survey maps represent water features — rivers, streams, canals and lakes. Roads are shown in various colours (motorways blue on some maps, A-roads red, B-roads orange). Footpaths are green dashed lines."},
    {q:"What is a 'cross-section' in map skills?",opts:["A view of the landscape from above","A side-on view showing the shape of the land between two points","A close-up of a map symbol","A type of compass bearing"],c:1,e:"A cross-section is drawn using contour lines to show what the landscape looks like from the side between two points. You plot the height of each contour line on graph paper to reveal hills, valleys, and slopes."},
    {q:"The compass direction exactly between North and East is:",opts:["North-West","South-East","North-East","East-North"],c:2,e:"The eight main compass points are: N, NE, E, SE, S, SW, W, NW. North-East (NE) is at 045° — halfway between North (000°) and East (090°). Using compass directions accurately is essential for describing locations and giving directions."},
    {q:"On an OS map, contour lines that form a 'V' shape pointing uphill indicate:",opts:["A flat plateau","A valley or river channel","A hilltop","A cliff edge"],c:1,e:"When contour lines form V-shapes pointing towards higher ground, they indicate a valley. Rivers flow along the bottom of valleys, so the V points upstream. This is a common exam question — remember 'V points to the source'."},
    {q:"What does 'relief' mean in geography?",opts:["A type of weather pattern","The height and shape of the land surface","The distance between two cities","A method of farming"],c:1,e:"Relief describes the shape of the land — its height, steepness, and features like hills, valleys, ridges, and plains. It is shown on maps using contour lines. High relief means rugged, mountainous terrain; low relief means flat land."},
    {q:"An Ordnance Survey map uses the symbol of a small blue 'P' inside a box. This represents:",opts:["A post office","A parking area","A police station","A public telephone"],c:1,e:"The blue 'P' symbol indicates a parking area. Learning common OS map symbols is essential for fieldwork and map reading. Other common symbols include a cross for a church with a tower, a tent for a campsite, and 'PH' for a public house."}
  ],
  "island-21":[
    {q:"What is the key difference between weather and climate?",opts:["Weather is long-term; climate is daily","They mean the same thing","Weather is short-term daily conditions; climate is the 30+ year average","Climate only measures temperature"],c:2,e:"'Climate is what you expect; weather is what you get.' Weather changes day-to-day; climate is the long-term average pattern for a region (measured over at least 30 years)."},
    {q:"Which instrument measures rainfall?",opts:["Thermometer","Barometer","Anemometer","Rain gauge"],c:3,e:"A rain gauge collects rainfall and measures it in millimetres (mm). Thermometer = temperature, barometer = air pressure, anemometer = wind speed."},
    {q:"The UK's mild, wet climate is mainly caused by:",opts:["Being close to the equator","Prevailing winds from North Africa","South-westerly winds from the Atlantic and the North Atlantic Drift","Being a very large continent"],c:2,e:"South-westerly winds bring warm, moist Atlantic air across the UK. The North Atlantic Drift (a warm ocean current) keeps UK winters warmer than expected for its latitude."},
    {q:"A barometer measures:",opts:["Wind speed","Rainfall","Atmospheric (air) pressure","Temperature"],c:2,e:"A barometer measures atmospheric pressure in millibars (mb). Rising pressure usually means fair weather; falling pressure often signals rain or storms. Normal sea-level pressure is about 1013 mb."},
    {q:"An anemometer is used to measure:",opts:["Air pressure","Wind speed","Humidity","Cloud cover"],c:1,e:"An anemometer has spinning cups that rotate faster as wind speed increases. Wind speed is measured in knots, mph, or m/s. A wind vane shows wind DIRECTION — the two instruments are often used together."},
    {q:"What is a 'depression' in weather terms?",opts:["A period of very hot weather","An area of low atmospheric pressure that brings cloud, wind and rain","A gap between two mountains","A long dry spell"],c:1,e:"A depression is a low-pressure weather system. Air rises at the centre, cools, and condenses to form clouds and rain. Depressions bring the UK's typical unsettled, wet and windy weather, especially in autumn and winter."},
    {q:"An air mass is best described as:",opts:["A single cloud formation","A large body of air with relatively uniform temperature and moisture","The wind blowing from the sea","The jet stream high in the atmosphere"],c:1,e:"Air masses are huge bodies of air that take on the temperature and humidity of the region where they form. The UK is affected by five main air masses: Tropical Maritime, Tropical Continental, Polar Maritime, Polar Continental, and Arctic Maritime."},
    {q:"A warm front on a weather map occurs when:",opts:["Cold air pushes under warm air","Warm air rises over retreating cold air, bringing steady rain","Two air masses move apart","Air pressure suddenly increases"],c:1,e:"At a warm front, advancing warm air gently rises over the denser cold air ahead of it. This produces a wide band of cloud and prolonged, steady rain. On weather maps, warm fronts are shown with red semicircles."},
    {q:"Cloud cover in the UK is measured in:",opts:["Percentages","Degrees","Oktas (eighths of the sky covered)","Millibars"],c:2,e:"Cloud cover is measured in oktas — the number of eighths of the sky covered by cloud. 0 oktas = clear sky, 4 oktas = half covered, 8 oktas = completely overcast. Observers estimate this by looking at the sky."},
    {q:"Why does the west of the UK generally receive MORE rainfall than the east?",opts:["The east is closer to the sea","Moist Atlantic air rises over western mountains (relief rainfall), losing moisture before reaching the east","The east has more vegetation that absorbs rain","Eastern winds are warmer"],c:1,e:"Prevailing south-westerly winds carry moist air from the Atlantic. When this air hits western uplands (e.g. Lake District, Snowdonia), it is forced to rise, cool, and release rainfall. By the time air reaches the east, it has lost much of its moisture — this is the 'rain shadow' effect."}
  ],
  "island-22":[
    {q:"Which process involves the river wearing away its channel?",opts:["Deposition","Transportation","Flooding","Erosion"],c:3,e:"Erosion = wearing away of material. River erosion processes include hydraulic action (force of water), abrasion (sediment scraping) and solution (dissolving rocks). Greatest in the upper course."},
    {q:"A meander forms because:",opts:["The river speeds up in a straight channel","Water flows faster on the outside of bends (eroding) and slower on the inside (depositing)","Heavy rainfall increases the river's volume","The river's source is at high altitude"],c:1,e:"Faster water outside → erosion → river cliff. Slower water inside → deposition → slip-off slope. Over time the bend is exaggerated. Eventually it can be cut off as an oxbow lake."},
    {q:"Deposition occurs when a river:",opts:["Speeds up on a steep slope","Increases its erosion rate","Loses energy and slows down","Reaches its source in the mountains"],c:2,e:"When a river slows down (loses energy), it can no longer carry its load and drops (deposits) it. This happens on the inside of bends, on floodplains, and at the river's mouth."},
    {q:"What is hydraulic action?",opts:["Rocks scraping against the river bed","The force of water crashing against the banks and bed, compressing air into cracks","Dissolving of rocks by acidic water","Rocks smashing into each other in the river"],c:1,e:"Hydraulic action is the sheer force of water hitting the river banks and bed. Water is forced into cracks, compressing air inside. When the water retreats, the air expands, weakening and breaking the rock over time."},
    {q:"How does an oxbow lake form?",opts:["A river cuts through a floodplain in a straight line","The neck of a meander is eroded until the river cuts through, leaving the old bend isolated","A dam blocks the river flow","Flooding creates a permanent lake"],c:1,e:"Over time, erosion on the outer banks narrows the neck of a meander. During a flood, the river breaks through the narrow neck, taking the shorter, straighter route. The old meander loop is abandoned and becomes an oxbow lake."},
    {q:"Attrition is a process of erosion where:",opts:["Water dissolves chemicals in the rock","The river bed is scraped by rocks","Rocks carried by the river collide and break into smaller, rounder pieces","Water crashes into the river bank"],c:2,e:"Attrition occurs when rocks and pebbles in the river bump into each other, gradually breaking down into smaller, smoother, rounder particles. This is why pebbles in the lower course are smaller and more rounded than jagged rocks in the upper course."},
    {q:"What is a floodplain?",opts:["The steep valley sides of the upper course","The wide, flat area of land either side of a river in the lower course, formed by repeated flooding","A dam built to prevent flooding","The area where a river begins"],c:1,e:"The floodplain is the flat land on either side of a river in its lower course. When a river floods, water spreads across the floodplain, depositing layers of fertile silt (alluvium). Floodplains are ideal for farming but risky for building."},
    {q:"A waterfall forms when a river flows over a band of:",opts:["Soft rock only","Hard rock overlying softer rock, which erodes faster underneath","Flat, even ground","Sand and gravel"],c:1,e:"A waterfall forms where hard rock sits on top of softer rock. The soft rock underneath erodes more quickly, creating an overhang. Eventually the unsupported hard rock collapses, and the waterfall retreats upstream, carving a gorge."},
    {q:"The long profile of a river shows:",opts:["A bird's-eye view of the river's path","How the gradient of the river changes from source to mouth","The width of the river at each point","The amount of rainfall the river receives"],c:1,e:"The long profile is a side view showing how the river's gradient (steepness) changes along its course. It is steep and irregular in the upper course, becoming gentler and smoother towards the mouth. The shape is typically concave."},
    {q:"Solution as a river process involves:",opts:["Water physically breaking rocks apart","Dissolved minerals being carried invisibly in the water","Large boulders rolling along the river bed","Fine particles floating in the water"],c:1,e:"Solution (also called corrosion) is a chemical process where slightly acidic river water dissolves soluble minerals from rocks (especially limestone and chalk). The dissolved material is carried invisibly in the water — you cannot see it. It is also a form of transportation."}
  ],
  "island-23":[
    {q:"Population density is calculated as:",opts:["Population × Area","Area ÷ Population","Population ÷ Area (km²)","Population + Area"],c:2,e:"Population density = population ÷ area (km²). The answer is in 'people per km²'. Example: 1,000,000 people in 500 km² = 2,000 people/km²."},
    {q:"Which factor would DISCOURAGE people from settling in an area?",opts:["Flat, fertile land","Reliable water supply","Steep mountainous terrain with a harsh climate","Proximity to a major road"],c:2,e:"Steep, mountainous areas are difficult to build on, hard to farm, and often have extreme weather. Historically, people settled on flat, sheltered land near fresh water."},
    {q:"Urbanisation refers to:",opts:["People moving from cities to the countryside","The growth of farming areas","The increasing proportion of people living in urban areas","The decline of city populations"],c:2,e:"Urbanisation = more people moving to and living in cities/towns, increasing the urban proportion of the population. It is driven by pull factors in cities (jobs, services) and push factors from rural areas."},
    {q:"A 'push factor' in migration is:",opts:["Something that attracts people to a new place","Something that forces or encourages people to leave their current location","A type of transport used by migrants","A government policy to increase population"],c:1,e:"Push factors drive people away from an area — examples include poverty, lack of jobs, natural disasters, war, poor services, or crop failure. Pull factors attract people TO a new area — jobs, better education, safety, or higher wages."},
    {q:"In a settlement hierarchy, which is the LARGEST type of settlement?",opts:["Hamlet","Village","Town","City"],c:3,e:"The settlement hierarchy from smallest to largest: isolated dwelling → hamlet → village → town → city → conurbation. Larger settlements have more services, a bigger population, and a wider sphere of influence."},
    {q:"The UK census is conducted every:",opts:["5 years","10 years","20 years","50 years"],c:1,e:"The UK census takes place every 10 years (most recently 2021). It counts the population and collects data on housing, employment, ethnicity, health, and more. This data helps the government plan services like schools, hospitals, and transport."},
    {q:"Rural-urban migration is most rapid in:",opts:["HICs (High Income Countries) like the UK","LICs (Low Income Countries) and NEEs (Newly Emerging Economies)","Countries with very cold climates","Countries with small populations"],c:1,e:"Rural-urban migration is fastest in LICs and NEEs, where people move from the countryside to cities seeking jobs and better services. The UK urbanised mainly during the Industrial Revolution (1700s-1800s). Many LICs are experiencing this process now."},
    {q:"A 'pull factor' that attracts people to cities is:",opts:["Drought and crop failure","Lack of schools","Better job opportunities and higher wages","War and conflict"],c:2,e:"Pull factors attract people to urban areas. Common pull factors include: better job opportunities, higher wages, access to education and healthcare, entertainment, and the perception of a better quality of life. These contrast with rural push factors like poverty and limited services."},
    {q:"What is a sparsely populated area?",opts:["An area with many people per km²","An area with very few people per km²","A city centre","An area with lots of buildings"],c:1,e:"Sparsely populated = few people per km² (low population density). Examples include the Scottish Highlands, the Sahara Desert, and the Amazon Rainforest. These areas are often mountainous, very hot, very cold, or difficult to farm."},
    {q:"Counter-urbanisation is the process of:",opts:["More people moving into cities","People moving from urban areas to rural areas","Building new factories in city centres","Increasing population density in towns"],c:1,e:"Counter-urbanisation is the movement of people OUT of cities to the surrounding countryside and villages. It is common in HICs and is driven by factors like congestion, pollution, improved transport links, and the desire for a quieter lifestyle. It can cause house prices in rural areas to rise."}
  ],
  "island-24":[
    {q:"Simplify the ratio 18 : 24.",opts:["9 : 12","3 : 4","6 : 8","2 : 3"],c:1,e:"HCF of 18 and 24 = 6. Divide both by 6: 18÷6=3, 24÷6=4. Ratio = 3:4. Always divide by the HIGHEST common factor."},
    {q:"Share £60 in the ratio 1 : 3.",opts:["£15 and £45","£20 and £40","£10 and £50","£30 and £30"],c:0,e:"Total parts = 1+3=4. One part = £60÷4=£15. Shares: 1×£15=£15 and 3×£15=£45. Check: £15+£45=£60 ✓"},
    {q:"A train travels 240 km in 3 hours. What is its average speed?",opts:["720 km/h","80 km/h","60 km/h","243 km/h"],c:1,e:"Speed = Distance ÷ Time = 240 ÷ 3 = 80 km/h. Remember the SDT triangle: cover the quantity you want to find."}
  ],
  "island-25":[
    {q:"Shakespeare's plays were performed at:",opts:["The Crystal Palace","The Globe Theatre","Westminster Abbey","The Royal Albert Hall"],c:1,e:"The Globe Theatre, built in 1599 on the South Bank of the Thames, was where most of Shakespeare's plays were first performed. It was open-air and circular."},
    {q:"In the PEE paragraph structure, what does the second 'E' stand for?",opts:["Evidence","Example","Explanation","Extract"],c:2,e:"PEE = Point, Evidence, Explanation. The Explanation shows HOW your evidence supports your point — it's the most important and often weakest part of students' writing."},
    {q:"In the Globe Theatre, 'groundlings' were:",opts:["Wealthy nobles in the upper galleries","The backstage crew and stagehands","Audience members who stood in the yard for the cheapest price","The actors who played villains"],c:2,e:"Groundlings paid 1 penny to stand in the yard (the pit) around the stage. It was the cheapest option and they had no roof or seats. They were very vocal — booing bad performances!"}
  ],
  "island-26":[
    {q:"Which text type would MOST likely use the '5 Ws' structure (who, what, where, when, why)?",opts:["A personal diary","A news article","A gothic short story","A Shakespearean soliloquy"],c:1,e:"News articles answer the 5 Ws in their opening paragraph so readers quickly understand the key facts. This is called the 'inverted pyramid' structure — most important information first."},
    {q:"'Surely we can do better than this?' is an example of:",opts:["Alliteration","A rhetorical question","A metaphor","An anecdote"],c:1,e:"A rhetorical question is asked for effect — the writer doesn't expect an actual answer. It engages the reader and implies the answer is obvious, making the point more persuasively."},
    {q:"AFOREST is a memory aid for persuasive techniques. What does the 'F' stand for?",opts:["Figurative language","Formal register","Facts and statistics","Feelings"],c:2,e:"AFOREST: Anecdote, Fact/statistics, Opinion, Rhetorical question, Emotive language, Statistics, Triplet (rule of three). Facts add credibility and make an argument harder to dismiss."}
  ],
  "island-27":[
    {q:"'The storm raged as she learned of her father's death.' This is an example of:",opts:["Alliteration","Onomatopoeia","Pathetic fallacy","Hyperbole"],c:2,e:"Pathetic fallacy uses weather/environment to reflect emotion or atmosphere. The storm mirrors the character's grief and shock. It's a powerful form of 'show, don't tell'."},
    {q:"Which of these is a feature of Gothic fiction?",opts:["Bright, cheerful settings","A focus on scientific progress","Dark settings, supernatural elements and an atmosphere of dread","Simple, everyday characters"],c:2,e:"Gothic fiction relies on atmosphere: dark/ruined settings, the supernatural, death, madness and mystery. It is designed to create unease and dread in the reader."},
    {q:"A myth typically differs from a legend because a myth:",opts:["Features only human heroes","Is based on real historical events","Explains natural phenomena and features gods","Is always shorter"],c:2,e:"Myths explain the world — why seasons change, how humans got fire, etc. — and feature divine beings. Legends are based (loosely) on historical figures and celebrate human courage or heroism."}
  ],
  "island-28":[
    {q:"Which of these is an example of ASEXUAL reproduction?",opts:["A cat giving birth to kittens","A strawberry plant producing runners","A human embryo developing","Pollination in a flower"],c:1,e:"Strawberry runners are an example of asexual reproduction — one parent produces identical offspring (clones). No fertilisation is involved. Other examples: bulbs, binary fission in bacteria."},
    {q:"In insect-pollinated flowers, pollen is transferred from the:",opts:["Stigma to the anther","Petal to the ovule","Anther to the stigma","Root to the stem"],c:2,e:"Pollen is produced in the anther (male part) and must reach the stigma (female part) for pollination to occur. In insect pollination, insects carry the sticky pollen between flowers."},
    {q:"Which hormone triggers the main changes in females during puberty?",opts:["Testosterone","Insulin","Adrenaline","Oestrogen"],c:3,e:"Oestrogen is the main female sex hormone, produced by the ovaries. It triggers puberty changes including breast development, the menstrual cycle beginning, and growth. Testosterone is the main male sex hormone."},
    {q:"In flowering plants, fertilisation occurs when:",opts:["A bee lands on the flower","Pollen lands on the stigma","The pollen tube delivers the male gamete to the ovule, where it fuses with the female gamete","Seeds are dispersed by the wind"],c:2,e:"Pollination = transfer of pollen to the stigma. Fertilisation = fusion of male gamete (from pollen) with female gamete (in the ovule). After pollination, the pollen tube grows down through the style to the ovule where fertilisation takes place."},
    {q:"In humans, fertilisation most commonly occurs in the:",opts:["Uterus (womb)","Vagina","Oviduct (fallopian tube)","Ovary"],c:2,e:"Fertilisation typically occurs in the oviduct (fallopian tube), where the egg meets sperm shortly after ovulation. The fertilised egg (zygote) then travels to the uterus and implants in the lining to develop."},
    {q:"Seed dispersal is important because it:",opts:["Provides water for germination","Prevents competition between parent plant and offspring for light, water and minerals","Protects seeds from insects","Allows seeds to grow faster"],c:1,e:"Seed dispersal moves seeds away from the parent plant, reducing competition. Methods include: wind (dandelion, sycamore), animals (berries, burrs), water (coconuts), and explosive mechanisms (peas)."},
    {q:"During the menstrual cycle, ovulation refers to:",opts:["The shedding of the uterus lining","The release of a mature egg from the ovary","The implantation of a fertilised egg","The production of progesterone by the uterus"],c:1,e:"Ovulation = the release of a mature egg from the ovary, usually around day 14 of a 28-day cycle. If fertilised, the egg implants in the uterus lining. If not, the lining breaks down and menstruation occurs."},
    {q:"Which is an advantage of SEXUAL reproduction over ASEXUAL reproduction?",opts:["It is faster","It produces more offspring","It creates genetic variation, important for evolution and adapting to change","It requires only one parent"],c:2,e:"Sexual reproduction produces offspring with a combination of both parents' genes, creating genetic variation. This variation means some individuals may cope better with disease or environmental change — important for the species' long-term survival. Asexual reproduction is faster but produces clones with no variation."},
    {q:"In a flower, which part produces pollen?",opts:["Stigma","Ovary","Petal","Anther"],c:3,e:"The anther (at the top of the stamen — the male part of the flower) produces pollen grains containing the male gametes. The stigma is the female receptor where pollen lands. The ovary contains the ovules (female gametes)."}
  ],
  "island-29":[
    {q:"Water (H₂O) is best described as:",opts:["An element","A compound","A mixture","An atom"],c:1,e:"Water is a COMPOUND — it contains two different elements (hydrogen and oxygen) that are chemically bonded together. It cannot be separated by physical means — you need electrolysis to split it."},
    {q:"In the Periodic Table, elements in the same GROUP have:",opts:["The same number of protons","The same mass number","Similar chemical properties","The same number of neutrons"],c:2,e:"Elements in the same group have the same number of electrons in their outer shell, which gives them similar chemical behaviour. E.g. all Group 1 metals react vigorously with water."},
    {q:"Which separation technique would you use to get salt back from salt water?",opts:["Filtration","Chromatography","Evaporation","Distillation"],c:2,e:"Evaporation: heat the salt water so the water evaporates, leaving the salt behind. Filtration separates insoluble solids. Distillation gives you pure water. Chromatography separates dissolved dyes."},
    {q:"Which of the following is a PHYSICAL change rather than a chemical change?",opts:["Iron rusting","Wood burning","Sugar dissolving in water","Baking a cake"],c:2,e:"Dissolving is a physical change — no new substance is made and it is reversible (evaporate the water and you get the sugar back). Rusting, burning and baking are chemical changes — new substances form and the change is hard to reverse."},
    {q:"In the reaction: magnesium + hydrochloric acid → magnesium chloride + hydrogen, the REACTANTS are:",opts:["Magnesium chloride and hydrogen","Magnesium and hydrochloric acid","Magnesium and magnesium chloride","Hydrochloric acid and hydrogen"],c:1,e:"Reactants are the substances that react together (on the left of the arrow). Products are the new substances made (on the right). Reactants: magnesium + hydrochloric acid; Products: magnesium chloride + hydrogen."},
    {q:"The chemical symbol for iron is:",opts:["Ir","I","Fe","In"],c:2,e:"Iron's symbol is Fe, from its Latin name 'Ferrum'. Other symbols from Latin: gold = Au, silver = Ag, sodium = Na, potassium = K, lead = Pb. About 20 elements have symbols that don't match their English names."},
    {q:"Carbon dioxide (CO₂) contains:",opts:["One element only","Two different elements","Three elements","Two compounds"],c:1,e:"CO₂ = carbon (C) and oxygen (O) — two different elements chemically combined. The subscript '2' means 2 oxygen atoms per molecule. CO₂ is a compound, not a mixture, because the elements are chemically bonded."},
    {q:"Which of the following is a MIXTURE?",opts:["Sodium chloride (table salt)","Water (H₂O)","Air","Carbon dioxide"],c:2,e:"Air is a mixture — mainly nitrogen (~78%) and oxygen (~21%), plus argon, CO₂ and other gases. Each gas keeps its own properties and they can be separated physically. NaCl, water and CO₂ are pure compounds."},
    {q:"Where in the Periodic Table are metals mostly found?",opts:["On the right-hand side only","On the left and centre","Only in Group 7","Only in Group 1"],c:1,e:"Metals are on the LEFT and CENTRE of the Periodic Table. Non-metals are on the RIGHT. A zigzag line (the metalloid staircase) separates them. Most elements (~80%) are metals — they are typically shiny, conduct electricity, and have high melting points."}
  ],
  "island-30":[
    {q:"A ball held above the ground has which type of energy?",opts:["Kinetic","Chemical","Gravitational potential","Elastic potential"],c:2,e:"Any object raised above the ground has gravitational potential energy (GPE) stored in it due to its position. When released, GPE transfers to kinetic energy as it falls."},
    {q:"Heat transfer through a solid material is called:",opts:["Convection","Radiation","Conduction","Evaporation"],c:2,e:"Conduction occurs in solids — vibrating particles pass energy along the material. Metals are excellent conductors. Convection requires a fluid (liquid or gas). Radiation requires no medium at all."},
    {q:"The Law of Conservation of Energy states that energy:",opts:["Is created when fuels burn","Is destroyed when objects cool down","Cannot be created or destroyed, only transferred","Disappears as 'waste heat'"],c:2,e:"Energy is always conserved — the total energy in a closed system stays constant. What we call 'wasted' energy (usually heat) hasn't disappeared — it's just transferred to the surroundings in a less useful form."},
    {q:"What is the unit of energy?",opts:["Newton (N)","Watt (W)","Joule (J)","Pascal (Pa)"],c:2,e:"Energy is measured in Joules (J). Power (energy transferred per second) is measured in Watts (W). 1 Watt = 1 Joule per second. Named after James Prescott Joule and James Watt respectively."},
    {q:"A light bulb transfers 100 J of electrical energy: 20 J becomes useful light. What is its efficiency?",opts:["20%","80%","100%","5%"],c:0,e:"Efficiency = (useful energy output ÷ total energy input) × 100 = (20 ÷ 100) × 100 = 20%. The remaining 80 J is wasted as heat. LED bulbs are far more efficient (~90%) than old incandescent bulbs (~10%)."},
    {q:"In a room heated by a radiator, convection currents form because:",opts:["All air moves directly towards the radiator","Hot air rises (less dense) and cool air sinks (denser), creating a circular current","Air moves only horizontally","Air stays still once warmed"],c:1,e:"Convection: the radiator heats nearby air → air expands, becomes less dense → rises. Cooler, denser air flows in to replace it, gets heated, and also rises. This circular convection current gradually warms the whole room."},
    {q:"Thermal radiation transfers heat differently from conduction and convection because it:",opts:["Requires particles to pass energy along","Can only occur in metals","Does not require a medium — it travels through a vacuum as infrared waves","Only heats dark objects"],c:2,e:"Radiation transfers heat as infrared electromagnetic waves — it requires no medium and can travel through a vacuum (empty space). This is how the Sun's heat reaches Earth across 150 million km of empty space."},
    {q:"GPE = mass × gravitational field strength × height. An object of mass 2 kg is raised 5 m. What is its GPE? (g = 10 N/kg)",opts:["10 J","25 J","100 J","1 J"],c:2,e:"GPE = m × g × h = 2 × 10 × 5 = 100 J. The unit is Joules. On the Moon (g = 1.6 N/kg), the same object at the same height would store only 2 × 1.6 × 5 = 16 J of GPE."},
    {q:"A Sankey diagram is used to:",opts:["Show the speed of energy transfer","Show how input energy is split into useful output and wasted energy","Calculate the mass of objects","Draw electrical circuit diagrams"],c:1,e:"Sankey diagrams use arrows whose WIDTH represents the amount of energy. Useful energy output and wasted energy (usually heat) are shown as separate branches. The wider the arrow, the more energy it represents — efficiency is immediately visible."}
  ],
  "island-38":[
    {q:"In an experiment testing how temperature affects enzyme activity, the temperature is the:",opts:["Dependent variable","Control variable","Independent variable","Constant"],c:2,e:"The independent variable is what you deliberately change. The dependent variable (rate of reaction) is what you measure. Control variables (pH, enzyme concentration) are kept the same to ensure a fair test."},
    {q:"A fair test means that:",opts:["The results are shared equally between all students","Only the independent variable is changed while all other variables are controlled","All variables are changed at the same time","The experiment is only repeated once"],c:1,e:"In a fair test, only ONE variable (the independent variable) is changed. Everything else that could affect the result (control variables) is kept constant. This ensures any change in the dependent variable is caused by the independent variable alone."},
    {q:"Which unit is used to measure force?",opts:["Kilogram (kg)","Joule (J)","Newton (N)","Metre per second (m/s)"],c:2,e:"Forces are measured in Newtons (N), named after Isaac Newton. Mass is in kilograms, energy in joules, and speed in metres per second. Always check units match in science calculations."},
    {q:"What is a hypothesis?",opts:["A final conclusion drawn from results","A testable prediction based on scientific reasoning, stating what you expect and why","A type of measurement","A list of equipment needed for an experiment"],c:1,e:"A hypothesis is a testable prediction made BEFORE an investigation. It states what you think will happen AND explains why. Example: 'I predict increasing temperature will increase enzyme activity because enzymes work faster when particles have more kinetic energy.'"},
    {q:"Why should experiments be REPEATED (measurements taken multiple times)?",opts:["To use more equipment","To make the experiment look more professional","To identify anomalous results and calculate a more reliable mean","To change the independent variable more times"],c:2,e:"Repeating measurements helps identify anomalous results (ones that don't fit the pattern) and allows calculation of a mean. More repeats = more reliable data. A result found once might be due to error; a consistent result is more trustworthy."},
    {q:"An anomalous result is one that:",opts:["Is higher than all others","Is exactly the same as all other results","Does not fit the pattern or trend of the other data","Comes from a very accurate instrument"],c:2,e:"An anomalous result is significantly different from the other values and doesn't fit the general trend. It may result from human error, equipment malfunction, or a genuine unusual event. Anomalous results are usually excluded when calculating a mean."},
    {q:"In a graph, the INDEPENDENT variable is plotted on:",opts:["The y-axis (vertical)","The x-axis (horizontal)","Either axis — it doesn't matter","The line itself"],c:1,e:"Convention: independent variable (what you change) → x-axis (horizontal); dependent variable (what you measure) → y-axis (vertical). Memory aid: 'I control x; I measure y.' Always label axes with the variable name AND units."},
    {q:"A result is described as 'accurate' if it is:",opts:["Very consistent when repeated","Close to the true or accepted value","Measured with an expensive instrument","The same as another student's result"],c:1,e:"Accuracy = how close a measurement is to the true value. Precision = how consistent repeated measurements are with each other. You can be precise but inaccurate (consistent results, but all wrong due to systematic error)."},
    {q:"What does a flame hazard symbol on a chemical label indicate?",opts:["The substance is toxic if swallowed","The substance is flammable — it can catch fire easily","The substance is corrosive","The substance is an oxidiser"],c:1,e:"The flame symbol = flammable. Keep away from naked flames and sparks. Other key symbols: skull and crossbones = toxic/very toxic; corrosion symbol = corrosive (damages skin/eyes); exclamation mark = harmful or irritant."}
  ],
  "island-39":[
    {q:"In a series circuit with two identical bulbs, if one bulb is removed:",opts:["The other bulb glows brighter","Both bulbs go out","The other bulb stays the same brightness","Only the bulb closer to the battery stays on"],c:1,e:"In a series circuit, all components are in one loop. If any component is removed or breaks, the circuit is incomplete and current cannot flow — all bulbs go out. This is why old-fashioned Christmas light strings failed completely when one bulb blew."},
    {q:"Iron filings arranged around a bar magnet show:",opts:["The weight distribution of the magnet","The magnetic field lines from north to south pole","Where the magnet's atoms are located","The temperature distribution in the magnet"],c:1,e:"Iron filings align with the magnetic field lines, which travel from the north pole to the south pole outside the magnet. Field lines are closest together at the poles, showing where the magnetic force is strongest."},
    {q:"An electromagnet is different from a permanent magnet because:",opts:["Electromagnets are always stronger","Electromagnets can be switched on and off by controlling the electric current","Permanent magnets can attract all metals","Electromagnets only work in water"],c:1,e:"Electromagnets are created by passing a current through a coil of wire. When the current is switched off, the magnetism disappears. This makes them very useful in electric motors, MRI scanners and scrapyard cranes."},
    {q:"Ohm's Law: if the voltage across a resistor is 12 V and its resistance is 4 Ω, what is the current?",opts:["48 A","3 A","0.33 A","8 A"],c:1,e:"V = I × R → rearrange: I = V ÷ R = 12 ÷ 4 = 3 A. Voltage in Volts (V), current in Amperes (A), resistance in Ohms (Ω). Always rearrange the equation first, then substitute values."},
    {q:"In a circuit, an ammeter should be connected:",opts:["In parallel with the component being measured","In series so the current flows through it","Between the battery terminals only","Anywhere — position doesn't matter"],c:1,e:"An ammeter measures current (Amperes) and must be in SERIES — the current flows through it. A voltmeter measures voltage (Volts) and must be in PARALLEL across a component. Getting these confused is a very common exam mistake."},
    {q:"Which of the following materials is magnetic?",opts:["Copper","Aluminium","Gold","Nickel"],c:3,e:"Magnetic materials: iron, steel, nickel and cobalt. Most metals (aluminium, copper, gold, silver) are NOT magnetic. Many students incorrectly assume all metals are magnetic — this is one of the most common science misconceptions."},
    {q:"How can you increase the strength of an electromagnet?",opts:["Increase the voltage only","Decrease the number of coils","Increase the current OR increase the number of coils of wire","Change the core to aluminium"],c:2,e:"An electromagnet's strength increases by: (1) increasing the current, (2) increasing the number of turns of wire, (3) adding an iron core. Iron can be magnetised and demagnetised easily, greatly amplifying the magnetic field."},
    {q:"In a PARALLEL circuit, the voltage across each branch is:",opts:["Shared equally between branches","Zero in each branch","Equal to the full supply voltage","Determined by the length of the wire"],c:2,e:"In a parallel circuit, each branch is connected directly across the supply — so each gets the FULL supply voltage. Unlike series circuits (where voltage is shared), this is why household appliances each work at full mains voltage independently."},
    {q:"Electrical resistance is:",opts:["The flow of electrons through a wire","The energy given to charge by the battery","The opposition to the flow of current through a component","The rate of energy transfer"],c:2,e:"Resistance (Ohms, Ω) is how much a component opposes current flow. Factors affecting resistance: wire length (longer = more), thickness (thinner = more), material, and temperature. V = I × R links all three quantities."}
  ],
  "island-40":[
    {q:"In a transverse wave, particles vibrate:",opts:["In the same direction as the wave travels","At right angles (perpendicular) to the direction of wave travel","In circles around the wave path","Only when the wave is reflected"],c:1,e:"In a transverse wave, the particles oscillate perpendicular to the direction of energy travel. Examples include light waves and water surface waves. In a longitudinal wave (like sound), particles vibrate parallel to the wave direction."},
    {q:"Which part of the electromagnetic spectrum has the HIGHEST frequency?",opts:["Radio waves","Microwaves","X-rays","Gamma rays"],c:3,e:"The EM spectrum from lowest to highest frequency: Radio → Microwave → Infrared → Visible → Ultraviolet → X-rays → Gamma rays. Gamma rays have the highest frequency, shortest wavelength and greatest energy — making them the most ionising and dangerous."},
    {q:"Infrared radiation is used in:",opts:["Sterilising equipment and tanning","TV remote controls and thermal imaging","Medical X-ray imaging","Radio communication"],c:1,e:"Infrared is used in TV remote controls (detected by a sensor), thermal imaging cameras (show heat), night-vision goggles, and in grills and toasters. UV is used for sterilising; X-rays for medical imaging; radio waves for communication."},
    {q:"The wave equation links speed, frequency and wavelength. Which equation is correct?",opts:["speed = frequency + wavelength","speed = frequency × wavelength","speed = frequency ÷ wavelength","speed = wavelength ÷ frequency"],c:1,e:"Wave speed (v) = frequency (f) × wavelength (λ). All EM waves travel at the same speed in a vacuum (3×10⁸ m/s), so higher frequency EM waves have proportionally shorter wavelengths."},
    {q:"Sound is an example of a LONGITUDINAL wave because:",opts:["It travels at the speed of light","Particles vibrate at right angles to the wave direction","Particles vibrate parallel to (in the same direction as) the wave direction","It can travel through a vacuum"],c:2,e:"In a longitudinal wave, particles vibrate PARALLEL to the direction of energy travel, creating compressions (close together) and rarefactions (spread apart). Sound is longitudinal. Light and other EM waves are transverse."},
    {q:"Microwaves are used in mobile phone communication because:",opts:["They travel through the Earth","They are visible to the eye","They can carry information and pass through the atmosphere","They are completely safe"],c:2,e:"Microwaves pass through the atmosphere and carry large amounts of information, making them ideal for mobile phones and satellite communication. Microwave ovens use a specific frequency absorbed by water molecules, causing heating."},
    {q:"The wavelength of ultraviolet (UV) compared to visible light is:",opts:["Longer than visible light","The same as visible light","Shorter than visible light","Much longer than radio waves"],c:2,e:"EM spectrum order: …Infrared → Visible → UV → X-rays… UV has shorter wavelength (higher frequency, more energy) than visible light. It is the UV in sunlight that causes sunburn and increases the risk of skin cancer."},
    {q:"Which electromagnetic wave is used in medical X-ray imaging?",opts:["Radio waves","Microwaves","Visible light","X-rays"],c:3,e:"X-rays penetrate soft tissue but are absorbed by dense bone, allowing skeletal images to be produced. Excess X-ray exposure is harmful (ionising radiation can damage DNA). Lead aprons protect surrounding tissues during X-ray procedures."},
    {q:"Gamma rays are particularly dangerous to human tissue because:",opts:["They are the slowest EM waves","They have the longest wavelength","They are highly ionising and can damage DNA, potentially causing cancer","They cannot penetrate the skin"],c:2,e:"Gamma rays have the highest frequency and shortest wavelength — they carry the most energy and are the most ionising. Ionising radiation removes electrons from atoms in body cells, damaging DNA. In controlled doses, gamma rays are used in radiotherapy to target cancer cells."}
  ],
  "island-41":[
    {q:"Which kingdom contains organisms with a cell wall made of chitin that feed by external digestion?",opts:["Plants","Animals","Fungi","Prokaryotes"],c:2,e:"Fungi (e.g. mushrooms, moulds, yeast) have cell walls made of chitin (not cellulose like plants). They cannot photosynthesise and feed by secreting enzymes onto food externally, then absorbing the products — saprotrophic nutrition."},
    {q:"The scientific name Panthera leo tells you that the lion's:",opts:["Common name is Panthera","Genus is Panthera and species is leo","Species is Panthera and genus is leo","Family is Panthera leo"],c:1,e:"In binomial nomenclature, the first word (capitalised) is the GENUS and the second (lowercase) is the SPECIES. Panthera is also the genus of tigers (Panthera tigris) and leopards (Panthera pardus) — showing these big cats are closely related."},
    {q:"Vertebrates are animals that:",opts:["Have an exoskeleton","Can only live on land","Have a backbone (vertebral column)","Are always warm-blooded"],c:2,e:"Vertebrates have a vertebral column (backbone). The five vertebrate groups are: fish, amphibians, reptiles, birds and mammals. Invertebrates (insects, worms, molluscs, crustaceans, etc.) have no backbone and make up about 95% of all animal species."},
    {q:"Insects belong to which broader animal group?",opts:["Vertebrates","Arachnids","Arthropods","Molluscs"],c:2,e:"Insects are arthropods — invertebrates with an exoskeleton, jointed legs and a segmented body. Key insect features: 6 legs, 3 body parts (head, thorax, abdomen), usually 2 pairs of wings. Spiders have 8 legs and are arachnids (also arthropods)."},
    {q:"The key difference between prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells is:",opts:["Prokaryotes are always larger","Eukaryotes have no DNA","Prokaryotes have no membrane-bound nucleus — their DNA floats in the cytoplasm","Eukaryotes cannot carry out respiration"],c:2,e:"Prokaryotes (bacteria) have no nuclear membrane — their DNA is in the cytoplasm. Eukaryotes (animals, plants, fungi, protists) have a true nucleus enclosed in a nuclear membrane. Prokaryotes are also much smaller and simpler in structure."},
    {q:"Viruses are NOT classified as living organisms because:",opts:["They are too small to be seen without a microscope","They cannot reproduce independently — they must use a host cell's machinery","They have no carbon in their structure","They were only recently discovered"],c:1,e:"Viruses cannot carry out most MRS GREN processes on their own. They cannot reproduce without invading a host cell and hijacking its machinery. For this reason, viruses are sometimes described as 'on the boundary of life'."},
    {q:"A species is defined as a group of organisms that:",opts:["All look similar to each other","Can interbreed to produce fertile offspring","Share the same habitat","Belong to the same genus"],c:1,e:"The biological species concept: a species = organisms that can interbreed to produce FERTILE offspring. Horses and donkeys can breed but produce sterile mules — so they are different species. Shared appearance alone is not enough."},
    {q:"Which of the following is a characteristic of ALL mammals?",opts:["They lay eggs","They are warm-blooded, have hair or fur, and feed young on milk","They live in water","They have scales"],c:1,e:"Key mammal features: warm-blooded (endothermic), hair or fur, mostly give birth to live young, feed offspring on milk. Examples: dogs, whales, bats, humans. The platypus and echidna are exceptions — egg-laying mammals (monotremes)."},
    {q:"The correct order of the classification hierarchy, from largest to smallest group, is:",opts:["Species → Genus → Family → Order → Class → Phylum → Kingdom","Kingdom → Phylum → Class → Order → Family → Genus → Species","Class → Order → Family → Genus → Species → Kingdom","Genus → Species → Kingdom → Phylum → Class → Order → Family"],c:1,e:"Largest to most specific: Kingdom → Phylum → Class → Order → Family → Genus → Species. Memory aid: 'King Philip Came Over For Good Spaghetti'. The smaller the group, the more closely related the organisms within it."}
  ],
  "island-42":[
    {q:"The main function of red blood cells is to:",opts:["Fight bacterial infections","Help blood to clot at wound sites","Carry oxygen around the body","Produce antibodies"],c:2,e:"Red blood cells (erythrocytes) are packed with haemoglobin, which binds to oxygen in the lungs and releases it in body tissues. They have no nucleus, maximising space for haemoglobin, and a biconcave shape to increase surface area for gas exchange."},
    {q:"In the digestive system, most nutrient absorption takes place in the:",opts:["Stomach","Large intestine","Small intestine","Oesophagus"],c:2,e:"The small intestine is the main site of both chemical digestion (enzymes break down nutrients) and absorption (nutrients pass into the bloodstream via villi — finger-like projections that increase surface area). The large intestine mainly absorbs water."},
    {q:"A reflex action is faster than a voluntary action because:",opts:["The brain processes the signal more quickly","The signal travels directly through the spinal cord without waiting for the brain","Reflex muscles are stronger","Nerves are shorter in reflex pathways"],c:1,e:"In a reflex arc, the nerve impulse travels: receptor → sensory neuron → relay neuron in spinal cord → motor neuron → effector. The brain is informed AFTER the response has occurred. This makes reflexes extremely fast — essential for protection from harm."},
    {q:"The LEFT side of the heart pumps blood to:",opts:["The lungs only","The rest of the body (systemic circulation)","The liver directly","The right side of the heart directly"],c:1,e:"The left side receives oxygenated blood from the lungs and pumps it to the body (systemic circulation). The right side receives deoxygenated blood from the body and pumps it to the lungs. The left ventricle has thicker walls — it pumps blood further."},
    {q:"Which component of blood is responsible for clotting at a wound?",opts:["White blood cells","Platelets","Plasma","Red blood cells"],c:1,e:"Platelets are tiny cell fragments that clump together at a wound site, triggering a clotting cascade that forms a scab. This prevents blood loss and stops pathogens entering. White blood cells fight infection. Red blood cells carry oxygen. Plasma is the liquid medium."},
    {q:"Which enzyme breaks down starch, and where is it produced?",opts:["Protease — produced in the stomach","Lipase — produced in the small intestine","Amylase — produced in the salivary glands and pancreas","Bile — produced in the liver"],c:2,e:"Amylase breaks starch into sugars. It is produced by the salivary glands (acts in the mouth) and the pancreas (acts in the small intestine). Protease breaks proteins; lipase breaks lipids. Bile emulsifies fats but is not an enzyme."},
    {q:"Arteries differ from veins because arteries:",opts:["Carry only deoxygenated blood","Have valves to prevent backflow","Carry blood AWAY from the heart at high pressure with thick walls","Carry blood toward the heart at low pressure"],c:2,e:"Arteries carry blood AWAY from the heart at high pressure — thick, muscular, elastic walls withstand this pressure. Veins carry blood BACK to the heart at lower pressure — thinner walls and valves prevent backflow. Capillaries are the tiny exchange vessels."},
    {q:"Which of the following is NOT a function of the human skeleton?",opts:["Supporting and giving the body shape","Producing blood cells in bone marrow","Protecting vital organs","Regulating body temperature"],c:3,e:"Skeleton functions: support, protection (skull protects brain; ribcage protects heart/lungs), movement (with muscles), blood cell production (in bone marrow), mineral storage (calcium, phosphorus). Temperature regulation is mainly controlled by the skin and blood vessels."},
    {q:"The nervous system communicates using:",opts:["Chemical hormones transported in the blood","Electrical impulses along neurons","Mechanical vibrations through muscles","Heat signals through the body"],c:1,e:"The nervous system sends electrical nerve impulses along neurons at speeds up to 100 m/s — very fast. The hormonal (endocrine) system uses chemical messengers carried in the blood — slower but longer-lasting. Both systems coordinate the body's responses."}
  ],
  "island-43":[
    {q:"An organism with genotype Tt (where T = tall, dominant) will have the phenotype:",opts:["Short","Neither tall nor short","Tall","It depends on other genes"],c:2,e:"T is dominant, so even one copy of T is enough for the dominant phenotype (tall) to be expressed. The recessive phenotype (short, tt) only appears when BOTH alleles are recessive. Tt is heterozygous — the organism carries both alleles but shows only the dominant trait."},
    {q:"Two parents both have genotype Bb. What percentage of offspring is expected to show the recessive phenotype (bb)?",opts:["0%","25%","50%","75%"],c:1,e:"Punnett square: B×B=BB, B×b=Bb, b×B=Bb, b×b=bb. Results: 25% BB, 50% Bb, 25% bb. Only bb shows the recessive phenotype → 25%. The dominant phenotype (BB or Bb) appears in 75% of offspring."},
    {q:"Natural selection leads to evolution because:",opts:["All individuals in a species are identical","Organisms with favourable adaptations survive and pass those alleles to offspring","Scientists select which organisms breed","The environment never changes"],c:1,e:"Natural selection: variation exists → those with advantageous traits survive and reproduce more → favourable alleles become more frequent in the population over generations. Over a very long time, this leads to new species. Darwin called this 'descent with modification'."},
    {q:"DNA is found mainly in the:",opts:["Cell membrane","Cytoplasm","Nucleus","Mitochondria"],c:2,e:"DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid) is mainly located in the nucleus, organised into chromosomes. Small amounts also exist in mitochondria. Nuclear DNA contains the genetic instructions for all of the cell's activities."},
    {q:"A human body cell normally contains how many chromosomes?",opts:["23","44","46","92"],c:2,e:"Human body cells (somatic cells) have 46 chromosomes — 23 pairs (diploid). Gametes (egg and sperm) have only 23 chromosomes (haploid). At fertilisation, the gametes combine to restore the full 46. Sex chromosomes: XX = female, XY = male."},
    {q:"Continuous variation is best described as:",opts:["Features that fall into distinct, separate categories","Features that show a smooth range of values with no clear categories, e.g. height or mass","Variation caused only by genes","Features that can only be described in words"],c:1,e:"Continuous variation shows a smooth range (e.g. height, mass, foot size) — you can take any value within a range. Discontinuous variation shows distinct categories (e.g. blood group, tongue rolling). Both types are influenced by genes and/or environment."},
    {q:"A MUTATION is:",opts:["A change in the DNA sequence of a gene","A type of animal adaptation","The process by which cells divide","The passing of characteristics from parent to offspring"],c:0,e:"A mutation is a random change in the DNA (nucleotide sequence). Most mutations are neutral or harmful; occasionally a mutation is beneficial, giving the organism an advantage. Mutations can be caused by radiation or certain chemicals (mutagens)."},
    {q:"How is biological sex determined in humans?",opts:["By the mother's genes only","By whether the fertilising sperm carries an X or Y chromosome","By a combination of equal genetic and environmental factors","By the father's chromosomes only, regardless of the sperm type"],c:1,e:"Females are XX, males are XY. All eggs carry X. Sperm carry either X or Y. X sperm + egg → XX (female); Y sperm + egg → XY (male). The father's sperm determines the biological sex of the offspring."},
    {q:"Which provides the BEST direct evidence for evolution?",opts:["The fact that all animals need food","The fossil record showing gradual change in species over millions of years","That animals have different colours","That species look different in different countries"],c:1,e:"Fossils provide direct evidence of how organisms changed over geological time. Other evidence includes: DNA similarities between related species, comparative anatomy (e.g. pentadactyl limb), and antibiotic resistance (evolution observed directly). Darwin combined many strands of evidence in 'On the Origin of Species' (1859)."}
  ],
  "island-44":[
    {q:"The reactants (raw materials) for photosynthesis are:",opts:["Oxygen and glucose","Carbon dioxide and water","Glucose and oxygen","Carbon dioxide and oxygen"],c:1,e:"Photosynthesis: CO₂ + H₂O → C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂ (using light energy and chlorophyll). Plants take in carbon dioxide through stomata and water through roots. Oxygen is the waste product released into the air — which is why plants are vital for maintaining atmospheric oxygen levels."},
    {q:"A plant has plenty of light and CO₂, but the rate of photosynthesis stops increasing. The most likely limiting factor is:",opts:["Amount of water given","Light intensity","CO₂ concentration","Temperature"],c:3,e:"If light and CO₂ are both abundant, temperature becomes the limiting factor. Enzyme-controlled reactions speed up with temperature — but only up to about 40°C. Above this, enzymes denature (lose their shape) and the rate drops sharply."},
    {q:"Anaerobic respiration in human muscle cells produces:",opts:["Carbon dioxide and water","Ethanol and carbon dioxide","Lactic acid","Glucose and oxygen"],c:2,e:"During intense exercise, when oxygen delivery is insufficient, human muscles respire anaerobically: Glucose → Lactic acid. Lactic acid builds up, causing muscle fatigue. It is broken down later when extra oxygen is available (the 'oxygen debt'). Yeast produces ethanol + CO₂ in anaerobic respiration (used in brewing and baking)."},
    {q:"Photosynthesis takes place in the:",opts:["Mitochondria","Nucleus","Chloroplasts","Vacuole"],c:2,e:"Photosynthesis occurs in chloroplasts — organelles containing chlorophyll (the green pigment). Chloroplasts are found in plant cells and algae. Mitochondria are the site of aerobic respiration. The nucleus contains DNA."},
    {q:"The word equation for aerobic respiration is:",opts:["Glucose + oxygen → carbon dioxide + water (+ energy)","Carbon dioxide + water → glucose + oxygen","Glucose → lactic acid","Glucose + water → carbon dioxide + ethanol"],c:0,e:"Aerobic respiration: Glucose + Oxygen → Carbon dioxide + Water (+ energy released). It occurs in mitochondria. The energy released powers all life processes. It is essentially the reverse of photosynthesis — plants carry out both."},
    {q:"Chlorophyll is important in photosynthesis because it:",opts:["Provides the carbon dioxide needed","Absorbs light energy to power the reaction","Is a product of photosynthesis","Controls the rate at which water enters the roots"],c:1,e:"Chlorophyll is the green pigment in chloroplasts. It absorbs red and blue light energy (reflecting green — which is why plants appear green). This light energy powers the conversion of CO₂ and water into glucose."},
    {q:"The reagent used to test a leaf for starch is:",opts:["Benedict's solution — turns brick red","Biuret reagent — turns purple","Iodine solution — turns blue-black","Litmus — turns red in acid"],c:2,e:"Iodine solution turns blue-black in the presence of starch. To test a leaf: boil in water → heat in ethanol to remove chlorophyll → rinse → add iodine. Blue-black = starch present (photosynthesis occurred). Yellow-brown = no starch."},
    {q:"Why do plants store glucose as STARCH rather than keeping it as glucose?",opts:["Starch is needed directly for respiration","Starch is insoluble, so it does not affect osmosis; glucose is soluble and would draw in too much water","Glucose cannot be made from CO₂","Starch travels more easily through the plant"],c:1,e:"Starch is insoluble (doesn't dissolve), so it doesn't affect water concentration in cells. If plants stored soluble glucose, it would draw water in by osmosis, disrupting cell function. Starch is also compact for long-term storage."},
    {q:"A leaf kept in the dark for 48 hours, then tested for starch, would show:",opts:["Starch present — leaves store starch permanently","No starch — without light, photosynthesis stops and existing starch is used up in respiration","More starch than normal","The same result as a leaf kept in light"],c:1,e:"Without light, no photosynthesis occurs (light is needed to power the reaction). Any stored starch is broken down and used in respiration over 48 hours. This 'de-starching' is used in experiments to create a blank baseline before testing the effect of light on photosynthesis."}
  ],
  "island-45":[
    {q:"Which type of rock is formed when magma or lava cools and solidifies?",opts:["Sedimentary","Metamorphic","Igneous","Composite"],c:2,e:"Igneous rocks form from cooling magma (underground) or lava (at the surface). Slow cooling underground forms large crystals (e.g. granite). Fast cooling at the surface forms small crystals (e.g. basalt). The word 'igneous' comes from the Latin for fire."},
    {q:"Fossils are most commonly found in which type of rock?",opts:["Igneous","Metamorphic","Sedimentary","Volcanic"],c:2,e:"Fossils form in sedimentary rocks. Dead organisms are buried under sediment, which over millions of years compresses into rock. The organism's hard parts (bones, shells) are preserved. Igneous and metamorphic rocks involve such extreme heat or pressure that fossils are destroyed."},
    {q:"Which correctly describes how metamorphic rocks form?",opts:["Sediment is compacted and cemented","Magma cools underground","Existing rocks are changed by heat and/or pressure","Minerals dissolve in sea water and solidify"],c:2,e:"Metamorphic rocks form when existing rock (any type) is subjected to intense heat and pressure deep in the Earth, causing minerals to recrystallise without fully melting. Examples: marble (from limestone) and slate (from mudstone). They are often banded with interlocking crystals."},
    {q:"Earth's MANTLE is made of:",opts:["Solid iron and nickel","Liquid water","Semi-molten rock that flows slowly","Solid granite"],c:2,e:"The mantle is a thick layer of semi-molten rock. Convection currents in the mantle, driven by heat from the core, drag the tectonic plates at the surface. The mantle makes up about 84% of Earth's total volume."},
    {q:"Intrusive igneous rocks (e.g. granite) have LARGER crystals than extrusive igneous rocks (e.g. basalt) because:",opts:["They are made of different minerals","They cool slowly underground, giving crystals more time to grow","They form at higher temperatures","They contain more iron"],c:1,e:"Crystal size = cooling rate. Intrusive rocks cool slowly underground → large visible crystals (granite). Extrusive rocks cool quickly at the surface → tiny/no crystals (basalt). Glass (lava cooled almost instantly) has no crystals at all."},
    {q:"Freeze-thaw weathering breaks rocks by:",opts:["Acid rain dissolving the rock surface","Water entering cracks, freezing, expanding and widening the crack over repeated cycles","Roots growing into cracks and applying chemical pressure","Sand blown by wind sandpapering the surface"],c:1,e:"Freeze-thaw (frost action): water enters cracks → freezes → expands by ~9% → widens crack → thaws → refreezes → repeats. Over time, rock fragments break off. Common in mountains with repeated freeze-thaw cycles. This is physical (mechanical) weathering."},
    {q:"The rock cycle is described as a 'cycle' because:",opts:["Rocks travel in circular paths underground","All rock types can eventually be converted into any other rock type over millions of years","The same rock types always form in the same order","Rocks rotate inside the mantle"],c:1,e:"The rock cycle has no beginning or end — igneous rocks can be weathered into sediment → sedimentary rock → metamorphic rock → melted into magma → new igneous rock. No rock type is permanent. The cycle is driven by tectonic activity and takes millions of years."},
    {q:"Oceanic crust differs from continental crust in that oceanic crust is:",opts:["Thicker and less dense","Thinner and denser, made mainly of basalt","Made of granite, which is less dense","Much older than continental crust"],c:1,e:"Oceanic crust: thin (5–10 km), dense, made mainly of basalt. Continental crust: thick (30–70 km), less dense, made mainly of granite. At destructive plate boundaries, the denser oceanic crust subducts beneath the lighter continental crust."},
    {q:"Sedimentary rocks are formed by:",opts:["Cooling and solidification of magma","Heat and pressure changing existing rocks","Compaction and cementation of layers of sediment over millions of years","Dissolution of minerals in sea water"],c:2,e:"Sedimentary rock formation: weathering → erosion → sediment transported → deposited in layers → buried → compressed → minerals cement particles together → sedimentary rock. The process takes millions of years. Examples: sandstone, limestone, chalk, shale."}
  ],
  "island-46":[
    {q:"In the water cycle, water vapour rising into the atmosphere cools and forms clouds. This process is called:",opts:["Evaporation","Transpiration","Condensation","Precipitation"],c:2,e:"Condensation occurs when water vapour cools and changes back into liquid water droplets, forming clouds. Evaporation = liquid → vapour (at the ocean surface). Precipitation = water falling from clouds as rain, snow, sleet or hail. Transpiration = water vapour released by plants."},
    {q:"The natural greenhouse effect keeps Earth warm by:",opts:["The ozone layer reflecting sunlight back to Earth","Greenhouse gases absorbing and re-emitting infrared radiation from Earth's surface","The Sun becoming gradually hotter","Heat from Earth's core warming the surface"],c:1,e:"Earth's surface absorbs solar radiation and emits infrared radiation. Greenhouse gases (CO₂, methane, water vapour) trap this outgoing infrared and re-emit it in all directions, including back toward Earth. Without the greenhouse effect, Earth's average temperature would be about −18°C instead of +15°C."},
    {q:"Which process releases carbon dioxide into the atmosphere?",opts:["Photosynthesis by plants","Shell formation by marine animals","Combustion of fossil fuels","Absorption by the oceans"],c:2,e:"Combustion (burning) releases CO₂ stored in fossil fuels back into the atmosphere — carbon that was locked away for millions of years. Photosynthesis, shell formation and ocean absorption all act as carbon sinks (stores). Human combustion has significantly raised atmospheric CO₂ levels."},
    {q:"Approximately what percentage of Earth's atmosphere is nitrogen?",opts:["21%","50%","78%","99%"],c:2,e:"Earth's atmosphere: ~78% nitrogen (N₂), ~21% oxygen (O₂), ~1% argon, ~0.04% CO₂ and trace gases. Nitrogen is relatively unreactive under normal conditions. The 21% oxygen is what most organisms need for aerobic respiration."},
    {q:"Which human activity has had the GREATEST impact on rising atmospheric CO₂?",opts:["Flying aeroplanes","Burning fossil fuels (coal, oil, gas) for energy","Farming cattle","Using plastic packaging"],c:1,e:"The largest contributor is combustion of fossil fuels — releasing CO₂ locked underground for millions of years. Deforestation is the second largest factor. All human activities contribute, but fossil fuel burning accounts for the majority of the increase in atmospheric CO₂."},
    {q:"In the carbon cycle, which process removes CO₂ from the atmosphere?",opts:["Respiration","Combustion","Decomposition","Photosynthesis"],c:3,e:"Photosynthesis absorbs CO₂ from the atmosphere, fixing it into organic molecules (glucose). Oceans also absorb CO₂. Respiration, combustion and decomposition all release CO₂ — they are carbon sources. The balance between sources and sinks determines atmospheric CO₂ levels."},
    {q:"Global warming is expected to cause:",opts:["Increased snowfall globally","Rising sea levels due to melting ice and thermal expansion of oceans","Decreased frequency of extreme weather events","Cooler summers in most regions"],c:1,e:"Global warming → melting glaciers and ice caps → rising sea levels (also from thermal expansion of warmer ocean water). Other expected effects: more extreme weather events, shifting rainfall patterns, species habitat changes, and more frequent droughts."},
    {q:"TRANSPIRATION in the water cycle refers to:",opts:["Water vapour condensing into clouds","Water evaporating from the ocean surface","Water vapour released by plants through their leaves","Rainfall collecting in rivers and lakes"],c:2,e:"Transpiration = the process by which plants release water vapour through tiny pores (stomata) in their leaves. A large tree can transpire hundreds of litres per day. Transpiration drives the movement of water up the plant through the xylem (transpiration stream)."},
    {q:"Acid rain is caused by:",opts:["CO₂ dissolving in rainwater","Sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides dissolving in atmospheric water to form sulfuric and nitric acids","Seawater evaporating","Ozone reacting with rainwater"],c:1,e:"Acid rain forms when SO₂ (from burning fossil fuels) and NOx (from vehicle engines and power stations) dissolve in water vapour, forming sulfuric acid and nitric acid. This falls as rain with pH below 5.6, damaging trees, acidifying lakes, and eroding stone buildings."}
  ],
  "island-47":[
    {q:"Which planet is closest to the Sun?",opts:["Venus","Earth","Mercury","Mars"],c:2,e:"Mercury is the closest planet to the Sun, orbiting at an average distance of about 58 million km. Despite being closest, Mercury is not the hottest planet — Venus is hotter because its thick CO₂ atmosphere traps heat. Mercury has virtually no atmosphere, so temperatures range from −180°C to +430°C."},
    {q:"A lunar eclipse occurs when:",opts:["The Moon passes between Earth and the Sun","Earth passes between the Sun and the Moon, casting a shadow on the Moon","The Moon is on the far side of the Sun","The Moon's orbit takes it too far from Earth"],c:1,e:"Lunar eclipse: Earth is between the Sun and the Moon, so Earth's shadow falls on the Moon. Solar eclipse: the Moon is between Earth and the Sun, blocking sunlight from reaching part of Earth. Lunar eclipses are visible from anywhere on the night side of Earth; solar eclipses are only seen on a narrow path."},
    {q:"The seasons on Earth are caused by:",opts:["Earth's varying distance from the Sun throughout the year","The Sun's energy output changing throughout the year","Earth's axial tilt causing different hemispheres to receive more direct sunlight at different times","The Moon's gravitational effect on Earth's atmosphere"],c:2,e:"Earth's axis is tilted at ~23.5°. When the Northern Hemisphere is tilted toward the Sun (summer), sunlight hits at a more direct angle → more energy per m² → warmer. When tilted away (winter), sunlight is more spread out → less energy per m² → colder. Earth's distance from the Sun is NOT the main cause of seasons."},
    {q:"Earth takes approximately how long to orbit the Sun once?",opts:["24 hours","1 month","365.25 days","27 days"],c:2,e:"Earth takes 365.25 days (one year) to orbit the Sun. We add a leap day every 4 years to account for the extra 0.25 days. The Moon takes ~27 days to orbit Earth. Earth rotates once on its axis every 24 hours (one day)."},
    {q:"A light year is a unit of:",opts:["Time — how long light has been travelling","Distance — how far light travels in one year","Speed — how fast light travels per year","Energy output of the Sun per year"],c:1,e:"A light year is a unit of DISTANCE, not time. It equals the distance light travels in one year: ~9.46 × 10¹⁵ metres (about 9.5 trillion km). The nearest star (Proxima Centauri) is ~4.2 light years away. Astronomical distances are too vast for km to be practical."},
    {q:"A galaxy is:",opts:["A single star and its orbiting planets","A cloud of gas and dust in space","A vast collection of billions of stars, gas, dust and dark matter held together by gravity","The region of space around a black hole"],c:2,e:"A galaxy is a vast system containing billions of stars, gas, dust and dark matter, all held together by gravity. Our Solar System is in the Milky Way galaxy (~200 billion stars). There are estimated to be over 2 trillion galaxies in the observable universe."},
    {q:"The Sun is best classified as:",opts:["A planet","A moon","A star","An asteroid"],c:2,e:"The Sun is a STAR — a massive ball of hot plasma (mainly hydrogen and helium) generating energy through nuclear fusion in its core. It is the closest star to Earth at ~150 million km (light takes ~8 minutes to travel from Sun to Earth)."},
    {q:"What keeps planets in orbit around the Sun?",opts:["The push from the solar wind","Magnetic fields from the Sun","The Sun's gravitational pull acting as a centripetal force","The rotation of the planets on their own axes"],c:2,e:"Gravity provides the centripetal force that keeps planets in orbit. The Sun's enormous mass creates a gravitational pull that continuously curves each planet's path inward. Without this force, planets would travel in a straight line and escape into space (Newton's First Law)."},
    {q:"During a SOLAR eclipse:",opts:["Earth passes between the Sun and Moon","The Moon passes between Earth and the Sun, blocking sunlight from part of Earth","The Sun is blocked by another planet","Earth's shadow covers the Moon"],c:1,e:"Solar eclipse: Moon passes between Earth and the Sun, casting a shadow on Earth. Only those in the shadow (umbra) experience a total solar eclipse — affecting just a narrow path. Never look directly at a solar eclipse without specialist eye protection."}
  ],
  "island-60":[
    {q:"Which nutrient group is the body's main source of energy?",opts:["Carbohydrates","Vitamins","Minerals","Fibre"],c:0,e:"Carbohydrates (found in bread, pasta, rice and potatoes) are the body's main and quickest source of energy. They are broken down into glucose during digestion."},
    {q:"What is the function of proteins in the diet?",opts:["To provide insulation","For growth and repair of cells and tissues","To provide quick energy","To prevent constipation"],c:1,e:"Proteins are needed for growth and repair of body cells and tissues. Good sources include meat, fish, eggs, beans and dairy products."},
    {q:"Which nutrient group provides a concentrated store of energy and insulation?",opts:["Lipids (fats and oils)","Vitamins","Fibre","Water"],c:0,e:"Lipids (fats and oils) provide a concentrated energy store — more energy per gram than carbohydrates. They also insulate the body and protect vital organs."},
    {q:"Why is fibre important in the diet even though it provides no energy?",opts:["It provides vitamins","It keeps the digestive system healthy and prevents constipation","It builds strong bones","It fights infections"],c:1,e:"Fibre (roughage) cannot be digested but it is essential for keeping food moving through the digestive system and preventing constipation."},
    {q:"Which deficiency disease is caused by a lack of vitamin C?",opts:["Rickets","Scurvy","Anaemia","Night blindness"],c:1,e:"Scurvy is caused by a lack of vitamin C. Symptoms include bleeding gums, weakness and poor wound healing. Vitamin C is found in citrus fruits and vegetables."},
    {q:"What is the correct order of organs in the digestive system?",opts:["Mouth → oesophagus → stomach → small intestine → large intestine","Mouth → stomach → oesophagus → large intestine → small intestine","Stomach → mouth → small intestine → oesophagus → large intestine","Mouth → small intestine → stomach → oesophagus → large intestine"],c:0,e:"Food travels: mouth → oesophagus (food pipe) → stomach → small intestine → large intestine → rectum. Each organ plays a specific role in digestion."},
    {q:"What is the role of enzymes in digestion?",opts:["They physically chew food into smaller pieces","They act as biological catalysts that speed up the breakdown of large food molecules into smaller ones","They absorb nutrients into the blood","They kill harmful bacteria"],c:1,e:"Enzymes are biological catalysts that speed up chemical reactions. In digestion, they break down large, insoluble food molecules into small, soluble ones that can be absorbed into the blood."},
    {q:"Where does most absorption of digested food take place?",opts:["Stomach","Mouth","Small intestine","Large intestine"],c:2,e:"The small intestine is the main site of absorption. Its inner surface is covered in tiny finger-like projections called villi, which increase the surface area for absorbing nutrients into the blood."},
    {q:"What is the main function of the large intestine?",opts:["To digest proteins","To absorb water from undigested food","To produce enzymes","To store bile"],c:1,e:"The large intestine absorbs water from the remaining undigested food, turning it from liquid into solid faeces. Helpful bacteria in the large intestine also produce some vitamins."},
    {q:"A food label says a portion contains 1,200 kJ of energy. If a person needs 8,400 kJ per day, what fraction of their daily energy does this portion provide?",opts:["About one seventh","About one half","About one quarter","About one third"],c:0,e:"1,200 ÷ 8,400 = 1/7. So this portion provides about one seventh of the person's daily energy requirement."},
    {q:"Which condition can result from a diet that consistently provides more energy than the body uses?",opts:["Scurvy","Obesity","Anaemia","Rickets"],c:1,e:"Obesity results from consistently consuming more energy than the body uses. The excess energy is stored as fat, leading to weight gain and increased risk of type 2 diabetes, heart disease and other conditions."},
    {q:"What role do bacteria play in the human digestive system?",opts:["They cause diseases in the stomach","They help break down food in the large intestine and produce some vitamins","They digest food in the mouth","They transport nutrients to cells"],c:1,e:"Beneficial bacteria in the large intestine help break down remaining food material and produce vitamins such as vitamin K and some B vitamins. These 'good' bacteria are an important part of a healthy digestive system."}
  ],
  "island-61":[
    {q:"What is the formula for calculating pressure?",opts:["Pressure = force × area","Pressure = force ÷ area","Pressure = area ÷ force","Pressure = force + area"],c:1,e:"Pressure = force ÷ area (P = F/A). Pressure is measured in Pascals (Pa) or N/m². A larger force over a smaller area creates greater pressure."},
    {q:"A force of 600 N acts on an area of 2 m². What is the pressure?",opts:["300 Pa","1200 Pa","600 Pa","298 Pa"],c:0,e:"P = F ÷ A = 600 ÷ 2 = 300 Pa. The force is spread over 2 m², so the pressure is 300 Pascals."},
    {q:"Why do snowshoes stop a person from sinking into soft snow?",opts:["They make the person lighter","They spread the person's weight over a larger area, reducing pressure","They increase the force on the snow","They make the snow harder"],c:1,e:"Snowshoes have a large surface area. Since P = F/A, increasing the area while keeping the force (weight) the same reduces the pressure on the snow, so the person does not sink."},
    {q:"What unit is pressure measured in?",opts:["Newtons (N)","Pascals (Pa) or N/m²","Joules (J)","Metres per second (m/s)"],c:1,e:"Pressure is measured in Pascals (Pa), which is the same as N/m² (Newtons per square metre). 1 Pa = 1 N/m²."},
    {q:"A drawing pin has a sharp point with an area of 0.0001 m². If you push it with a force of 20 N, what pressure does the point exert?",opts:["200,000 Pa","2,000 Pa","20 Pa","0.000005 Pa"],c:0,e:"P = F ÷ A = 20 ÷ 0.0001 = 200,000 Pa. The tiny area of the point creates a very large pressure, which is why it pushes easily into surfaces."},
    {q:"What happens to atmospheric pressure as you go higher above sea level?",opts:["It increases","It decreases","It stays the same","It doubles"],c:1,e:"Atmospheric pressure decreases with altitude because there is less air above you. At sea level, the full weight of the atmosphere pushes down; on a mountain top, there is less air above, so less pressure."},
    {q:"Why does atmospheric pressure exist?",opts:["Because of the Sun's heat","Because air has weight and gravity pulls it down, creating a force on surfaces","Because the Earth spins","Because of magnetism"],c:1,e:"Air has mass, and gravity pulls it downwards. The weight of the column of air above any surface creates atmospheric pressure — approximately 101,325 Pa (about 101 kPa) at sea level."},
    {q:"What happens to pressure in a liquid as you go deeper?",opts:["It decreases","It stays the same","It increases","It disappears"],c:2,e:"Pressure in a liquid increases with depth because there is more liquid above pushing down. This is why deep-sea divers experience much greater pressure than swimmers at the surface."},
    {q:"An object placed in water experiences an upward force. What is this force called?",opts:["Gravity","Friction","Upthrust","Air resistance"],c:2,e:"Upthrust is the upward force exerted by a liquid (or gas) on an object placed in it. It acts in the opposite direction to the object's weight."},
    {q:"An object floats when:",opts:["Its weight is greater than the upthrust","Its weight equals the upthrust","There is no upthrust acting on it","It has no mass"],c:1,e:"An object floats when the upthrust (upward force from the liquid) equals its weight (downward force due to gravity). If the weight is greater than the upthrust, the object sinks."},
    {q:"A box has a weight of 500 N. It rests on one face with an area of 0.5 m², then is turned to rest on a face with an area of 2.5 m². What happens to the pressure?",opts:["The pressure increases from 200 Pa to 1000 Pa","The pressure decreases from 1000 Pa to 200 Pa","The pressure stays the same","The pressure becomes zero"],c:1,e:"On the small face: P = 500 ÷ 0.5 = 1000 Pa. On the large face: P = 500 ÷ 2.5 = 200 Pa. Increasing the area decreases the pressure because the same force is spread over a larger area."},
    {q:"Why do tractors have very wide tyres?",opts:["To go faster","To spread their heavy weight over a larger area, reducing pressure on soft ground","To increase the pressure on the ground","To look more impressive"],c:1,e:"Tractors are very heavy. Wide tyres spread the weight over a larger area (P = F/A), reducing the pressure on the ground so the tractor does not sink into soft soil."}
  ],
  "island-62":[
    {q:"In the Periodic Table, what is a 'period'?",opts:["A vertical column of elements","A horizontal row of elements","A group of metals","A type of chemical reaction"],c:1,e:"A period is a horizontal row in the Periodic Table. Elements in the same period have the same number of electron shells. There are seven periods in the modern Periodic Table."},
    {q:"In the Periodic Table, what is a 'group'?",opts:["A horizontal row of elements","A vertical column of elements","A random collection of elements","A type of bond"],c:1,e:"A group is a vertical column in the Periodic Table. Elements in the same group have the same number of electrons in their outer shell, giving them similar chemical properties."},
    {q:"Which group in the Periodic Table contains the alkali metals?",opts:["Group 0","Group 7","Group 1","Group 4"],c:2,e:"Group 1 contains the alkali metals: lithium, sodium, potassium, rubidium, caesium and francium. They are very reactive metals that react vigorously with water."},
    {q:"The halogens are found in which group?",opts:["Group 1","Group 0","Group 7","Group 3"],c:2,e:"Group 7 contains the halogens: fluorine, chlorine, bromine, iodine and astatine. They are reactive non-metals that form salts when they react with metals."},
    {q:"Why are the noble gases (Group 0) unreactive?",opts:["They are too heavy to react","They have a full outer shell of electrons, making them very stable","They are all radioactive","They only exist at very high temperatures"],c:1,e:"Noble gases (helium, neon, argon, krypton, xenon, radon) have a full outer electron shell, which makes them very stable and unreactive. This is why they are also called inert gases."},
    {q:"Who is credited with creating the first widely accepted Periodic Table?",opts:["Isaac Newton","Albert Einstein","Dmitri Mendeleev","Marie Curie"],c:2,e:"Dmitri Mendeleev (1869) arranged elements by atomic mass and left gaps for undiscovered elements. He even predicted the properties of these missing elements, and when they were later found, his predictions were remarkably accurate."},
    {q:"What key feature made Mendeleev's Periodic Table so successful?",opts:["He included every element known today","He left gaps for undiscovered elements and predicted their properties","He only included metals","He arranged elements alphabetically"],c:1,e:"Mendeleev left gaps in his table where no known element fitted the pattern. He predicted the properties of these missing elements (e.g. 'eka-silicon', later discovered as germanium). When the elements were found and matched his predictions, his table gained wide acceptance."},
    {q:"Most elements in the Periodic Table are:",opts:["Non-metals","Noble gases","Metalloids","Metals"],c:3,e:"About 80% of the elements in the Periodic Table are metals. Metals are found on the left and centre of the table; non-metals are found on the right-hand side."},
    {q:"Which of these is a typical property of metals?",opts:["Brittle and dull","Good conductors of electricity and heat","Poor conductors of heat","Low melting points"],c:1,e:"Metals are typically good conductors of electricity and heat, shiny (lustrous), malleable (can be bent), ductile (can be drawn into wires) and have high melting points (except mercury, which is liquid at room temperature)."},
    {q:"Which of these is a typical property of non-metals?",opts:["Shiny and malleable","Good conductors of electricity","Poor conductors of electricity and often brittle when solid","High density"],c:2,e:"Non-metals are typically poor conductors of electricity and heat (insulators), dull in appearance, brittle when solid, and have lower melting and boiling points than metals."},
    {q:"As you go down Group 1 (alkali metals), what happens to their reactivity?",opts:["Reactivity decreases","Reactivity stays the same","Reactivity increases","They become non-metals"],c:2,e:"Reactivity increases as you go down Group 1. Lithium reacts gently with water, sodium reacts more vigorously, and potassium reacts violently (with a lilac flame). The outer electron is easier to lose in larger atoms because it is further from the nucleus."},
    {q:"As you go down Group 7 (halogens), what happens to their reactivity?",opts:["Reactivity increases","Reactivity decreases","Reactivity stays the same","They become metals"],c:1,e:"Reactivity decreases as you go down Group 7. Fluorine is the most reactive halogen; iodine is much less reactive. In larger atoms, the outer shell is further from the nucleus, making it harder to attract an extra electron."}
  ],
  "island-63":[
    {q:"Which of these metals is the MOST reactive?",opts:["Gold","Iron","Potassium","Copper"],c:2,e:"The reactivity series from most to least reactive includes: potassium, sodium, calcium, magnesium, aluminium, zinc, iron, copper, silver, gold, platinum. Potassium is the most reactive of these options."},
    {q:"What is the reactivity series?",opts:["A list of metals in alphabetical order","A list of metals arranged in order of how vigorously they react","A list of non-metals","A list of compounds"],c:1,e:"The reactivity series is a list of metals ranked from most reactive (e.g. potassium) to least reactive (e.g. platinum). It helps predict whether a displacement reaction will occur."},
    {q:"Why is gold found as a native (pure) metal in the ground?",opts:["It is the most common metal","It is very unreactive, so it does not easily form compounds with other elements","It is the lightest metal","It is magnetic"],c:1,e:"Gold is very low in the reactivity series — it is extremely unreactive. This means it does not combine with oxygen or other elements easily, so it is found in its pure metallic form in the Earth's crust."},
    {q:"How is iron extracted from iron ore?",opts:["By electrolysis","By heating the ore with carbon in a blast furnace","By dissolving it in water","By filtering"],c:1,e:"Iron is extracted by heating iron oxide ore with carbon (coke) in a blast furnace. Carbon is more reactive than iron, so it displaces iron from its oxide: iron oxide + carbon → iron + carbon dioxide."},
    {q:"Why can carbon be used to extract metals like iron and zinc from their ores?",opts:["Carbon is a metal","Carbon is more reactive than iron and zinc, so it can displace them from their oxides","Carbon is less reactive than all metals","Carbon dissolves metal ores"],c:1,e:"Carbon sits between aluminium and zinc in the reactivity series. Metals below carbon (e.g. iron, lead, zinc) can be extracted by heating their ores with carbon — a displacement reaction. Metals above carbon (e.g. aluminium) require electrolysis instead."},
    {q:"Why can't carbon be used to extract aluminium from its ore?",opts:["Aluminium does not exist in ores","Aluminium is more reactive than carbon, so carbon cannot displace it","Carbon reacts with aluminium to form a gas","Aluminium is too heavy"],c:1,e:"Aluminium is more reactive than carbon in the reactivity series. Since carbon is less reactive, it cannot displace aluminium from its oxide. Instead, aluminium is extracted using electrolysis, which is more expensive."},
    {q:"A ceramic material such as a clay pot is typically:",opts:["Flexible and a good conductor","Hard, brittle and resistant to heat","Soft and magnetic","A good conductor of electricity"],c:1,e:"Ceramics (e.g. clay, porcelain, glass, bricks) are hard, brittle, heat-resistant and electrically insulating. They are made by heating natural materials such as clay to very high temperatures."},
    {q:"What is a polymer?",opts:["A type of metal alloy","A long-chain molecule made of many small repeating units (monomers)","A mixture of two metals","A naturally occurring mineral"],c:1,e:"Polymers are very long molecules made by joining many small molecules (monomers) together. Examples include plastics (polythene, PVC), rubber and nylon. They are generally lightweight, flexible and electrical insulators."},
    {q:"What is a composite material?",opts:["A pure element","A material made by combining two or more different materials to get improved properties","A type of polymer","A metal that has been melted"],c:1,e:"A composite is made from two or more materials combined to produce a material with better properties than either on its own. Examples: fibreglass (glass fibres + plastic), reinforced concrete (steel + concrete), carbon fibre (carbon strands + resin)."},
    {q:"A bridge needs to be strong but lightweight. Which material would be MOST suitable?",opts:["Pure gold","Clay ceramic","Carbon fibre composite","Cotton fabric"],c:2,e:"Carbon fibre composite is extremely strong for its weight — it has a high strength-to-weight ratio. This makes it ideal for applications where both strength and low weight are important, such as bridges, aircraft and racing cars."},
    {q:"If you place a piece of zinc into a copper sulfate solution, what happens?",opts:["Nothing — no reaction occurs","The zinc is coated with copper as zinc displaces copper from the solution","The copper sulfate turns into zinc","The solution freezes"],c:1,e:"Zinc is more reactive than copper, so zinc displaces copper from the copper sulfate solution. The zinc dissolves and copper is deposited on the zinc's surface. This is a displacement reaction: zinc + copper sulfate → zinc sulfate + copper."},
    {q:"Which property makes polymers useful for insulating electrical wires?",opts:["They conduct electricity well","They are poor conductors of electricity (good insulators)","They are magnetic","They are very heavy"],c:1,e:"Polymers such as PVC and rubber are excellent electrical insulators — they do not conduct electricity. This makes them ideal for coating electrical wires to prevent electric shocks and short circuits."}
  ],
  "island-64":[
    {q:"What does Hooke's Law state?",opts:["Force equals mass times acceleration","The extension of a spring is directly proportional to the force applied, up to the limit of proportionality","Energy cannot be created or destroyed","Every action has an equal and opposite reaction"],c:1,e:"Hooke's Law states: F = k × e, where F is the force applied (in N), k is the spring constant (in N/m), and e is the extension (in m). This relationship is linear up to the limit of proportionality."},
    {q:"In the equation F = k × e, what does 'k' represent?",opts:["The extension of the spring","The force applied","The spring constant — a measure of the stiffness of the spring","The weight of the spring"],c:2,e:"The spring constant (k) measures how stiff a spring is. It is measured in N/m (Newtons per metre). A higher value of k means a stiffer spring that requires more force to stretch it by a given amount."},
    {q:"A spring has a spring constant of 25 N/m. What force is needed to extend it by 0.2 m?",opts:["5 N","125 N","0.008 N","50 N"],c:0,e:"F = k × e = 25 × 0.2 = 5 N. A force of 5 Newtons is needed to extend this spring by 0.2 metres."},
    {q:"A force of 10 N stretches a spring by 0.5 m. What is the spring constant?",opts:["5 N/m","20 N/m","0.05 N/m","50 N/m"],c:1,e:"k = F ÷ e = 10 ÷ 0.5 = 20 N/m. This spring has a spring constant of 20 N/m, meaning it requires 20 N of force for every 1 m of extension."},
    {q:"What is the difference between elastic and plastic deformation?",opts:["Elastic deformation is permanent; plastic deformation is temporary","Elastic deformation means the object returns to its original shape when the force is removed; plastic deformation means it does not","Elastic deformation only happens to rubber; plastic deformation only happens to plastic","There is no difference"],c:1,e:"In elastic deformation, the object returns to its original shape and size when the force is removed (like stretching a spring gently). In plastic deformation, the object is permanently deformed and does not return to its original shape."},
    {q:"What is the 'limit of proportionality'?",opts:["The maximum force a spring can withstand before breaking","The point beyond which force and extension are no longer directly proportional (Hooke's Law no longer applies)","The minimum force needed to stretch a spring","The length of the spring at rest"],c:1,e:"The limit of proportionality is the point on a force–extension graph where the line stops being straight. Beyond this point, the spring no longer obeys Hooke's Law — the extension increases more rapidly for each unit of force, and deformation may become plastic."},
    {q:"On a force–extension graph for a spring obeying Hooke's Law, what does the line look like?",opts:["A curve","A straight line through the origin","A horizontal line","A vertical line"],c:1,e:"When a spring obeys Hooke's Law (F = k × e), the force–extension graph is a straight line passing through the origin. The gradient (slope) of this line equals the spring constant (k)."},
    {q:"A spring has a natural length of 10 cm. When a force is applied, it stretches to 14 cm. What is the extension?",opts:["14 cm","10 cm","4 cm","24 cm"],c:2,e:"Extension = stretched length − original length = 14 − 10 = 4 cm. Extension is the amount the spring has been stretched beyond its natural (unstretched) length."},
    {q:"Two springs have spring constants of 10 N/m and 40 N/m. Which spring is stiffer?",opts:["The spring with k = 10 N/m","The spring with k = 40 N/m","They are equally stiff","Neither — spring constant does not relate to stiffness"],c:1,e:"The spring with k = 40 N/m is stiffer. A higher spring constant means more force is needed to produce the same extension. The 40 N/m spring requires four times as much force per metre of stretch as the 10 N/m spring."},
    {q:"A spring with k = 50 N/m is stretched by a force of 15 N. What is the extension?",opts:["750 m","0.3 m","3.33 m","35 m"],c:1,e:"e = F ÷ k = 15 ÷ 50 = 0.3 m. The spring extends by 0.3 metres (or 30 cm) when a 15 N force is applied."},
    {q:"A student stretches a spring with increasing force. At first the extension is proportional to the force, but after a certain point the spring stretches much more for the same increase in force. What has happened?",opts:["The spring has broken","The spring has passed its limit of proportionality","Hooke's Law has been disproved","The spring constant has increased"],c:1,e:"The spring has exceeded its limit of proportionality. Beyond this point, the relationship between force and extension is no longer linear, and the spring may be undergoing plastic deformation (it may not return to its original length)."},
    {q:"If you double the force applied to a spring (within the limit of proportionality), what happens to the extension?",opts:["It halves","It stays the same","It doubles","It quadruples"],c:2,e:"Within the limit of proportionality, Hooke's Law applies: F = k × e. Since force and extension are directly proportional, doubling the force doubles the extension."}
  ],
  "island-65":[
    {q:"What is a drug?",opts:["Any food that gives you energy","A substance that changes the way the body or mind works","A type of vitamin","Water with added minerals"],c:1,e:"A drug is any substance that changes the way the body or mind works. This includes medicines (e.g. painkillers, antibiotics) and recreational drugs (e.g. alcohol, tobacco, caffeine, illegal drugs)."},
    {q:"Which of these is a legal recreational drug in the UK?",opts:["Cannabis","Cocaine","Alcohol","Ecstasy"],c:2,e:"Alcohol is a legal recreational drug for adults (18+) in the UK. Cannabis, cocaine and ecstasy are illegal (classified under the Misuse of Drugs Act). Legal does not mean harmless — alcohol causes significant health problems."},
    {q:"What effect does alcohol have on the nervous system?",opts:["It is a stimulant that speeds up reactions","It is a depressant that slows down brain activity and reaction times","It has no effect on the brain","It improves memory"],c:1,e:"Alcohol is a depressant — it slows down the activity of the brain and nervous system. This leads to slower reaction times, impaired judgement, loss of coordination and reduced self-control. Excessive drinking can cause unconsciousness."},
    {q:"Which organ is most damaged by long-term alcohol misuse?",opts:["Lungs","Liver","Skin","Ears"],c:1,e:"The liver breaks down alcohol, but long-term excessive drinking can cause liver disease (including cirrhosis, where liver cells are permanently damaged and replaced by scar tissue). Alcohol also affects the brain, heart and stomach."},
    {q:"What harmful substance in cigarette smoke is addictive?",opts:["Tar","Carbon monoxide","Nicotine","Oxygen"],c:2,e:"Nicotine is the addictive substance in tobacco smoke. It reaches the brain within seconds and creates a feeling of relaxation, but the body quickly becomes dependent on it, making it very difficult to stop smoking."},
    {q:"What does tar in cigarette smoke do to the lungs?",opts:["It cleans the airways","It coats the lungs and airways, damaging cilia and increasing the risk of lung cancer and bronchitis","It helps oxygen absorption","It reduces infections"],c:1,e:"Tar is a sticky, brown substance that coats the lungs and airways. It damages the tiny hair-like cilia that normally sweep mucus and dirt out of the lungs. Tar contains carcinogens (cancer-causing chemicals) and greatly increases the risk of lung cancer."},
    {q:"How does carbon monoxide from cigarette smoke affect the blood?",opts:["It increases oxygen levels","It binds to haemoglobin in red blood cells, reducing the amount of oxygen the blood can carry","It makes blood clot faster","It removes toxins from the blood"],c:1,e:"Carbon monoxide (CO) binds to haemoglobin in red blood cells much more strongly than oxygen does. This means the blood carries less oxygen to the body's cells, putting strain on the heart and reducing fitness."},
    {q:"Why is substance misuse particularly dangerous for young people?",opts:["It is not dangerous for young people","Young people's brains are still developing, making them more vulnerable to lasting damage","Young people have stronger livers","Drugs have no effect on young people"],c:1,e:"The brain continues to develop until the mid-20s. Using drugs and alcohol during this period can cause lasting damage to brain development, affecting memory, learning, decision-making and mental health."},
    {q:"What is meant by 'tolerance' in relation to drugs?",opts:["Being allergic to a drug","The body adapts so that more of the drug is needed to get the same effect","Being able to resist peer pressure","The drug stops working completely"],c:1,e:"Tolerance develops when the body adapts to a drug so that larger doses are needed to produce the same effect. This can lead to taking dangerously high doses and increases the risk of addiction and overdose."},
    {q:"What is drug dependence (addiction)?",opts:["Choosing to take a drug once","A condition where a person feels they cannot manage without a drug and experiences withdrawal symptoms without it","Using a drug prescribed by a doctor","Taking vitamins daily"],c:1,e:"Drug dependence (addiction) is when a person's body or mind has become so used to a drug that they feel unable to function normally without it. Stopping the drug causes unpleasant withdrawal symptoms (e.g. anxiety, shaking, nausea)."},
    {q:"Passive smoking means:",opts:["Choosing to smoke","Breathing in other people's cigarette smoke","Smoking while sleeping","Using nicotine patches"],c:1,e:"Passive smoking (also called second-hand smoking) means breathing in smoke from other people's cigarettes. It is harmful because the smoke contains the same toxic chemicals, including tar, nicotine and carbon monoxide, increasing the risk of lung disease and cancer in non-smokers."},
    {q:"A student says: 'Caffeine is not a drug because it is legal.' Why is this statement wrong?",opts:["Caffeine is actually illegal","A drug is any substance that changes how the body works — caffeine is a stimulant that speeds up the nervous system, so it IS a drug","Caffeine has no effect on the body","Only illegal substances are drugs"],c:1,e:"Caffeine is a legal drug — it is a stimulant found in coffee, tea, energy drinks and chocolate. It speeds up brain activity and increases alertness. The definition of a drug is any substance that changes how the body or mind works, regardless of whether it is legal or illegal."}
  ],
  "island-66":[
    {q:"On a distance–time graph, what does a horizontal (flat) line represent?",opts:["Constant speed","Acceleration","The object is stationary (not moving)","The object is moving backwards"],c:2,e:"A flat (horizontal) line on a distance–time graph means the distance is not changing — the object is stationary (stopped). Time is still passing, but no distance is being covered."},
    {q:"On a distance–time graph, what does a straight diagonal line going upwards represent?",opts:["The object is stationary","The object is moving at a constant speed","The object is decelerating","The object has stopped"],c:1,e:"A straight diagonal line on a distance–time graph represents constant speed. The steeper the line, the faster the object is moving (because more distance is covered in the same time)."},
    {q:"How do you calculate speed from a distance–time graph?",opts:["Speed = time ÷ distance","Speed = gradient of the line (distance ÷ time)","Speed = area under the graph","Speed = distance × time"],c:1,e:"Speed is calculated from the gradient (slope) of the line on a distance–time graph: speed = distance ÷ time. A steeper gradient means a higher speed."},
    {q:"An object travels 100 metres in 20 seconds at constant speed. What is its speed?",opts:["2000 m/s","5 m/s","120 m/s","0.2 m/s"],c:1,e:"Speed = distance ÷ time = 100 ÷ 20 = 5 m/s. The object is travelling at a constant speed of 5 metres per second."},
    {q:"On a distance–time graph, a steeper line means:",opts:["The object is going slower","The object has stopped","The object is going faster","The object is going backwards"],c:2,e:"A steeper line means a greater gradient, which means more distance is covered per unit of time — the object is moving faster. A shallow line means a slower speed."},
    {q:"A cyclist rides 300 m in 60 seconds, then stops for 30 seconds, then rides another 150 m in 30 seconds. What was their speed during the first section?",opts:["5 m/s","10 m/s","0.2 m/s","300 m/s"],c:0,e:"Speed for the first section = distance ÷ time = 300 ÷ 60 = 5 m/s. The stop would appear as a flat line on the graph, and the second section would be a separate diagonal line."},
    {q:"A cyclist rides 300 m in 60 seconds, then stops for 30 seconds, then rides another 150 m in 30 seconds. What was their speed during the last section?",opts:["10 m/s","5 m/s","0.2 m/s","150 m/s"],c:1,e:"Speed for the last section = distance ÷ time = 150 ÷ 30 = 5 m/s. Both sections happen to have the same speed, but you must calculate each separately using the distance and time for that section only."},
    {q:"What does the total distance on a distance–time graph represent?",opts:["The speed of the object","The total distance the object has travelled from its starting point","The time taken","The acceleration"],c:1,e:"The y-axis on a distance–time graph shows the total distance the object has travelled from its starting point. The x-axis shows the time elapsed. Reading the final distance value tells you how far the object has gone in total."},
    {q:"Two runners set off at the same time. Runner A's line on the distance–time graph is steeper than Runner B's. What does this tell you?",opts:["Runner A is slower","Runner A is faster","Runner B is faster","They are the same speed"],c:1,e:"A steeper gradient on a distance–time graph means a higher speed. Since Runner A's line is steeper, Runner A covers more distance in the same time and is therefore faster than Runner B."},
    {q:"A distance–time graph shows a straight line from (0, 0) to (10, 50). What is the speed?",opts:["500 m/s","5 m/s","0.2 m/s","60 m/s"],c:1,e:"Speed = gradient = change in distance ÷ change in time = (50 − 0) ÷ (10 − 0) = 50 ÷ 10 = 5 m/s."},
    {q:"A car travels at 20 m/s for 5 seconds, then at 10 m/s for 10 seconds. What total distance has it covered?",opts:["100 m","200 m","150 m","300 m"],c:1,e:"First section: distance = speed × time = 20 × 5 = 100 m. Second section: distance = 10 × 10 = 100 m. Total distance = 100 + 100 = 200 m."},
    {q:"On a distance–time graph, a curve getting steeper over time means the object is:",opts:["Slowing down","Moving at constant speed","Speeding up (accelerating)","Stationary"],c:2,e:"If the line curves upwards and gets steeper, the gradient is increasing over time. Since gradient = speed, an increasing gradient means the speed is increasing — the object is accelerating."}
  ],
  "island-31":[
    {q:"Pope Urban II called for the First Crusade in:",opts:["1066","1095","1215","1348"],c:1,e:"In 1095 at the Council of Clermont, Pope Urban II called on Christian knights to travel to the Holy Land and recapture Jerusalem from the Seljuk Turks. He promised spiritual rewards including forgiveness of sins."},
    {q:"Saladin recaptured Jerusalem from the Crusaders in:",opts:["1099","1187","1215","1291"],c:1,e:"Saladin (Salah ad-Din) retook Jerusalem in 1187, ending almost 90 years of Crusader rule. He was noted for his relatively merciful treatment of the city's Christian inhabitants."},
    {q:"One long-term positive consequence of the Crusades for Europe was:",opts:["The permanent control of the Holy Land","The elimination of the Islamic world","Increased trade and the transfer of Islamic knowledge to Europe","The unification of all Christian kingdoms"],c:2,e:"Through contact with the Islamic world, Europeans encountered advanced knowledge in medicine, astronomy, mathematics and philosophy. This cultural exchange contributed to the European Renaissance."},
    {q:"The First Crusade (1096-1099) succeeded in:",opts:["Defeating the Byzantine Empire","Capturing Jerusalem from Muslim control","Converting the entire Middle East to Christianity","Establishing permanent European rule over all of Asia"],c:1,e:"The First Crusade was the most successful for the Christians. Crusader armies captured Jerusalem in 1099 and established four Crusader states in the Holy Land. However, maintaining these states proved extremely difficult."},
    {q:"Why did Pope Urban II call for the First Crusade?",opts:["To conquer Egypt for its gold","To help the Byzantine Emperor defend against Seljuk Turks and to recapture the Holy Land","To punish the King of England","To stop Viking raids on Europe"],c:1,e:"The Byzantine Emperor Alexios I asked for help against the Seljuk Turks. Urban II saw an opportunity to unite Christendom, reclaim Jerusalem, and strengthen papal authority. He promised that Crusaders would have their sins forgiven."},
    {q:"Richard I of England (the Lionheart) is famous during the Crusades for:",opts:["Capturing Jerusalem permanently","Leading the Third Crusade and negotiating a truce with Saladin","Never leaving England","Destroying Constantinople"],c:1,e:"Richard I led the Third Crusade (1189-1192) after Saladin recaptured Jerusalem. Although Richard won several battles, he was unable to retake Jerusalem. He agreed a truce with Saladin allowing Christian pilgrims access to the holy sites."},
    {q:"The Knights Templar were:",opts:["Muslim warriors defending Jerusalem","A military religious order that protected Christian pilgrims in the Holy Land","English barons who opposed the king","Merchants who traded silk and spices"],c:1,e:"The Knights Templar were a powerful military order founded around 1119 to protect Christian pilgrims travelling to the Holy Land. They became enormously wealthy and influential before being suppressed in 1312."},
    {q:"What motivated ordinary people (not just knights) to join the Crusades?",opts:["Only the promise of wealth and land","Religious devotion, the promise of forgiveness of sins, and the hope of adventure and riches","They were all forced by their lords","They wanted to escape the Black Death"],c:1,e:"Crusaders had mixed motives: genuine religious belief and the promise of spiritual rewards (remission of sins), desire for land and wealth, a sense of adventure, and pressure from peers. For peasants, it was also an escape from their hard lives under feudalism."},
    {q:"How did the Crusades affect trade between Europe and the Middle East?",opts:["Trade stopped completely","New trade routes opened, bringing goods like spices, silk, sugar and new foods to Europe","Europe exported everything and imported nothing","Only weapons were traded"],c:1,e:"The Crusades greatly expanded trade between Europe and the Middle East. Europeans developed a taste for luxury goods — spices, silk, sugar, cotton, and citrus fruits. Italian cities like Venice and Genoa grew wealthy as trading middlemen."},
    {q:"Why did later Crusades mostly fail?",opts:["Europeans lost interest in religion entirely","Muslim forces were united and better organised, while Crusader states were weakened by internal divisions","The Pope banned further Crusades","Europe ran out of soldiers"],c:1,e:"After the First Crusade, Muslim forces became more united under leaders like Saladin. Crusader states quarrelled among themselves, supply lines from Europe were long and unreliable, and enthusiasm for Crusading gradually declined. The last Crusader stronghold, Acre, fell in 1291."}
  ],
  "island-32":[
    {q:"The Renaissance began in which country?",opts:["England","France","Germany","Italy"],c:3,e:"The Renaissance began in the Italian city-states (Florence, Venice, Rome) around the 14th century. Italy's wealth from trade and banking funded the arts and learning that defined the Renaissance."},
    {q:"Martin Luther's 95 Theses (1517) were primarily a protest against:",opts:["The sale of indulgences by the Church","The power of the English king","The teaching of science in universities","The use of Latin in education"],c:0,e:"Luther objected to the Church selling indulgences — paying money to reduce time in purgatory. He argued salvation came from faith alone (sola fide), not from financial payments to the Church."},
    {q:"Henry VIII's Act of Supremacy (1534) made him:",opts:["King of France","Head of the Church of England","The first Protestant king in Europe","Holy Roman Emperor"],c:1,e:"The Act of Supremacy declared the English monarch (Henry VIII) the Supreme Head of the Church of England, replacing the Pope's authority. This was the legal foundation of the English Reformation."},
    {q:"'Humanism' during the Renaissance placed new emphasis on:",opts:["Only religious texts and prayer","Individual human potential, classical learning, and reason","Military conquest","The feudal system"],c:1,e:"Humanism shifted focus from purely religious concerns to the study of classical Greek and Roman texts, human achievement, and the power of reason. It encouraged curiosity, education, and individual talent — a break from the medieval worldview."},
    {q:"Leonardo da Vinci is remembered as a Renaissance figure because he was:",opts:["Only a painter","A polymath — an artist, scientist, engineer and inventor","A military commander","A pope who reformed the Church"],c:1,e:"Leonardo da Vinci (1452-1519) embodied the Renaissance ideal of the 'universal man'. He painted masterpieces (Mona Lisa, The Last Supper), studied anatomy, designed flying machines, and filled notebooks with scientific observations centuries ahead of their time."},
    {q:"Why did the printing press (c.1440) have such a revolutionary impact?",opts:["It made books cheaper and faster to produce, spreading ideas widely","It only printed religious texts","It was invented in England","It replaced all handwriting permanently"],c:0,e:"Gutenberg's printing press allowed books to be mass-produced for the first time. Knowledge spread rapidly across Europe — literacy increased, new ideas (including Luther's criticisms of the Church) reached millions, and the monopoly of the Church and universities on learning was broken."},
    {q:"Michelangelo is best known for:",opts:["Inventing the telescope","Painting the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel and sculpting the statue of David","Writing the 95 Theses","Discovering America"],c:1,e:"Michelangelo (1475-1564) was one of the greatest Renaissance artists. His painting of the Sistine Chapel ceiling in Rome (1508-1512) and his marble sculpture of David are masterpieces that demonstrate the Renaissance celebration of human beauty and skill."},
    {q:"Martin Luther believed that salvation came through:",opts:["Buying indulgences from the Church","Faith alone (sola fide), not through payments or good works","Military service in the Crusades","Becoming a monk"],c:1,e:"Luther argued that people were saved by faith alone — a personal relationship with God through scripture. He rejected the idea that the Church could sell forgiveness (indulgences). His ideas challenged the Pope's authority and split Christianity in Western Europe."},
    {q:"The Reformation led to the creation of which new branch of Christianity?",opts:["Eastern Orthodox","Roman Catholicism","Protestantism","Buddhism"],c:2,e:"The Reformation, triggered by Luther in 1517, led to the rise of Protestant churches across Europe. Different forms emerged — Lutheranism in Germany, Calvinism in Switzerland and Scotland, and Anglicanism in England. Europe was religiously divided for centuries."},
    {q:"Why did Renaissance ideas spread from Italy to the rest of Europe?",opts:["Italy conquered all of Europe","Trade, travel, the printing press, and wealthy patrons helped spread ideas northward","Ideas were forced on other countries by the Pope","Italy was the only country with universities"],c:1,e:"Italy's wealth from trade and banking funded the arts, but ideas spread through trade routes, travelling scholars, diplomats, and especially the printing press. Northern Renaissance artists like Albrecht Durer and writers like Erasmus adapted Italian ideas to their own cultures."}
  ],
  "island-33":[
    {q:"Which Tudor monarch was known as 'Bloody Mary'?",opts:["Catherine of Aragon","Mary Queen of Scots","Mary I","Elizabeth I"],c:2,e:"Mary I (reigned 1553–58) earned this nickname by burning approximately 300 Protestants at the stake for heresy as she tried to return England to Catholicism. Her reign was deeply unpopular."},
    {q:"The Spanish Armada (1588) was defeated mainly because of:",opts:["A superior English army on land","English fireships at Gravelines and violent storms","The Pope withdrawing his support for Spain","France joining the English side"],c:1,e:"English fireships caused the Armada to scatter at Gravelines. Violent storms then destroyed much of the fleet as it tried to sail home around Scotland and Ireland. The weather was crucial."},
    {q:"Elizabeth I's religious settlement was designed to:",opts:["Make England strictly Calvinist Protestant","Restore full Catholic worship","Create a broad Protestant church that most English people could accept","Please the Pope and maintain good relations with Spain"],c:2,e:"Elizabeth's 'middle way' was deliberately moderate — Protestant in theology but keeping some Catholic-style ceremony. She wanted religious stability after the upheavals of her father, brother and sister's reigns."},
    {q:"How many wives did Henry VIII have?",opts:["Two","Four","Six","Eight"],c:2,e:"Henry VIII had six wives: Catherine of Aragon, Anne Boleyn, Jane Seymour, Anne of Cleves, Catherine Howard, and Catherine Parr. His desire for a male heir and his break with Rome over his divorce from Catherine of Aragon were central to the English Reformation."},
    {q:"Why was the Spanish Armada sent to England in 1588?",opts:["To establish trade with Elizabeth I","To invade England and restore Catholicism under Philip II of Spain","To deliver a peace treaty","To rescue English prisoners held in the Tower"],c:1,e:"Philip II of Spain launched the Armada to overthrow the Protestant Elizabeth I, restore Catholicism in England, and stop English attacks on Spanish ships and colonies. The Armada's defeat was a major turning point in European history."},
    {q:"Edward VI (1547-1553) is significant because during his reign:",opts:["England became more strongly Catholic","England became more strongly Protestant","England was invaded by France","The feudal system was restored"],c:1,e:"Edward VI, Henry VIII's son, was a committed Protestant. During his short reign (he died aged 15), England moved further towards Protestantism — English-language Prayer Books were introduced and Catholic practices were removed from churches."},
    {q:"Why is William Shakespeare associated with the Elizabethan era?",opts:["He was Elizabeth I's personal secretary","He was the most famous playwright of the era, writing during Elizabeth's reign","He invented the English language","He built the first school in England"],c:1,e:"Shakespeare (1564-1616) wrote most of his greatest plays during Elizabeth's reign and James I's. His works — including Romeo and Juliet, Hamlet, and Macbeth — were performed at the Globe Theatre and reflect the culture, language, and ideas of the Elizabethan age."},
    {q:"The Act of Uniformity (1559) under Elizabeth I required:",opts:["Everyone to attend Catholic mass","All churches to use the Book of Common Prayer and everyone to attend church on Sundays","All monasteries to be reopened","Latin to be the only language used in services"],c:1,e:"The Act of Uniformity was part of Elizabeth's religious settlement. It made the Protestant Book of Common Prayer the standard for all church services and fined people who did not attend church (recusants). It aimed to create religious unity."},
    {q:"What happened to the monasteries under Henry VIII?",opts:["They were expanded and enriched","They were dissolved (closed) and their wealth seized by the Crown","They were converted into universities","They were handed over to the Pope"],c:1,e:"The Dissolution of the Monasteries (1536-1541) saw Henry VIII close all monasteries, priories, convents and friaries in England, Wales and Ireland. Their wealth and lands were seized by the Crown and sold to supporters, making Henry richer and rewarding loyalty."},
    {q:"Mary I's persecution of Protestants earned her the nickname 'Bloody Mary' because she:",opts:["Led an army into battle","Had approximately 300 Protestants burned at the stake for heresy","Banned all food imports from Europe","Destroyed every Protestant church in England"],c:1,e:"Between 1555 and 1558, around 300 Protestants were executed by burning, including prominent bishops like Thomas Cranmer. Mary was trying to reverse the Reformation and restore Catholicism, but the burnings made her deeply unpopular."}
  ],
  "island-34":[
    {q:"Which leg of the triangular trade was known as the 'Middle Passage'?",opts:["Britain to West Africa","West Africa to the Americas","The Americas back to Britain","The overland route through North Africa"],c:1,e:"The Middle Passage was the horrific sea crossing from West Africa to the Caribbean and Americas, where enslaved people were transported in appalling conditions. Up to 20% died during the crossing."},
    {q:"The 1807 Slave Trade Act in Britain:",opts:["Freed all enslaved people in British colonies immediately","Made it illegal to buy or sell enslaved people in British territories","Gave enslaved people the right to vote","Compensated enslaved people for their suffering"],c:1,e:"The 1807 Act abolished the slave TRADE (buying and selling) but NOT slavery itself. Enslaved people in British colonies remained enslaved until the Slavery Abolition Act of 1833."},
    {q:"Olaudah Equiano was significant in the abolition movement because:",opts:["He was a British MP who campaigned in Parliament","He was an enslaved African who wrote a powerful first-hand autobiography","He was a lawyer who proved slavery was illegal","He led a major slave revolt in the Caribbean"],c:1,e:"Equiano's autobiography (1789) gave readers a powerful first-hand account of the slave trade and the Middle Passage. It humanised enslaved people and was hugely influential in building public opposition to slavery."},
    {q:"The 'triangular trade' involved three legs. What was traded on the first leg (Britain to West Africa)?",opts:["Enslaved people","Sugar and tobacco","Manufactured goods such as guns, cloth and alcohol","Raw cotton"],c:2,e:"British ships sailed to West Africa carrying manufactured goods — guns, textiles, alcohol, and metal goods. These were traded for enslaved Africans. The second leg (Middle Passage) took enslaved people to the Americas. The third leg brought sugar, tobacco and cotton back to Britain."},
    {q:"What was life like for enslaved people on plantations?",opts:["They worked short hours and were well paid","They were forced to work long hours in brutal conditions with no pay or freedom","They could leave whenever they chose","They were treated as employees with rights"],c:1,e:"Enslaved people on plantations endured backbreaking labour (often 18+ hours a day), brutal punishments, family separation, and complete loss of freedom. They were treated as property, not people. Conditions were especially harsh on sugar plantations in the Caribbean."},
    {q:"William Wilberforce's main contribution to abolition was:",opts:["Leading a slave revolt","Campaigning tirelessly in Parliament for decades to end the slave trade","Personally freeing all enslaved people in the Caribbean","Writing the Magna Carta"],c:1,e:"Wilberforce was an MP who, from 1789, introduced bills in Parliament year after year to abolish the slave trade. Despite repeated defeats, he persisted for nearly 20 years until the 1807 Slave Trade Act was finally passed."},
    {q:"The Slavery Abolition Act of 1833 was different from the 1807 Act because it:",opts:["Only banned the trade in enslaved people","Abolished slavery itself in most of the British Empire, freeing enslaved people","Applied only to England","Made the slave trade legal again"],c:1,e:"The 1807 Act banned the buying and selling of enslaved people (the trade). The 1833 Act went further — it abolished slavery itself in most British colonies, emancipating around 800,000 enslaved people. However, former enslaved people received no compensation, while slave owners were paid 20 million pounds."},
    {q:"Why were conditions on the Middle Passage so deadly?",opts:["Ships were too fast for safety","Enslaved people were crammed into tiny spaces with little food, water, or air, leading to disease and death","The journey only took a few hours","Ships were deliberately sunk"],c:1,e:"Enslaved Africans were chained below decks in spaces barely 50cm high. Disease (dysentery, smallpox), dehydration, and despair killed many — mortality rates of 15-20% were common. Some captives chose to jump overboard rather than endure the crossing."},
    {q:"How did enslaved people resist their enslavement?",opts:["They never resisted","Through revolts, running away, work slowdowns, maintaining cultural traditions, and sabotage","By writing letters to Parliament only","By refusing to eat only"],c:1,e:"Resistance took many forms: outright revolts (like the Haitian Revolution), escaping to freedom, deliberately breaking tools, working slowly, maintaining African languages, music and religions, and forming communities. Resistance was dangerous but constant."},
    {q:"Which city in Britain grew wealthy partly from the transatlantic slave trade?",opts:["Edinburgh","Liverpool","Cambridge","York"],c:1,e:"Liverpool became one of Britain's wealthiest cities partly through the slave trade — by the late 1700s, Liverpool ships carried about 80% of Britain's slave trade. Bristol was another major slave-trading port. The wealth generated built grand buildings and funded industries."}
  ],
  "island-35":[
    {q:"Which biome is found closest to the Equator and receives the most rainfall?",opts:["Tundra","Coniferous forest","Tropical rainforest","Hot desert"],c:2,e:"The tropical rainforest biome is found near the Equator (0°) where temperatures are consistently high (~27°C) and rainfall is heavy year-round (over 2,000 mm/year), creating ideal conditions for maximum biodiversity."},
    {q:"'Drip-tip leaves' are an adaptation found in the tropical rainforest. Their purpose is to:",opts:["Absorb maximum sunlight","Allow excess rainwater to run off quickly to prevent rot","Store water during dry seasons","Attract pollinating insects"],c:1,e:"The pointed drip-tips help shed the frequent, heavy rainfall quickly. This reduces the weight on leaves and prevents the growth of fungi and mosses that would block sunlight and damage the leaf."},
    {q:"Deforestation of the Amazon rainforest contributes to climate change because:",opts:["It increases rainfall in the region","Trees absorb CO₂; removing them releases stored carbon and reduces future absorption","It makes the soil more fertile","It reduces the number of animals that breathe out CO₂"],c:1,e:"Forests are carbon sinks — they absorb CO₂ from the atmosphere. When trees are burned or cut down, stored carbon is released as CO₂ (a greenhouse gas), contributing to global warming."},
    {q:"The tundra biome is characterised by:",opts:["Dense tree cover and heavy rainfall","Extremely cold temperatures, permafrost, and very few trees","Hot, dry conditions year-round","Moderate temperatures and deciduous trees"],c:1,e:"Tundra is found in high latitudes near the Arctic. Temperatures are below freezing for most of the year, the ground is permanently frozen (permafrost), and only mosses, lichens and small shrubs can survive. Growing seasons are very short."},
    {q:"Hot deserts receive less than how much rainfall per year?",opts:["250 mm","500 mm","1000 mm","2000 mm"],c:0,e:"Hot deserts (like the Sahara and Atacama) receive less than 250 mm of rainfall per year. Despite extreme heat during the day, temperatures can drop sharply at night. Plants and animals have special adaptations to survive the aridity."},
    {q:"A camel's hump is an adaptation to desert life because it:",opts:["Stores water directly","Stores fat, which can be metabolised for energy and water","Provides shade from the sun","Helps the camel run faster"],c:1,e:"Contrary to popular belief, camel humps store fat, not water. This fat can be broken down to release energy and metabolic water when food and water are scarce. Other desert adaptations include wide feet (to walk on sand) and thick eyelashes (to keep sand out)."},
    {q:"The coniferous forest (taiga) biome is found mainly in:",opts:["Tropical regions near the Equator","Northern latitudes across Canada, Scandinavia and Russia","The Sahara Desert","Coastal regions of Australia"],c:1,e:"The taiga (boreal forest) stretches across northern Russia, Scandinavia, and Canada between about 50°N and 70°N. It contains evergreen conifers (spruce, pine, fir) adapted to cold winters with needle-like leaves and conical shapes to shed snow."},
    {q:"Tropical rainforests have the highest biodiversity on Earth because:",opts:["They have the coldest temperatures","Constant warmth, heavy rainfall and sunlight provide ideal conditions for growth year-round","They have very poor soil","They experience all four seasons"],c:1,e:"Tropical rainforests have consistently high temperatures (~27°C), heavy rainfall (2000+ mm/year), and year-round sunlight. These ideal growing conditions support an enormous variety of plant and animal species — rainforests contain over half of all species on Earth despite covering only 6% of the land."},
    {q:"Deciduous forests are called 'deciduous' because their trees:",opts:["Never lose their leaves","Lose their leaves in autumn to conserve water during winter","Only grow in deserts","Produce fruit all year round"],c:1,e:"Deciduous trees shed their leaves in autumn when temperatures drop and daylight decreases. This reduces water loss through transpiration during the cold winter months when the ground may be frozen. New leaves grow in spring when conditions improve."},
    {q:"Latitude affects climate because:",opts:["Higher latitudes are closer to the Sun","Areas near the Equator (low latitude) receive more direct sunlight and are warmer; polar regions (high latitude) receive less direct sunlight","Latitude has no effect on climate","Only southern latitudes receive sunlight"],c:1,e:"At the Equator, the Sun's rays hit the Earth at a direct angle, concentrating energy on a small area — making it hot. At higher latitudes (nearer the poles), sunlight hits at a lower angle and is spread over a larger area — making it cooler. This is the main reason for global temperature differences."}
  ],
  "island-36":[
    {q:"What drives the movement of tectonic plates?",opts:["The Moon's gravitational pull","Convection currents in the mantle","Earth's rotation","Magnetic fields in the core"],c:1,e:"Heat from the Earth's core causes convection currents in the semi-molten mantle. Hot rock rises, spreads, cools, and sinks — this movement drags the tectonic plates above it."},
    {q:"At a DESTRUCTIVE plate boundary, what typically happens to the oceanic plate?",opts:["It rises to form new mountains","It melts as it subducts beneath the continental plate","It slides past the continental plate","It splits apart to form a rift valley"],c:1,e:"At destructive boundaries, the denser oceanic plate is forced under (subducts) the lighter continental plate into the mantle, where it melts. This creates volcanoes above and causes earthquakes."},
    {q:"The epicentre of an earthquake is:",opts:["The point underground where the earthquake originates","The point on the surface directly above the focus","The outer edge of the affected area","The point of maximum tsunami height"],c:1,e:"The focus (hypocentre) is the underground origin point. The epicentre is on the surface directly above it — usually where shaking is most intense. News reports give the epicentre location."},
    {q:"At a CONSTRUCTIVE plate boundary, what happens?",opts:["Two plates collide and one is destroyed","Two plates move apart and new crust is formed from rising magma","Two plates slide past each other","Plates remain completely still"],c:1,e:"At constructive (divergent) boundaries, plates move apart. Magma rises from the mantle to fill the gap, creating new crust. This often forms mid-ocean ridges (like the Mid-Atlantic Ridge) and volcanic islands like Iceland."},
    {q:"A conservative plate boundary is where two plates:",opts:["Move apart from each other","Collide head-on","Slide past each other, causing earthquakes but no volcanic activity","Stack on top of each other"],c:2,e:"At conservative (transform) boundaries, plates slide past each other horizontally. No crust is created or destroyed, so there are no volcanoes — but friction causes powerful earthquakes. The San Andreas Fault in California is a famous example."},
    {q:"What causes a tsunami?",opts:["Strong surface winds","An underwater earthquake or volcanic eruption displacing a large volume of seawater","Heavy rainfall over the ocean","The Moon's gravitational pull"],c:1,e:"Tsunamis are triggered when an earthquake, volcanic eruption or landslide displaces a large volume of water on the ocean floor. Waves travel at speeds up to 800 km/h in open ocean and grow enormously as they reach shallow coastal water."},
    {q:"The Richter Scale measures:",opts:["The height of a volcano","The magnitude (energy released) of an earthquake","Wind speed during a hurricane","The depth of the ocean"],c:1,e:"The Richter Scale measures earthquake magnitude — the amount of energy released. It is logarithmic: each whole number increase represents 10 times more ground shaking and about 32 times more energy. A magnitude 7 earthquake is 1,000 times stronger than a magnitude 5."},
    {q:"Why do people continue to live near volcanoes despite the danger?",opts:["Volcanoes are never dangerous","Volcanic soil is extremely fertile for farming, and volcanoes provide geothermal energy and tourism","There is nowhere else to live","Governments force people to stay"],c:1,e:"Volcanic soils (from weathered lava and ash) are among the most fertile in the world — ideal for farming. Volcanoes also attract tourists, provide geothermal energy, and offer minerals and building materials. Many communities have lived near volcanoes for generations."},
    {q:"What are convection currents in the mantle?",opts:["Circular movements of semi-molten rock caused by heat from the core","Fast-flowing rivers of lava at the surface","Wind patterns in the atmosphere","Ocean currents near the coast"],c:0,e:"Radioactive decay in Earth's core generates enormous heat. This heats mantle rock, causing it to rise slowly. As it moves sideways near the surface, it cools and sinks back down. These convection currents drag the tectonic plates above, causing them to move."},
    {q:"The 'focus' of an earthquake is:",opts:["The point on the surface where damage is worst","The point underground where the earthquake's energy is released","The depth of the magma chamber","The edge of the tectonic plate"],c:1,e:"The focus (also called hypocentre) is the point within the Earth where the rock fractures and energy is released. Shallow-focus earthquakes (less than 70 km deep) tend to cause the most surface damage. The epicentre is the point on the surface directly above the focus."}
  ],
  "island-37":[
    {q:"The Human Development Index (HDI) combines which THREE measures?",opts:["GDP, military strength, and population size","Life expectancy, education, and income per person","Rainfall, temperature, and land area","Birth rate, death rate, and migration"],c:1,e:"HDI = life expectancy (health) + education (years of schooling/literacy) + GNI per capita (standard of living). It gives a more complete picture of development than GDP alone, which only measures economic output."},
    {q:"Africa is best described as:",opts:["A single country with one government","A continent of 54 diverse countries","Mostly covered in jungle and rainforest","A continent with no major cities"],c:1,e:"Africa is a continent of 54 countries with enormous diversity — in landscapes (deserts, forests, mountains, coastlines), languages (over 2,000), cultures, religions and levels of economic development."},
    {q:"'Leakage' in tourism refers to:",opts:["Water escaping from tourist infrastructure","Tourists leaving the country early","Profits going to foreign companies rather than the local economy","Information about tourist attractions spreading abroad"],c:2,e:"Leakage = the proportion of tourism income that leaves the local economy — e.g. a hotel owned by a foreign company, flights on a foreign airline, food imported from abroad. High leakage reduces the economic benefit to local people."},
    {q:"What is Fairtrade?",opts:["A type of international war","A system that ensures producers in developing countries receive a fair price for their goods","Free trade with no taxes","A charity that builds schools in Africa"],c:1,e:"Fairtrade guarantees farmers and workers in developing countries a minimum fair price for their products (e.g. coffee, cocoa, bananas). It also provides a Fairtrade Premium — extra money invested in community projects like schools, clean water, and healthcare."},
    {q:"How does colonialism continue to affect development in many African countries?",opts:["It has no lasting effects","Colonial powers drew arbitrary borders, extracted resources, and left many countries with weak institutions and economies dependent on raw material exports","Colonialism only affected North Africa","All colonial effects were positive"],c:1,e:"European colonisers drew borders that divided ethnic groups and forced rivals together, extracted resources for their own benefit, and often did not invest in education or infrastructure. Many African nations gained independence with artificial borders, limited industries, and economies reliant on exporting raw materials."},
    {q:"GDP stands for:",opts:["General Development Plan","Gross Domestic Product — the total value of goods and services produced by a country in a year","Global Democracy Programme","Government Development Policy"],c:1,e:"GDP (Gross Domestic Product) measures the total value of all goods and services produced within a country in a year. GDP per capita (per person) is calculated by dividing GDP by the population. It is a common but imperfect measure of economic development."},
    {q:"Which of these is a social indicator of development?",opts:["GDP per capita","Number of factories","Literacy rate","Value of exports"],c:2,e:"Social indicators measure quality of life — literacy rate, life expectancy, infant mortality, access to clean water, and doctors per 1,000 people. Economic indicators (GDP, trade) measure wealth. The HDI combines both types for a more complete picture."},
    {q:"What is 'tied aid'?",opts:["Aid given with no conditions","Aid that requires the receiving country to spend the money on goods and services from the donor country","Aid given during natural disasters only","Aid provided by charities"],c:1,e:"Tied aid comes with conditions — the receiving country must buy goods or hire companies from the donor country. Critics argue this benefits the donor more than the recipient. Untied aid lets the receiving country spend the money where it is most needed."},
    {q:"Sustainable development means:",opts:["Building as many factories as possible","Development that meets present needs without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs","Stopping all economic growth","Only using traditional farming methods"],c:1,e:"Sustainable development balances economic growth, social progress, and environmental protection. It ensures that resources are used wisely so that future generations can also thrive. Examples include renewable energy, eco-tourism, and conservation alongside development."},
    {q:"Why is the HDI considered a better measure of development than GDP alone?",opts:["HDI is easier to calculate","HDI combines health, education, AND income — giving a more complete picture of people's quality of life","HDI only measures economic output","HDI ignores education completely"],c:1,e:"GDP only measures economic output — a country could have high GDP but poor healthcare and education. HDI combines three dimensions: life expectancy (health), years of schooling (education), and GNI per capita (income). This gives a more rounded view of how well people actually live."}
  ],
  "island-48":[
    {q:"Geography is the study of:",opts:["Only maps and atlases","The Earth's physical features, human societies, and how they interact","Only volcanoes and earthquakes","The history of ancient civilisations"],c:1,e:"Geography studies the Earth — both its physical features (landforms, rivers, climate) and human activities (cities, population, trade). It also examines how people and their environment interact and affect each other."},
    {q:"Physical geography focuses on:",opts:["People, cities and economies","Natural features and processes such as rivers, weather, and landforms","Only human-made structures","Trade and transport networks"],c:1,e:"Physical geography studies natural processes and features — including weather, climate, rivers, coasts, volcanoes, ecosystems, and rocks. Human geography, by contrast, focuses on people, settlements, economies, and cultures."},
    {q:"How many continents are there on Earth?",opts:["5","6","7","8"],c:2,e:"There are 7 continents: Africa, Antarctica, Asia, Australia (Oceania), Europe, North America, and South America. Asia is the largest by both area and population. Antarctica is the least populated — it has no permanent residents."},
    {q:"The Equator is an imaginary line that:",opts:["Runs from the North Pole to the South Pole","Divides the Earth into the Northern and Southern Hemispheres at 0° latitude","Separates Europe from Asia","Marks the edge of the Arctic Circle"],c:1,e:"The Equator is at 0° latitude and circles the Earth halfway between the North and South Poles. Countries on or near the Equator (e.g. Ecuador, Kenya, Indonesia) experience hot temperatures year-round because they receive the most direct sunlight."},
    {q:"Lines of longitude run:",opts:["Horizontally, parallel to the Equator","Vertically, from the North Pole to the South Pole","Diagonally across maps","Only across the oceans"],c:1,e:"Lines of longitude (meridians) run vertically from pole to pole. The Prime Meridian (0°) passes through Greenwich, London. Longitude is measured in degrees east or west of the Prime Meridian, up to 180°."},
    {q:"Which is the largest ocean on Earth?",opts:["Atlantic Ocean","Indian Ocean","Arctic Ocean","Pacific Ocean"],c:3,e:"The Pacific Ocean is by far the largest, covering about one-third of the Earth's surface — more than all the land areas combined. The five oceans in order of size: Pacific, Atlantic, Indian, Southern, Arctic."},
    {q:"The four countries that make up the United Kingdom are:",opts:["England, France, Scotland, Wales","England, Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland","England, Ireland, Scotland, Iceland","England, Scotland, Wales, Republic of Ireland"],c:1,e:"The United Kingdom (UK) consists of England (capital: London), Scotland (Edinburgh), Wales (Cardiff), and Northern Ireland (Belfast). The Republic of Ireland is a separate country. Great Britain refers to England, Scotland, and Wales only."},
    {q:"The Tropic of Cancer is located at:",opts:["0° latitude","23.5°N latitude","23.5°S latitude","66.5°N latitude"],c:1,e:"The Tropic of Cancer is at 23.5°N — the furthest north the Sun appears directly overhead (on the June solstice). The Tropic of Capricorn is at 23.5°S. The region between them is called the tropics, which receives the most intense sunlight."},
    {q:"Lines of latitude run:",opts:["From North Pole to South Pole","Horizontally, parallel to the Equator","Only through capital cities","Diagonally from east to west"],c:1,e:"Lines of latitude run horizontally around the Earth, parallel to the Equator. The Equator is 0°, the North Pole is 90°N, and the South Pole is 90°S. Latitude tells you how far north or south a place is from the Equator."},
    {q:"'Scale' on a map tells you:",opts:["The age of the map","The relationship between distance on the map and real distance on the ground","The height of mountains","The population of an area"],c:1,e:"Map scale shows how map distance relates to real-world distance. For example, 1:25,000 means 1 cm on the map = 25,000 cm (250 m) in reality. A larger scale (1:25,000) shows more detail than a smaller scale (1:250,000)."}
  ],
  "island-49":[
    {q:"The longest river in the United Kingdom is the:",opts:["Thames","Severn","Trent","Mersey"],c:1,e:"The River Severn is the longest river in the UK at 354 km, flowing from Wales through the English Midlands to the Bristol Channel. The Thames (346 km) is the second longest and flows through London."},
    {q:"The Lake District is located in which part of England?",opts:["South-East England","North-West England (Cumbria)","East Anglia","South-West England"],c:1,e:"The Lake District is in Cumbria, North-West England. It is a national park famous for its glacial lakes (Windermere is the largest), mountains (Scafell Pike is England's highest peak at 978m), and association with the poet William Wordsworth."},
    {q:"The Pennines are often called the:",opts:["Garden of England","Backbone of England","Gateway to Scotland","Highlands of Britain"],c:1,e:"The Pennines are a chain of hills and mountains running roughly north-south through northern England, from Derbyshire to the Scottish border. They are called the 'backbone of England' because of their central position."},
    {q:"What is the 'North-South divide' in the UK?",opts:["A physical mountain range separating north from south","An economic and social inequality where the south-east tends to be wealthier than the north","A river that divides England in half","A political border between England and Scotland"],c:1,e:"The North-South divide describes the economic gap between the generally wealthier south-east of England (centred on London) and the relatively less prosperous North, Midlands, and other regions. It is reflected in differences in wages, house prices, health, and employment."},
    {q:"Which of these is NOT a National Park in England or Wales?",opts:["Snowdonia","Peak District","Hyde Park","Dartmoor"],c:2,e:"Hyde Park is a public park in central London, not a National Park. National Parks are large areas of outstanding natural beauty protected by law — including Snowdonia (Wales), the Peak District, Dartmoor, the Lake District, and the Yorkshire Dales."},
    {q:"The Scottish Highlands are characterised by:",opts:["Flat, low-lying farmland","Rugged mountains, deep glens and lochs, and sparse population","Dense tropical forest","Large industrial cities"],c:1,e:"The Scottish Highlands are a mountainous region in northern Scotland with dramatic landscapes — including Ben Nevis (UK's highest peak at 1,345m), deep glacial valleys (glens), and freshwater lakes (lochs). The population density is very low due to the harsh terrain and climate."},
    {q:"The River Thames is important to the UK because:",opts:["It is the longest river in Europe","It flows through London, the capital city, and has been vital for trade and transport for centuries","It forms the border between England and Wales","It is the deepest river in the world"],c:1,e:"The Thames flows 346 km through southern England and through London. It has been crucial for trade, transport, and London's growth since Roman times. Major landmarks (Tower Bridge, Houses of Parliament, the Thames Barrier) line its banks."},
    {q:"Which coast of the UK is most affected by erosion?",opts:["The west coast only","The south coast only","The east coast, particularly areas with soft rock like Holderness","The north coast of Scotland only"],c:2,e:"The Holderness Coast in East Yorkshire is one of the fastest-eroding coastlines in Europe, retreating up to 2 metres per year. The soft boulder clay cliffs are easily eroded by waves, especially during storms. Coastal management strategies try to slow this process."},
    {q:"The UK has a variety of economic activities. Which sector employs the MOST people?",opts:["Primary (farming, fishing, mining)","Secondary (manufacturing)","Tertiary (services such as retail, education, healthcare)","Quaternary (research and IT)"],c:2,e:"The UK is a post-industrial economy — the tertiary (service) sector employs around 80% of workers. Primary and secondary sectors have declined as manufacturing moved overseas and farming became mechanised. The quaternary sector (research, IT) is growing."},
    {q:"What is a 'coastline' in geographical terms?",opts:["The deepest part of the ocean","The boundary where the land meets the sea","The centre of an island","A line on a map showing elevation"],c:1,e:"The coastline is where land meets the sea. The UK has approximately 31,000 km of coastline — one of the longest in Europe due to its irregular shape with many inlets, peninsulas, and islands. Coastlines are constantly changing due to erosion and deposition."}
  ],
  "island-50":[
    {q:"Which type of rock is formed from layers of sediment being compacted and cemented together over millions of years?",opts:["Igneous","Metamorphic","Sedimentary","Volcanic"],c:2,e:"Sedimentary rocks form when layers of sediment (sand, mud, shells, dead organisms) are buried, compressed by the weight above, and cemented together by minerals. Examples include sandstone, limestone, and chalk. They often contain fossils."},
    {q:"Granite is an example of which rock type?",opts:["Sedimentary","Metamorphic","Igneous (intrusive)","Igneous (extrusive)"],c:2,e:"Granite is an intrusive igneous rock — it forms when magma cools slowly underground, allowing large crystals to develop. It is very hard and durable, which is why it is used in building and for kitchen worktops."},
    {q:"The rock cycle describes how:",opts:["Rocks only form once and never change","All three rock types can be transformed into each other over millions of years","Only igneous rocks can change into other types","Rocks only form at the surface"],c:1,e:"The rock cycle shows that no rock type is permanent. Igneous rock can be weathered into sediment (forming sedimentary rock), which can be changed by heat and pressure (forming metamorphic rock), which can melt and cool (forming igneous rock again). The cycle has no fixed starting point."},
    {q:"Freeze-thaw weathering is a type of:",opts:["Chemical weathering","Biological weathering","Physical (mechanical) weathering","Erosion"],c:2,e:"Freeze-thaw (frost shattering) is physical weathering — it breaks rock apart without changing its chemical composition. Water enters cracks, freezes (expanding by about 9%), widens the crack, thaws, and refreezes repeatedly until rock fragments break off."},
    {q:"Chemical weathering occurs when:",opts:["Rocks are physically broken into smaller pieces","Rainwater (slightly acidic) reacts with minerals in the rock, dissolving or weakening it","Tree roots grow into cracks","Ice expands inside rocks"],c:1,e:"Chemical weathering changes the chemical composition of rocks. Slightly acidic rainwater (containing dissolved CO₂) reacts with minerals — especially in limestone and chalk (calcium carbonate), dissolving the rock over time. This creates features like caves and limestone pavements."},
    {q:"Biological weathering is caused by:",opts:["Chemical reactions with acid rain","Water freezing in cracks","Living organisms such as plant roots growing into cracks and animals burrowing","Wind blowing sand against rocks"],c:2,e:"Biological weathering involves living things breaking down rocks. Tree roots grow into cracks and widen them as they expand. Burrowing animals (rabbits, worms) disturb rock and soil. Lichens and mosses produce weak acids that slowly dissolve rock surfaces."},
    {q:"Marble is a metamorphic rock formed from:",opts:["Granite","Sandstone","Limestone","Basalt"],c:2,e:"Marble forms when limestone is subjected to intense heat and pressure deep within the Earth. The calcium carbonate recrystallises into interlocking crystals, creating a harder, denser rock with a characteristic smooth texture. Slate is metamorphic rock formed from mudstone."},
    {q:"Soil is formed from:",opts:["Only dead leaves and plants","The weathering of rock combined with decomposed organic matter (humus)","Volcanic eruptions only","Ocean sediments washed ashore"],c:1,e:"Soil forms over hundreds of years as rock is weathered into small particles, which mix with decomposed plant and animal material (humus). Different rock types, climates, and organisms create different soil types. Soil contains minerals, air, water, and living organisms."},
    {q:"Which rock type is MOST likely to contain fossils?",opts:["Igneous","Metamorphic","Sedimentary","All rock types equally"],c:2,e:"Fossils are found almost exclusively in sedimentary rocks, because organisms are buried in sediment that gradually hardens into rock. Igneous rocks form from molten material (too hot for fossils) and metamorphic rocks are changed by heat and pressure that usually destroys any fossils."},
    {q:"Basalt is an extrusive igneous rock. 'Extrusive' means it formed:",opts:["Deep underground from slowly cooling magma","At or near the Earth's surface from rapidly cooling lava","Under extreme pressure in the mantle","From layers of volcanic ash"],c:1,e:"Extrusive igneous rocks form when lava erupts onto the surface and cools quickly. Rapid cooling means crystals have little time to grow, so basalt has very small (or no visible) crystals. Compare this with granite (intrusive), which cools slowly underground and has large, visible crystals."}
  ],
  "island-51":[
    {q:"GIS stands for:",opts:["General Information System","Geographical Information System — a computer system for storing, analysing and displaying geographical data","Global Internet Service","Ground Investigation Survey"],c:1,e:"GIS (Geographical Information System) uses computer technology to collect, store, analyse and display geographical data on digital maps. It can layer different data sets (e.g. population, land use, flood risk) to reveal patterns and help decision-making."},
    {q:"In a fieldwork investigation, the hypothesis is:",opts:["The final conclusion","A testable prediction made before data collection","The method used to collect data","A type of graph"],c:1,e:"A hypothesis is a statement you can test through investigation. For example: 'River velocity increases downstream.' You then design your fieldwork to collect data that will support or disprove this prediction."},
    {q:"The mean is calculated by:",opts:["Finding the middle value in an ordered list","Finding the most common value","Adding all values together and dividing by the number of values","Subtracting the smallest from the largest value"],c:2,e:"Mean = total of all values ÷ number of values. For example, the mean of 4, 6, 8, 10, 12 is (4+6+8+10+12) ÷ 5 = 40 ÷ 5 = 8. The mean gives an average but can be affected by extreme values (outliers)."},
    {q:"The median is:",opts:["The most frequent value","The average of all values","The middle value when data is arranged in order","The difference between the highest and lowest values"],c:2,e:"To find the median, arrange values in order from smallest to largest and find the middle one. If there is an even number of values, the median is the mean of the two middle values. The median is less affected by extreme values than the mean."},
    {q:"The mode is:",opts:["The middle value in a data set","The most frequently occurring value in a data set","The average of all values","The range of the data"],c:1,e:"The mode is the value that appears most often. A data set can have no mode (all values different), one mode (unimodal), or more than one mode (bimodal/multimodal). For example, in 3, 5, 5, 7, 9 — the mode is 5."},
    {q:"A choropleth map uses:",opts:["Dots to show individual locations","Shading or colours to show different values across areas","Only contour lines","Photographs instead of drawings"],c:1,e:"Choropleth maps use colours or shading to represent different data values across defined areas (e.g. countries or regions). Darker shading usually indicates higher values. They are commonly used to show population density, rainfall, or deprivation levels."},
    {q:"Why is it important to collect PRIMARY data in fieldwork?",opts:["Primary data is always more accurate than secondary data","It is data you collect yourself, tailored to your specific investigation","Primary data is free to access online","It requires no planning or preparation"],c:1,e:"Primary data is information you collect first-hand through your own fieldwork — surveys, measurements, observations. It is specifically designed to answer YOUR research question. Secondary data (maps, census data, textbooks) was collected by someone else for a different purpose."},
    {q:"What is a 'sampling strategy' in fieldwork?",opts:["A way to present your results","A method for choosing where or what to measure when you cannot measure everything","A type of graph","A way to write up your conclusion"],c:1,e:"Sampling strategies help you select representative data points. Random sampling uses chance (e.g. random number generator); systematic sampling takes measurements at regular intervals; stratified sampling divides the area into zones and samples within each. The strategy chosen affects the reliability of results."},
    {q:"Data reliability in fieldwork means:",opts:["The data looks attractive when displayed","Results would be similar if the investigation were repeated in the same way","The data was collected quickly","Only one measurement was taken"],c:1,e:"Reliable data gives consistent results when the investigation is repeated. You can improve reliability by: taking multiple measurements, using accurate equipment, following a clear method, and training all data collectors to use the same technique."},
    {q:"A scatter graph is used to show:",opts:["How data changes over time","The relationship (correlation) between two variables","The proportion of different categories","How one variable compares across places"],c:1,e:"Scatter graphs plot two variables against each other to see if there is a relationship (correlation). Positive correlation: both increase together. Negative correlation: one increases as the other decreases. No correlation: no clear pattern. A line of best fit shows the trend."}
  ],
  "island-52":[
    {q:"Globalisation is best defined as:",opts:["A type of climate change","The increasing interconnection of the world's economies, cultures and populations through trade, communication and migration","A UK government policy","The growth of cities in developing countries"],c:1,e:"Globalisation means the world is becoming more interconnected. Improvements in transport, communication (internet, social media), and the growth of transnational corporations (TNCs) mean goods, people, money, and ideas flow more freely across borders than ever before."},
    {q:"A TNC (Transnational Corporation) is a company that:",opts:["Only operates in one country","Operates in two or more countries, with its headquarters usually in a HIC","Is owned by the United Nations","Only sells products online"],c:1,e:"TNCs are large companies that operate across national borders — for example, Apple, Nike, and Unilever. They typically have headquarters in HICs but manufacture in LICs/NEEs where labour and land costs are lower. They are a major driver of globalisation."},
    {q:"'Food miles' refers to:",opts:["The number of calories in food","The distance food travels from where it is produced to where it is consumed","The weight of food transported by ship","The cost of food per kilogram"],c:1,e:"Food miles measure how far food has travelled before reaching your plate. For example, green beans flown from Kenya to the UK travel thousands of miles. High food miles mean more transport emissions (CO₂), but the issue is complex — air freight can support developing economies."},
    {q:"Which of these has been a major cause of globalisation?",opts:["Reduced internet access","Improvements in transport and communication technology","Countries closing their borders","A decrease in world trade"],c:1,e:"Faster, cheaper transport (container ships, air freight) and communication technology (internet, mobile phones, video calls) have made it easier and cheaper to move goods, money, and information around the world — driving globalisation."},
    {q:"One benefit of globalisation for LICs (Low Income Countries) is:",opts:["Complete economic independence","TNCs can create jobs and bring investment, technology and infrastructure","All profits stay within the local economy","Reduced cultural exchange"],c:1,e:"TNCs investing in LICs can create employment, build infrastructure (roads, factories), transfer technology, and increase tax revenue. However, critics argue that wages are often low, working conditions poor, and most profits flow back to the TNC's home country."},
    {q:"A 'supply chain' is:",opts:["A type of anchor chain used on cargo ships","The network of organisations, people and activities involved in creating and delivering a product from raw materials to the consumer","A chain of shops on a high street","The route a delivery van takes"],c:1,e:"Supply chains can span many countries. For example, a smartphone might use minerals mined in Africa, components made in China, software developed in the USA, and be assembled in Vietnam before being sold worldwide. Globalisation has made supply chains longer and more complex."},
    {q:"One criticism of globalisation is that it can lead to:",opts:["Increased cultural diversity everywhere","The loss of local cultures and traditions as global brands and Western culture dominate","Better protection of traditional customs","More isolated communities"],c:1,e:"As global brands (McDonald's, Starbucks, Netflix) spread worldwide, local businesses, languages, foods, and traditions can be displaced. This 'cultural homogenisation' worries those who value diversity. However, globalisation also enables cultural exchange and the sharing of different traditions."},
    {q:"The UK's main trading partners are:",opts:["Only African countries","Countries in the EU and the USA","Only Asian countries","Only countries in the Southern Hemisphere"],c:1,e:"The UK trades most with the EU (especially Germany, France, Netherlands), the USA, and China. Historically, the EU has been the UK's largest trading partner. Since Brexit, trade relationships have been renegotiated, but the EU and USA remain dominant."},
    {q:"Migration is a consequence of globalisation because:",opts:["People no longer want to travel","Improved transport and communication make it easier to move to other countries for work or study","Borders have become completely open worldwide","Migration only happened before globalisation"],c:1,e:"Globalisation makes migration easier — cheap flights, online job searches, instant communication with family back home, and established migrant communities all encourage movement. The UK has experienced significant migration, bringing economic benefits and cultural diversity."},
    {q:"What is meant by 'interdependence' in globalisation?",opts:["Countries are completely independent from each other","Countries depend on each other for goods, services, labour and resources","Only rich countries depend on poor countries","Only neighbouring countries trade with each other"],c:1,e:"Interdependence means countries rely on each other. The UK depends on imports (food, energy, manufactured goods) and exports (financial services, technology). A disruption in one country (e.g. a factory closure or pandemic) can affect supply chains worldwide."}
  ],
  "island-53":[
    {q:"After the Romans left Britain (c. 410 AD), which groups migrated to and settled in England?",opts:["The Normans","The Anglo-Saxons — Angles, Saxons and Jutes from northern Europe","The Crusaders","The Vikings only"],c:1,e:"After Roman withdrawal, Germanic tribes — the Angles (from modern Denmark/Germany), Saxons (from northern Germany) and Jutes (from Jutland/Denmark) — migrated to Britain. They gradually established kingdoms and their language evolved into Old English."},
    {q:"Which Anglo-Saxon kingdom was ruled by Alfred the Great?",opts:["Mercia","Northumbria","East Anglia","Wessex"],c:3,e:"Alfred the Great (reigned 871-899) was King of Wessex in southern England. He successfully defended his kingdom against Viking invasion, promoted education and literacy, and created a legal code. He is the only English monarch called 'the Great'."},
    {q:"The Viking raids on Britain began with an attack on which monastery in 793 AD?",opts:["Canterbury","Westminster","Lindisfarne","Glastonbury"],c:2,e:"The Viking Age in Britain is traditionally dated from the raid on Lindisfarne monastery (Holy Island) off the Northumbrian coast in 793 AD. The raiders looted treasures, killed monks, and shocked Christian Europe. More raids followed along the coastlines."},
    {q:"The Danelaw was:",opts:["A set of laws written by Alfred the Great","The area of England under Viking control and Danish law, mainly in the north and east","A Viking warship","A treaty between France and Denmark"],c:1,e:"The Danelaw was the large area of northern and eastern England where Danish (Viking) law and customs prevailed, established after the Treaty of Wedmore (c.878) between Alfred the Great and the Viking leader Guthrum. It roughly covered the area north and east of Watling Street."},
    {q:"What was the Great Heathen Army?",opts:["A Roman legion that invaded Britain","A large Viking invasion force that arrived in 865 AD to conquer Anglo-Saxon kingdoms","Alfred the Great's personal army","A group of Norman knights"],c:1,e:"The Great Heathen Army was a massive Viking force (possibly thousands of warriors) that landed in East Anglia in 865 AD. Unlike earlier hit-and-run raids, this army aimed to conquer and settle. Within a few years, they had overrun Northumbria, East Anglia, and most of Mercia."},
    {q:"Edward the Confessor was the last Anglo-Saxon king before:",opts:["The Viking invasions","The Norman Conquest of 1066","The Roman invasion","The Peasants' Revolt"],c:1,e:"Edward the Confessor died on 5 January 1066 without a clear heir, triggering the succession crisis that led to the Norman Conquest. Harold Godwinson was crowned the same day, but William of Normandy and Harald Hardrada also claimed the throne."},
    {q:"Anglo-Saxon society was organised into:",opts:["A single unified state with one government","Multiple independent kingdoms such as Wessex, Mercia and Northumbria","Only coastal settlements","Underground communities"],c:1,e:"Anglo-Saxon England was divided into several kingdoms — the most powerful being Wessex, Mercia, Northumbria, and East Anglia. These kingdoms often competed and fought each other. It was not until the 10th century that they were united into a single kingdom of England."},
    {q:"What role did monasteries play in Anglo-Saxon England?",opts:["They were only military forts","They were centres of learning, education, art and book production","They were used as prisons","They were Viking trading posts"],c:1,e:"Monasteries were the main centres of education, literacy, and culture in Anglo-Saxon England. Monks copied manuscripts by hand, created illuminated texts like the Lindisfarne Gospels, taught reading and writing, and preserved knowledge during the early medieval period."},
    {q:"Alfred the Great's most important achievement was:",opts:["Conquering all of Scandinavia","Defending Wessex against the Vikings and beginning the reconquest of the Danelaw","Building the first castle in England","Invading France"],c:1,e:"Alfred reorganised Wessex's defences — building a network of fortified towns (burhs), creating a naval fleet, and reforming the army. He defeated the Vikings at the Battle of Edington (878) and secured a peace treaty. His successors continued the reconquest of the Danelaw."},
    {q:"The Anglo-Saxons converted to Christianity mainly through:",opts:["Viking missionaries","Roman missionaries led by Augustine (597 AD) and Celtic monks from Iona","Muslim traders from the Mediterranean","Norman priests after 1066"],c:1,e:"Pope Gregory the Great sent Augustine to Kent in 597 AD. King Ethelbert of Kent converted, and Christianity gradually spread south. Meanwhile, Celtic missionaries from Ireland and Scotland (e.g. Aidan from Iona to Lindisfarne) converted the north. By the 7th century, most of England was Christian."}
  ],
  "island-54":[
    {q:"The Peasants' Revolt took place in:",opts:["1066","1215","1348","1381"],c:3,e:"The Peasants' Revolt broke out in 1381, triggered by the introduction of a third Poll Tax. It was the largest popular uprising in medieval English history and reflected the deep social tensions caused by the Black Death and its aftermath."},
    {q:"The Statute of Labourers (1351) angered peasants because it:",opts:["Gave them more land","Tried to fix wages at pre-Black Death levels and restrict peasant movement","Abolished the feudal system","Increased the power of Parliament"],c:1,e:"After the Black Death killed a third of the population, surviving workers demanded higher wages. The Statute of Labourers tried to freeze wages at 1346 levels and prevent peasants from leaving their lord's manor. Peasants saw this as deeply unfair, as lords were trying to deny them the benefits of the labour shortage."},
    {q:"The Poll Tax of 1380 was unpopular because it:",opts:["Only taxed the wealthy","Required every person over 15 to pay the same amount, regardless of wealth","Was voluntary","Funded improvements to peasant housing"],c:1,e:"The Poll Tax was a flat tax — everyone over 15 paid the same amount (1 shilling), whether rich or poor. This was the third Poll Tax in four years and was three times higher than the first. Peasants saw it as grossly unfair since the wealthy paid the same as the poorest."},
    {q:"Who was the leader of the Peasants' Revolt?",opts:["Simon de Montfort","William Wallace","Wat Tyler","Robin Hood"],c:2,e:"Wat Tyler from Kent emerged as the main leader of the revolt. He led the rebels to London and met King Richard II at Smithfield. Tyler was killed during the meeting by the Lord Mayor of London, William Walworth."},
    {q:"John Ball was a radical priest who preached that:",opts:["The king had absolute power from God","All people were born equal and the feudal system was unjust","Peasants should never question authority","The Church should collect more tithes"],c:1,e:"John Ball was a travelling priest who inspired the rebels with sermons about equality. He is famous for asking: 'When Adam delved and Eve span, who was then the gentleman?' — arguing that God created all people equal, and the feudal hierarchy was man-made and unjust."},
    {q:"What did the rebels do when they reached London?",opts:["They peacefully petitioned the king","They burned John of Gaunt's Savoy Palace, opened prisons and killed officials they blamed for the Poll Tax","They surrendered immediately","They only marched around the city walls"],c:1,e:"The rebels entered London, attacked properties of those they blamed for their suffering (including the magnificent Savoy Palace of John of Gaunt), opened prisons, and killed several royal officials including the Archbishop of Canterbury, Simon Sudbury. They were angry but initially focused on specific targets."},
    {q:"At Smithfield, King Richard II promised the rebels:",opts:["Nothing at all","The abolition of serfdom, lower taxes and freedom for peasants","Immediate execution for all rebels","A place in Parliament"],c:1,e:"The 14-year-old Richard II met the rebels at Smithfield and promised to abolish serfdom, grant pardons, and reduce rents. After Wat Tyler was killed, Richard famously rode towards the angry crowd saying 'I am your captain, follow me.' His promises calmed the situation."},
    {q:"What happened AFTER the Peasants' Revolt?",opts:["All of Richard II's promises were kept immediately","Richard II broke his promises, and the leaders of the revolt were hunted down and executed","Peasants were given full voting rights","The feudal system was immediately abolished"],c:1,e:"Once the rebels dispersed, Richard II revoked all his promises. Rebel leaders, including John Ball, were captured and executed. In the short term, the revolt failed. However, in the long term, the Poll Tax was never collected again and serfdom gradually disappeared over the following century."},
    {q:"Why is the Peasants' Revolt considered historically significant?",opts:["It immediately ended feudalism","It was the first time ordinary people challenged royal authority on a large scale, showing that the ruling class could not ignore popular anger","It had no lasting impact at all","It led to the Norman Conquest"],c:1,e:"The Peasants' Revolt showed that ordinary people could organise and challenge authority. Although it failed in its immediate demands, it demonstrated that excessive taxation and unfair laws had limits. The Poll Tax was never reimposed, and serfdom gradually faded away over the next century."},
    {q:"The immediate cause (trigger) of the Peasants' Revolt was:",opts:["The Black Death arriving in England","The Norman Conquest","Tax collectors trying to enforce the third Poll Tax in Essex and Kent","A Viking invasion of southern England"],c:2,e:"In May 1381, villagers in Essex attacked a tax collector who was trying to enforce the hated Poll Tax. The rebellion quickly spread to Kent, where Wat Tyler took command. The anger had been building for years, but the tax collection was the spark."}
  ],
  "island-55":[
    {q:"The head of the medieval Christian Church was:",opts:["The King of England","The Archbishop of Canterbury","The Pope in Rome","The local parish priest"],c:2,e:"The Pope in Rome was the supreme head of the Western (Catholic) Christian Church throughout the medieval period. He had authority over all bishops, priests, and monks, and claimed spiritual authority over kings and emperors. This sometimes led to conflicts with secular rulers."},
    {q:"A tithe was:",opts:["A type of medieval weapon","A 10% tax on income or produce paid to the Church","A holy relic kept in a cathedral","A prayer said before meals"],c:1,e:"Every person was expected to give one-tenth (10%) of their annual produce or income to the Church. Tithes made the Church enormously wealthy — it became the largest landowner in England. The tithe barn, where produce was stored, can still be seen in many villages."},
    {q:"Thomas Becket was the Archbishop of Canterbury who was:",opts:["Crowned King of England","Murdered in Canterbury Cathedral in 1170 by knights loyal to Henry II","The first Pope from England","The founder of the Dominican order"],c:1,e:"Thomas Becket quarrelled with his former friend King Henry II over the rights of the Church versus the Crown. In December 1170, four knights murdered Becket in Canterbury Cathedral. He was made a saint in 1173, and Canterbury became England's most important pilgrimage site."},
    {q:"Why did Henry II and Thomas Becket quarrel?",opts:["Becket wanted to be king","Henry wanted the royal courts to have power over Church courts, which Becket opposed","Becket refused to conduct church services","Henry wanted to abolish Christianity"],c:1,e:"Henry II wanted to reform the justice system so that clergy who committed crimes would be tried in royal courts, not lenient Church courts. Becket fiercely defended the independence of the Church. Their dispute became personal and bitter, eventually leading to Becket's murder."},
    {q:"Medieval pilgrimages were journeys to:",opts:["Foreign battlefields","Holy sites and shrines, often to pray, seek healing, or gain forgiveness for sins","Market towns for trade","Castles to pledge loyalty to the king"],c:1,e:"Pilgrims travelled to holy places such as Canterbury (Becket's shrine), Jerusalem, Rome, and Santiago de Compostela. They went to pray, seek forgiveness, be healed of illness, or fulfil a religious vow. Chaucer's Canterbury Tales describes a group of pilgrims travelling to Canterbury."},
    {q:"Relics in the medieval Church were:",opts:["Ancient Roman weapons","Objects associated with saints (bones, clothing, belongings) believed to have miraculous powers","Types of stained glass windows","Musical instruments used in worship"],c:1,e:"Relics — bones, fragments of clothing, or possessions of saints — were housed in churches and cathedrals and attracted pilgrims. People believed relics could perform miracles, especially healing the sick. Some relics were undoubtedly fake, but they brought wealth to the churches that held them."},
    {q:"Monasteries were important in medieval life because they:",opts:["Were only places of silent prayer","Served as centres of education, healthcare, hospitality for travellers, and farming innovation","Were military training camps","Were only used by the king and his court"],c:1,e:"Monasteries served multiple functions: they educated children, copied books by hand (preserving knowledge), cared for the sick, provided hospitality for travellers, developed farming techniques, and produced goods like wool, ale, and honey. They were vital to medieval communities."},
    {q:"Excommunication was a punishment where the Church:",opts:["Increased someone's tithes","Banned a person from the Church and its sacraments, effectively cutting them off from salvation","Promoted someone to bishop","Gave someone extra land"],c:1,e:"Excommunication was the most severe punishment the Church could impose. The excommunicated person was banned from all church services, sacraments (baptism, marriage, communion), and — in medieval belief — condemned to hell. Even kings feared this punishment. Pope Innocent III excommunicated King John in 1209."},
    {q:"The hierarchy of the medieval Church, from top to bottom, was:",opts:["Priest → Bishop → Archbishop → Pope","Pope → Archbishops → Bishops → Priests","King → Pope → Monks → Priests","Monks → Priests → Bishops → Pope"],c:1,e:"The Church had a strict hierarchy: the Pope at the top, then archbishops (like Canterbury and York), bishops (who oversaw dioceses), and parish priests (who served local churches). Monks and nuns lived in monasteries and convents under their own rules but answered to the Pope."},
    {q:"The parish church was central to medieval village life because:",opts:["It was only used for Sunday services","It served as the centre of community life — for worship, celebrations, education, dispute resolution and news","It was where the lord of the manor lived","It was only open to wealthy people"],c:1,e:"The parish church was the heart of every village. Everyone attended services on Sundays and holy days. The church was used for baptisms, marriages, and burials. It was where news was shared, festivals were celebrated, and disputes were sometimes settled. For most people, the church was the only stone building they ever entered."}
  ],
  "island-56":[
    {q:"The Wars of the Roses (1455-1487) were fought between which two families?",opts:["The Tudors and the Stuarts","The House of Lancaster (red rose) and the House of York (white rose)","The Normans and the Saxons","The Plantagenets and the Capetians"],c:1,e:"The Wars of the Roses were a series of civil wars between two branches of the royal Plantagenet family: Lancaster (red rose) and York (white rose). Both sides claimed the right to the throne. The wars ended when Henry Tudor (Lancaster) defeated Richard III (York) at Bosworth in 1485."},
    {q:"The Battle of Towton (1461) is considered significant because it was:",opts:["The first battle of the wars","The bloodiest battle ever fought on English soil, with possibly 28,000 dead","A small skirmish with no casualties","The final battle of the wars"],c:1,e:"Fought in a snowstorm on Palm Sunday 1461 in Yorkshire, Towton was the largest and bloodiest battle of the Wars of the Roses — and likely the deadliest ever on English soil. The Yorkist victory put Edward IV on the throne and drove Henry VI into exile."},
    {q:"Richard Neville, the Earl of Warwick, was known as 'Warwick the Kingmaker' because he:",opts:["Built the most castles in England","Was so powerful that he could make and unmake kings through his political and military influence","Was the king himself","Only fought in one battle"],c:1,e:"Warwick was the richest and most powerful nobleman in England. He first helped Edward IV seize the throne (1461), then switched sides and briefly restored Henry VI (1470). His ability to determine who sat on the throne earned him the nickname 'Kingmaker'. He was killed at the Battle of Barnet in 1471."},
    {q:"What happened to the Princes in the Tower?",opts:["They grew up and became kings","Edward V and his brother Richard were imprisoned in the Tower of London and disappeared — probably murdered on the orders of Richard III","They escaped to France and lived long lives","They were released by Henry VII"],c:1,e:"In 1483, the 12-year-old Edward V and his 9-year-old brother were placed in the Tower of London by their uncle Richard, Duke of Gloucester. They were never seen again. Richard took the throne as Richard III. Most historians believe they were murdered, though the exact circumstances remain debated."},
    {q:"Henry VII won the throne at which battle?",opts:["Battle of Hastings","Battle of Towton","Battle of Bosworth Field (1485)","Battle of Crécy"],c:2,e:"Henry Tudor defeated Richard III at the Battle of Bosworth Field on 22 August 1485. Richard was killed in the fighting — the last English king to die in battle. Henry was crowned on the battlefield and became Henry VII, founding the Tudor dynasty."},
    {q:"How did Henry VII unite the warring families of Lancaster and York?",opts:["He executed all members of both families","He married Elizabeth of York, combining both claims to the throne","He abolished the monarchy","He declared both roses illegal"],c:1,e:"Henry VII (Lancaster) married Elizabeth of York in January 1486, symbolically uniting the two rival families. He created the Tudor rose — combining the red rose of Lancaster with the white rose of York — as a symbol of this union and national peace."},
    {q:"Henry VI was a weak king who contributed to the Wars of the Roses because:",opts:["He was a strong military leader who won every battle","He suffered from periods of mental illness, was easily influenced, and could not control his powerful nobles","He voluntarily gave up the throne","He invaded France successfully"],c:1,e:"Henry VI was pious but politically weak. He suffered mental breakdowns, lost England's French territories, and could not manage the rivalries among powerful nobles. His weakness created a power vacuum that ambitious nobles — especially Richard, Duke of York — exploited, leading to civil war."},
    {q:"Edward IV was the first Yorkist king. He came to power in:",opts:["1399","1455","1461","1485"],c:2,e:"Edward IV seized the throne in 1461 after the Yorkist victory at Towton. He was tall, charismatic, and a skilled military leader. He reigned until 1470 (when Henry VI was briefly restored), regained the throne in 1471, and ruled until his death in 1483."},
    {q:"Richard III is often portrayed as a villain. One reason for this is:",opts:["He was a great reformer who was loved by everyone","He is widely believed to have ordered the murder of his young nephews (the Princes in the Tower)","He had a very long and peaceful reign","He defeated the Spanish Armada"],c:1,e:"Richard III's reputation as a villain comes largely from the disappearance of the Princes in the Tower and Shakespeare's portrayal of him as a scheming, ruthless tyrant. Some historians argue this is unfair Tudor propaganda, but the fate of the princes remains his most controversial legacy."},
    {q:"Why was Henry VII's reign important for England?",opts:["He continued the civil wars","He restored stability, strengthened royal finances, and established the Tudor dynasty that ruled for over a century","He abolished Parliament","He lost all of England's territory"],c:1,e:"Henry VII ended decades of civil war, secured the throne through marriage and diplomacy, rebuilt royal finances (leaving a full treasury), and avoided expensive wars. His careful, pragmatic rule established the Tudor dynasty and gave England the stability needed for future prosperity."}
  ],
  "island-57":[
    {q:"Edward I conquered Wales between:",opts:["1066-1087","1215-1225","1277-1283","1455-1487"],c:2,e:"Edward I launched two campaigns to conquer Wales — the first in 1277 and the second in 1282-83. The second campaign followed a Welsh revolt led by Llywelyn ap Gruffudd. By 1283, Wales was under full English control, and Llywelyn was dead."},
    {q:"Llywelyn ap Gruffudd was:",opts:["An English baron who supported Edward I","The last native Prince of Wales, who resisted English conquest","A Viking leader who invaded Wales","The first Tudor king"],c:1,e:"Llywelyn ap Gruffudd was the last independent Prince of Wales. He initially accepted English overlordship but later rebelled. He was killed in 1282 near Builth Wells, and his brother Dafydd was captured and executed in 1283. Welsh independence ended with their deaths."},
    {q:"Edward I built castles in Wales primarily to:",opts:["Provide homes for Welsh nobles","Control the conquered Welsh population and prevent future rebellions","Encourage tourism","Store grain for English farmers"],c:1,e:"Edward I built a ring of massive stone castles across North Wales — including Caernarfon, Conwy, Harlech, and Beaumaris. These were designed to dominate the landscape, house English garrisons, and make rebellion impossible. They are among the finest medieval castles ever built."},
    {q:"Caernarfon Castle was designed to be particularly impressive because:",opts:["It was the smallest castle in Wales","Edward I intended it as the seat of English power in Wales and a symbol of conquest","It was built by Welsh craftsmen as a gift to Edward","It was purely decorative"],c:1,e:"Caernarfon was Edward I's masterpiece — its polygonal towers and banded stonework were deliberately modelled on the walls of Constantinople to project imperial authority. Edward's son (the future Edward II) was born there in 1284, and Edward named him Prince of Wales — a title held by heirs to the throne ever since."},
    {q:"William Wallace was a Scottish leader who:",opts:["Peacefully negotiated with Edward I","Led Scottish resistance against English rule and won the Battle of Stirling Bridge in 1297","Was King of Scotland","Surrendered without fighting"],c:1,e:"William Wallace was a Scottish knight who led a major uprising against English occupation. His greatest victory was at Stirling Bridge (1297), where he used the narrow bridge to defeat a much larger English army. He was later captured in 1305 and executed in London."},
    {q:"The Battle of Stirling Bridge (1297) was significant because:",opts:["It was an English victory","Wallace's smaller Scottish force defeated a larger English army by using the narrow bridge as a tactical advantage","Scotland surrendered permanently","Edward I was killed in the battle"],c:1,e:"At Stirling Bridge, Wallace and Andrew Moray exploited the narrow bridge — only a few English soldiers could cross at a time, allowing the Scots to overwhelm them in sections. It was a stunning victory that briefly freed Scotland from English control and made Wallace a national hero."},
    {q:"Robert the Bruce became King of Scotland in 1306 and is famous for:",opts:["Surrendering Scotland to England","Defeating Edward II's English army at the Battle of Bannockburn in 1314, securing Scottish independence","Building castles for the English","Becoming King of England"],c:1,e:"Robert the Bruce fought a long guerrilla war against the English before winning the decisive Battle of Bannockburn in 1314, where he routed a much larger English army led by Edward II. This victory effectively secured Scottish independence, formally recognised by England in the Treaty of Edinburgh-Northampton (1328)."},
    {q:"The Battle of Bannockburn (1314) was fought near:",opts:["London","Edinburgh","Stirling","Cardiff"],c:2,e:"Bannockburn was fought near Stirling Castle in central Scotland on 23-24 June 1314. Bruce's army of around 7,000 defeated Edward II's force of up to 20,000. It was one of Scotland's greatest military victories and is celebrated as a defining moment in Scottish history."},
    {q:"Why did Edward I want to control both Wales and Scotland?",opts:["He wanted to unify the whole island of Britain under English rule and expand his kingdom","He was trying to escape from London","He needed to find new farmland","The Pope ordered him to"],c:0,e:"Edward I believed the English king should rule the entire island of Britain. He saw Wales and Scotland as territories that should submit to English authority. His campaigns in Wales were successful; his attempts to conquer Scotland ultimately failed after his death in 1307."},
    {q:"The castle at Harlech in Wales is famous for:",opts:["Being destroyed immediately after construction","Its dramatic clifftop location and being considered virtually impregnable","Being the smallest castle Edward I built","Being built by the Welsh themselves"],c:1,e:"Harlech Castle sits on a rocky outcrop overlooking the sea in North Wales. Its concentric design and dramatic position made it almost impossible to capture. It was besieged several times throughout history and is now a UNESCO World Heritage Site, along with Caernarfon, Conwy, and Beaumaris."}
  ],
  "island-58":[
    {q:"Medieval towns grew in importance because they became centres of:",opts:["Farming only","Trade, craft production and commerce","Military training only","Religious worship only"],c:1,e:"As the medieval economy developed, towns became centres of trade and manufacturing. Markets attracted buyers and sellers, craftsmen produced goods, and merchants traded both locally and internationally. Towns offered more freedom than the countryside — 'town air makes you free' was a common saying."},
    {q:"A town charter was a document that:",opts:["Banned all trade in the town","Granted a town certain rights and freedoms, often including the right to hold markets and self-govern","Ordered the destruction of the town","Was only given to villages"],c:1,e:"A royal charter granted towns privileges such as the right to hold a weekly market, an annual fair, elect their own officials, and collect their own taxes. Charters freed townspeople from some feudal obligations and encouraged economic growth."},
    {q:"Medieval guilds were organisations that:",opts:["Controlled and regulated specific trades or crafts, setting quality standards, prices and training","Were secret military groups","Only existed in London","Had no rules or regulations"],c:1,e:"Guilds controlled individual trades — for example, the Weavers' Guild or the Goldsmiths' Guild. They set quality standards for products, regulated prices, controlled who could practise the trade, and provided welfare for members' families. Guilds were powerful economic and social organisations."},
    {q:"An apprenticeship in the medieval period typically lasted:",opts:["One month","About 7 years","One year","A lifetime"],c:1,e:"A young person (usually a boy, from around age 12-14) would be apprenticed to a master craftsman for about 7 years. The apprentice lived with the master, learned the trade, and received food and lodging but no wages. After completing the apprenticeship, they became a journeyman and could eventually become a master."},
    {q:"England's most important export in the medieval period was:",opts:["Iron and steel","Wool and later woollen cloth","Gold and silver","Spices"],c:1,e:"Wool was medieval England's most valuable export — so important that the Lord Chancellor still sits on a woolsack in the House of Lords today. English wool was prized across Europe, especially in Flanders (modern Belgium/Netherlands) where it was woven into fine cloth. Later, England began exporting finished cloth, which was even more profitable."},
    {q:"Medieval fairs were different from weekly markets because they:",opts:["Were held every day","Were larger annual events lasting several days, attracting merchants from across Europe","Were only for selling animals","Were held in castles"],c:1,e:"Fairs were major annual trading events — much larger than weekly markets. They lasted several days and attracted international merchants selling luxury goods, spices, cloth, and exotic items. Famous English fairs included Stourbridge Fair near Cambridge, one of the largest in Europe."},
    {q:"What was a major problem with sanitation in medieval towns?",opts:["Towns were extremely clean and well-planned","There was no proper sewage system — waste was thrown into streets and rivers, causing disease","Towns had modern plumbing","All waste was recycled"],c:1,e:"Medieval towns were dirty, smelly, and unhealthy. Human and animal waste was dumped in the streets or into rivers. There was no sewage system, clean water supply, or understanding of germs. Diseases like dysentery and cholera were common, and the cramped conditions helped the Black Death spread rapidly."},
    {q:"A 'market town' was:",opts:["A town that banned all trade","A town that had been granted the right to hold a regular market, making it a local trading centre","A town with only one shop","A town that only sold food"],c:1,e:"Market towns were granted a charter allowing them to hold a regular market (usually weekly). They became local centres of trade where farmers sold produce and craftsmen sold goods. Many English towns that are still called 'market towns' today — like Market Harborough — trace their origins to these medieval charters."},
    {q:"Why did medieval towns attract people from the countryside?",opts:["Towns had better farmland","Towns offered freedom from feudal obligations, economic opportunities, and the chance to learn a trade","Towns had no rules or laws","Lords forced all peasants to move to towns"],c:1,e:"Towns offered a chance to escape the restrictions of feudalism — a serf who lived in a town for a year and a day was legally free. Towns also provided economic opportunities through trade and crafts, as well as more social freedom. This is why towns grew steadily throughout the medieval period."},
    {q:"The typical layout of a medieval town included:",opts:["Wide boulevards and parks","Narrow, winding streets, a central market square, a church, town walls and gates","Underground tunnels for transport","Grid-pattern streets like a modern city"],c:1,e:"Medieval towns were compact and crowded. Narrow streets wound between timber-framed buildings that jutted out over the street (jettying). The market square was the economic heart, the church the social and spiritual centre, and town walls with gates provided defence and controlled who entered."}
  ],
  "island-59":[
    {q:"The Islamic Golden Age is generally dated to approximately:",opts:["500-600 AD","750-1258 AD","1400-1600 AD","1800-1900 AD"],c:1,e:"The Islamic Golden Age lasted roughly from 750 AD (establishment of the Abbasid Caliphate) to 1258 AD (when the Mongols sacked Baghdad). During this period, Islamic civilisation led the world in science, mathematics, medicine, philosophy, and the arts."},
    {q:"Baghdad was important during the Islamic Golden Age because it was:",opts:["A small fishing village","The capital of the Abbasid Caliphate and a major centre of learning, trade and culture","A European trading port","The birthplace of Christianity"],c:1,e:"Baghdad, founded in 762 AD, became the world's largest and most prosperous city. It was the capital of the Abbasid Caliphate and attracted scholars, scientists, and traders from across the known world. Its position on trade routes between East and West made it a hub of commerce and knowledge."},
    {q:"The House of Wisdom (Bayt al-Hikma) in Baghdad was:",opts:["A royal palace for the caliph's family","A major library and centre of translation and scholarship where ancient texts were preserved and studied","A military fortress","A mosque for public worship only"],c:1,e:"The House of Wisdom was a centre of intellectual activity where scholars translated Greek, Persian, Indian, and Chinese texts into Arabic, preserving knowledge that might otherwise have been lost. Scholars also conducted original research in mathematics, astronomy, medicine, and philosophy."},
    {q:"Al-Khwarizmi is known as the 'father of algebra' because he:",opts:["Invented the printing press","Wrote a pioneering book on solving equations that gave algebra its name","Discovered gravity","Built the first telescope"],c:1,e:"Al-Khwarizmi (c. 780-850 AD) wrote a groundbreaking mathematical text whose title contained the Arabic word 'al-jabr' — from which we get the word 'algebra'. He also helped popularise the Hindu-Arabic numeral system (0-9) in the Islamic world, which later spread to Europe."},
    {q:"Ibn Sina (Avicenna) made major contributions to:",opts:["Architecture and castle-building","Medicine — his Canon of Medicine was used as a textbook in European universities for centuries","Military strategy","Ship-building"],c:1,e:"Ibn Sina (980-1037 AD) wrote the Canon of Medicine, a vast medical encyclopaedia that systematised Greek, Roman, and Islamic medical knowledge. It was translated into Latin and used as a standard medical textbook in European universities for over 500 years."},
    {q:"Arabic (Hindu-Arabic) numerals (0, 1, 2, 3...) replaced Roman numerals in Europe because they:",opts:["Looked more attractive","Were far easier to use for calculations, especially with the introduction of zero","Were forced on Europe by military conquest","Were identical to Roman numerals"],c:1,e:"The Hindu-Arabic numeral system, transmitted to Europe via Islamic scholars, included the revolutionary concept of zero and a place-value system. This made arithmetic, algebra, and complex calculations far simpler than with Roman numerals (try multiplying XLVII by XXIII!). It transformed European mathematics, science, and commerce."},
    {q:"Islamic scholars made significant advances in optics (the study of light). Who is considered a pioneer in this field?",opts:["Aristotle","Ibn al-Haytham (Alhazen)","Galileo","Isaac Newton"],c:1,e:"Ibn al-Haytham (965-1040 AD) is often called the 'father of optics'. He correctly explained that vision works by light entering the eye (not by rays leaving it, as the Greeks believed). His Book of Optics influenced later European scientists including Roger Bacon and Johannes Kepler."},
    {q:"How did Islamic astronomy advance human knowledge?",opts:["Islamic astronomers only copied Greek ideas without improvement","They refined Greek astronomical models, built observatories, created accurate star catalogues, and developed instruments like the astrolabe","They had no interest in the stars","They believed the Earth was flat"],c:1,e:"Islamic astronomers built sophisticated observatories, created detailed star charts (many star names we use today are Arabic, e.g. Aldebaran, Betelgeuse), refined calculations of the Earth's circumference, and developed the astrolabe for navigation and timekeeping. Their work was essential to later European advances."},
    {q:"Compared to medieval Europe, the Islamic world during the Golden Age was:",opts:["Less advanced in every way","Generally more advanced in science, medicine, mathematics, and learning","Exactly the same","Focused only on religion with no interest in science"],c:1,e:"While much of medieval Europe had limited literacy, poor medicine, and little scientific progress, the Islamic world was experiencing a flourishing of knowledge. Islamic scholars preserved and extended Greek and Roman learning, made original discoveries, and created the foundations for many fields that later helped spark the European Renaissance."},
    {q:"The Islamic Golden Age ended largely because of:",opts:["A natural disaster","The Mongol invasion and destruction of Baghdad in 1258","A voluntary decision to stop learning","The discovery of America"],c:1,e:"In 1258, the Mongol army led by Hulagu Khan sacked Baghdad, destroying the House of Wisdom and killing the caliph. Libraries were burned and countless manuscripts were lost. While Islamic scholarship continued in other regions (Egypt, Spain, Persia), the destruction of Baghdad marked the symbolic end of the Golden Age."}
  ]
});
